http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-3&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/bush-nominates-zoellick-run-world/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257B02133F90-0D8B-42FC-B139-F82DC10726D6%257D%26dist%3Dhplatest&cid=1116788973&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Bush nominates Zoellick to run World Bank - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs Bush nominates Zoellick to run World Bank Last Update: 12:45 PM ET May 30, 2007 WASHINGTON (MarketWatch) -- President Bush nominated Robert Zoellick, a Washington insider with broad experience in global economics, to succeed Paul Wolfowitz at the head of the poverty-fighting World Bank. Zoellick "is deeply devoted to the mission of the World Bank," Bush said in a brief announcement Wednesday. "He wants to help struggling nations defeat poverty, to grow their economies and offer their people the hope of a better life." If approved by the World Bank board as expected, Zoellick would take over a mammoth institution grappling to redefine itself in the wake of the ethics scandal that led to Wolfowitz's resignation after a bitter battle that lasted months. The board said in a statement late Tuesday that it would accept nominations from any board member, not just the United States, and hoped to make a final decision by June 30, when Wolfowitz officially steps down. The United States controls about 16% of the board's voting power. By tradition, the U.S. president names the president of the bank, while the Europeans have controlled the leadership of its sister institution, the International Monetary Fund. However, the appointment in 2005 of Wolfowitz, one of the architects of the U.S. war in Iraq, led many in the developing world and in Europe to question whether the tradition ought to be abandoned. "We need to put yesterday's discord behind us and to focus on the future together," Zoellick said in his remarks at the White House. Zoellick promised to listen carefully to the bank's staff, donors and borrowers. By all accounts, Zoellick, 53, is well regarded in the tight world of global finance, winning the backing of key European finance ministers. He served as U.S. trade representative in Bush's first term, helping to launch the World Trade Organization's latest round of trade talks. He then moved to the State Department, serving as Condoleezza Rice's top deputy. He's been a managing director at Goldman Sachs for the past year. Praise for Zoellick flowed in from official Washington. "Bob has the skills and the integrity to put the bank back on the right path," said Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee. "The institution's membership should expect a leader dedicated to reducing poverty and intolerant of corruption and kleptocracy," said Rep. Roy Blunt, R-Mo., the minority whip in the House. "The president should have been selected on merit, not nationality," said Elizabeth Stuart, a senior policy adviser for Oxfam International, in a statement. However, Zoellick could prove himself the right person for the job if he turns the bank's priorities upside down to focus on helping the poor, rather than on pleasing donors or bureaucrats. "We are disappointed," said Sameer Dossani, director of the 50 Years is Enough Network. "He's another white, male, neoconservative." Dossani said Zoellick had carried the water for U.S. corporations, especially the pharmaceutical industry, in trade negotiations. "He doesn't have any development experience, and he doesn't have the respect of many people." Rex Nutting is Washington bureau chief of MarketWatch. Related Blog Posts & Articles U.S. stocks rise amid deal news Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion U.S. mortgage rates edge higher for third straight week U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Dell seen posting 22% drop in profit as it fights H-P threat Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion Jobs wants to use iPhone to put the 'baby Internet' to bed U.S. futures up after Wachovia deal, Yahoo upgrade Want to beat the market? Take