 Another bill awaiting House action calls for mandatory random steroid tests for every high school athlete in the state. A rush of legislation is expected today as the Texas House and Senate hurry to get as much done as possible before the Legislature adjourns at midnight (Central time). Thirty-two bills are left on the schedule. Democratic state Representative Joaquin Castro and others who participated in the walkout say they could vote to suspend the rules to take up the legislation when they meet this afternoon. The only bills lawmakers are required to pass before the end of the session is the state budget. The Associated Press Contributed to this report. All content &copy; Copyright 2002 - 2007 WorldNow and KVIA. All Rights Reserved. For more information on this site, please read our
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-5&fd=R&url=http://www.silive.com/news/advance/index.ssf%3F/base/news/118061283048400.xml%26coll%3D1&cid=1116778683&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Racial uproar over naming a city street for radical - SILive.com More From Staten Island Advance Subscribe To Staten Island Advance Racial uproar over naming a city street for radical The City Council rejects tribute to Sonny Carson after a raucous debate Thursday, CITY HALL BUREAU Racial tensions reached a fever pitch in the City Council yesterday, during a loud, antagonistic debate over renaming a Brooklyn street after Sonny Abubadika Carson, a black activist regarded both as a key civil rights leader and an anti-white, anti-Semitic provocateur. As Council members took turns speaking on the issue, crowds booed, hissed and cheered, and the meeting was called to order several times. Adding to the drama, Council Speaker Christine Quinn, who is white, was chastised by Councilman Charles Barron, a Brooklyn Democrat and a former Black Panther, for her opposition to the measure. The Council voted down the measure 25-15, with seven abstentions. Staten Island's three-member contingent rejected the Carson street renaming. The tally broke down largely along racial lines, with only one vote to rename the street coming from a white member and all black members either voting for the renaming or abstaining. "This fairly innocuous bill, a street renaming ... sounds so innocuous, so routine, and yet now it's not that," said Councilman Albert Vann, a black Democrat from Bedford-Stuyvesant who spearheaded the measure. "You've hit a nerve. You're harking back to a time that we've already overcome. You're infringing upon our human right." Ms. Quinn, a Democrat, called Carson "divisive" in explaining her "no" vote. "If you look at the life and the full record of who Sonny Carson was, it was divisive. It is a record that is without apology. It is not a record which stood in full support and full solidarity for all New Yorkers of all races and religions," Ms. Quinn said, while the crowd fired jeers of "You didn't know him!" Carson, a Korean War veteran who died in 2002, led protests against police brutality, among other things. He was criticized for calling himself "anti-white," a quote Barron said was taken out of context by the media. Carson was arrested in 1974 on charges of murder, attempted murder and kidnapping -- prosecutors claimed he had ordered the revenge shootings of two men -- and convicted of kidnapping. Sentenced to seven years in prison, he served 15 months and became politically active following his release. Ms. Quinn, who is openly gay and is regarded as having liberal views, was on the end of a harangue by Barron and other black Council members. "You brought us to a place of divide that this City Council has never experienced," Barron said, often pointing a finger at her during his speech and refusing to stop when his two-minute time allotment ended. Car vandals on a rampage Racial uproar over naming a city street for radical MOVIE VET'S OPENING BOW AT FILM FEST Copyright 2007 The Staten Island Advance. Used with permission. Talk News In Our Forums Search for Colleges and Schools Cool Contests and Giveaways The Best Local Classifieds Have The Advance delivered to your home or business. Save 26% off the newsstand price with EZPay. Use of this site constitutes acceptance of our &copy;2007 Staten Island Live LLC. All Rights Reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-4&fd=R&url=http://www.azstarnet.com/allheadlines/185425&cid=1116552892&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ 59 spellers dodge the deadly ding; 'sardoodledom'? That's a laugh | www.azstarnet.com Â® Make us your home page Thu, now, it's free! Buy Daily Star photo reprints Kennyi Aouad, 11, sees the funny side of things as he tries to spell "sardoodledom" â and succeeds. Jacquelyn Martin / the associated press Arizona's Jonathan Horton, 14, of Gilbert, who finished in a tie for sixth last year, advanced to the semifinals. Bert's Electric & Plumbing High School Dance Teacher 59 spellers dodge the deadly ding; 'sardoodledom'? That's a laugh Scripps Howard News Service Tucson, Arizona | Published: 05.31.2007 WASHINGTON â Humor and the horror of the fatal ding punctuated the Scripps National Spelling Bee's first day of competition here Wednesday. When the words settled, 59 out of 286 spellers were left standing. The battle continues this morning, with the semifinals on ESPN from 7 to 10 a.m. Tucson time. ABC will broadcast the finals at 7 p.m. in Tucson. This year marks the first time for metal detectors at the bee's site in a downtown Washington, D.C., hotel. Guards inspected all bags and stood ready to more closely examine anyone or anything setting off the detectors. Bee director Paige Kimble said the measures are "proactive, not reactive." Officials felt it was time to match security to the event's rising profile. The Wednesday afternoon quarterfinals brought a new enemy: the ding of a bell, the kind that could be sitting on any hotel counter. If the contestant got a word wrong, it was o-v-e-r, signaled by a ding. After that sound, a bee crew member shook the defeated speller's hand and led him off the stage. His next stop was the "comfort room," also known as the crying room, where the speller could come to terms with his loss in private. Expected to end by 5:30 p.m., the quarterfinals kept going until 6:20. Kimble said creating a bee schedule is a "guessing game." By the last 90 minutes, empty chairs had gone from a rarity to a trend onstage as the ever-more-difficult words decimated the ranks of the spellers. The contestants fidgeted in their chairs and played with their placards before falling into a line three deep behind the microphone. Shelley Clark's pigtails looked as if they were sagging while she struggled with "acuminate." The 13-year-old home-schooled student from Tigard, Ore., got the definition from the judge: "Tapering to a slender point. Pointed." "Is that from the Latin 'ad,' meaning towards?" she asked, dismissing any notion her brain was as tired as her pigtails. After acing the word, she was suddenly bursting with energy as she bounced back to her chair. Luck is a big factor in winning, and Lady Luck wasn't exactly smiling on Kennyi Aouad. That didn't stop him from grinning and outright cracking up. The 11-year-old sixth-grader at Otter Creek Middle School in Indiana was waiting at the microphone when the judge calmly lobbed "Sardoodledom" at him. A grin as bright as his red shirt immediately broke out on his face, and he started guffawing. The audience cracked up, too. "Sardoodledom?" Kennyi said, still chuckling. "Sardoodledom," the judge confirmed. "Sardoodle â ," Kennyi's giggles interrupted his efforts to repeat the word. He recovered and asked for the definition. "It's another word for melodrama," the judge said, in part. Kennyi's face turned solemn, and he asked for the language of origin. "It's from a French name," the judge said. The speller's lips moved silently. "Umm. Umm," he said. "Is it like kingdom?" Kennyi asked the judge. Then he took down the word, conquering it one letter at a time while the crowd listened in amazement. The boy dashed back to his seat, his arms raised in celebration. And, indeed, the crowd went wild. 0 Comments on this story $1 Sunday delivery - Subscribe to the Arizona Daily Star Letter to the editor â¢ sign up now U of A basketball coverage
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-2&fd=R&url=http://timesunion.com/AspStories/story.asp%3FstoryID%3D593860%26category%3DFRONTPG%26BCCode%3DHOME%26newsdate%3D5/31/2007&cid=1116714320&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Path to citizenship can be a test of patience, wallet -- Page 1 -- Times Union - Albany NY E-MAIL STORY TO A FRIEND 3 of 26 Local/Capitol stories: Charlene Amanda Knight of Albany recently passed the naturalization test. (Paul Buckowski / Times Union) Identity of crash victim sought State soccer championships in Wilton Women's press group honors Bellevue CEO Model plane collectors take hobby to new heights Path to citizenship can be a test of patience, wallet $275 fee increase, new questions for naturalization exam leading to complaints Click byline for more stories by writer. First published: Thursday, -- While President Bush and Congress clash over federal immigration policy, there's good news and bad news on taking the test to become a U.S. citizen. New questions being finalized this summer appear to be easier, for some, than the old test questions. The citizenship test was last changed in 1986. On the downside, it will cost substantially more to take the test: $675, up from $400. The hike takes effect July 30 as part of substantial across-the-board increases in fees for immigration services ranging from green cards ($195 to $370) to permanent resident status ($325 to $1,010). There's a rising chorus of complaints over the fee hikes. "The fee increases put too much of a burden on the backs of the working poor," said Tom Shea, a staff attorney with the New York Immigration Coalition. While the Bureau of Citizenship and Immigration Services receives about 5 million immigration form applications annually, a political battle continues to rage in Washington over what to do with the country's estimated 11 million illegal immigrants. Meanwhile, after six years of tinkering, new test questions are being finalized on what amounts to the final hurdle before naturalization. About 84 percent passed the old citizenship test on the first try according to a 2004 survey. About 95 percent passed a pilot test with new questions on the first try in a 10-city trial over the past six months. Albany was one of the test cities and the passage rate locally was slightly higher than the national average, according to Shawn Saucier, a bureau spokesman. "I got 10 out of 10 right and thought the new questions were really easy compared to the old test questions I had studied," said Charlene Amanda Knight, who took the test at the bureau's Latham office May 5. The person giving the citizenship test selects 10 questions out of a new pool of 100 that will be put in place next year. Passing the test requires answering six out of 10 questions correctly. A test taker gets two chances to pass the test. After that, the immigrant must reapply and pay the $675 fee again. There is no limit on how many times the test can be taken. In a typical year, the bureau receives about 1 million applications for citizenship and naturalizes about 700,000 people. In the Latham office, about 1,200 people are naturalized each year. Knight, 26, of Albany, works as an administrative assistant in the state Health Department. She held Jamaican citizenship but grew up mostly in the U.S. and was granted American citizenship Friday in a ceremony in Troy. Her parents, who live in Florida, had become citizens years earlier, but Knight's paperwork was lost in the immigration bureaucracy. "I kept putting off taking the test because I worried about studying for it and having to pay the fee," said Knight. "Mostly, I really wanted to be able to vote because I got tired of watching the news on Election Night without voting," Knight said. Warren Roberts, a distinguished professor of history at the University at Albany, found some of the new citizenship test questions unduly difficult. 50% off Times Union home delivery. Subscribe today! Identity of crash victim sought State soccer championships in Wilton Women's press group honors Bellevue CEO Model plane collectors take hobby to new heights $20 for 26 weeks of Thurs. & Sun. All Times Union materials copyright 1996-2007, Capital Newspapers Division of The Hearst Corporation, Albany, N.Y.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-2&fd=R&url=http://www.tcpalm.com/tcp/local_news/article/0,,TCP_16736_5561977,00.html&cid=1116758582&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Subscription Services &#150; Home Delivery Specials! Letters to the Editor As Lake O level falls, so does business Lake O 'waiting for the rain' OKEECHOBEE &#151; Bubba Helton wonders how long he can keep his doors open. Larry Wright would love to take someone fishing. Wendy Woodman figures it's going to be a slow Fourth of July holiday. Lake Okeechobee tied a record low water level Wednesday &#151; 8.97 feet above sea level. But the water level isn't the only thing hitting bottom in this part of Central Florida. Businesses around the northern rim of the nation's second- largest freshwater lake also are seeing record lows. Retail sales, dinners served at area restaurants, motel/campsite bookings and rentals are well off the mark following a slower than average season &#151; January through April. And the summer slowdown might spell the end for some businesses. Helton blames a large portion of his lost business on mismanaged water and mis-modeled weather forecasting. "The Army Corps of Engineers and South Florida Water Management District don't know how to run the business they're in," said Helton, owner of Garrard's Bait and Tackle on 441 in Okeechobee. "For 18 months they dumped water out of the lake, and then we went into a natural drought." The low water levels have prevented anglers from taking fishing trips on Florida's most famed fishing lake. Although the fishing is good for bass and bluegill, almost no one can get out onto the lake since the waters have receded to the point where boat ramps empty onto dry ground. Helton said he knows of three tackle shops around the lake that already have closed their doors because of waning customer traffic, and he might not be that far behind if business doesn't pick up soon. Wright, a captain who has guided anglers to lunker largemouth bass for 26 years, hopes he can continue to make a living despite what he estimates as a 75 percent drop in charters. "In May last year, I worked 26 days," said Wright, 55. "This year, I had 10." He had 21 trips last June, but has only three on the books this year. Wright said few customers are coming from other states to fish because of the low water. "We get quite a few anglers from South Carolina, Georgia and Alabama who come here to fish this time of year," he said. "The moms and dads will get their high school kids fishing trips. They're just not coming. "They may think the lake is just completely dried up." Woodman, general manager of the K.O.A. Campground in Okeechobee, said the Memorial Day weekend wasn't too bad for bookings; however, Fourth of July reservations are off quite a bit. "Our business is impacted a little bit," Woodman said, "but we have guests who come here for activities besides fishing and boating." The way Helton sees it, the entire economy of Okeechobee is tied directly or indirectly to the level of the lake. "This doesn't only affect me," Helton said. "Motels, gas stations, grocery stores, even Wal-Mart has slower sales when the traffic is down." And Helton's unhappiness doesn't end with the water managers. "We've been let down by our county commissioners, congressmen, senators and governor," Helton said. "I don't care if there's a three-legged dog running in the next election, I'm voting against all of them." 3 (bookings to date) 41 bass, 48 bluegill and shellcracker 31 bass to 8 pounds Forecasters with the National Weather Service predict a roughly 40 percent chance of rain on Friday and a 50 percent chance of rain on Saturday. The South Florida Water Management District says even if it does rain, it would have to fall directly over the lake to help it rebound. Bubba Helton wonders how long he can keep his doors open. Larry Wright would love to take someone fishing. Wendy Woodman figures it's going to be a slow Fourth of July holiday. As Lake O level falls, so does business Build an ad with PHOTOS Free ad - Classified items under $500 Advertise and only pay for clicks - $50 free to start Our new real estate search engine has more local listings than anyone else &raquo; The most local job listings to get your new career search in high gear &raquo; Deals on wheels galore. You can search local dealer inventories 24/7 &raquo; Shop through our newspaper ads online&raquo; Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers . Site Users are subject to our Contact TCPalm.com at Feedback@tcpalm.com Other E.W. Scripps Web sites:
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-4&fd=R&url=http://www.abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory%3Fid%3D3226097&cid=1116758582&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ ABC News: Florida's Lake Okeechobee Bone-dry Lake Okeechobee Ties Record Low Level Lake Okeechobee in Fla. Ties Record for Its Lowest Water Level; Lake Bed Burns Amid Drought Deep cracks cover the bottom of what should be five-feet deep Lake Okeechobe near Okeechobee, Fla. Tuesday as the drought continues statewide in Florida. Lake Okeechobee, a backup drinking water source for millions in South Florida and the lifeblood of the Everglades, is nearing a record low at 9.6 feet, four feet below average. &#40;J. Pat Carter/AP Photo&#41; By JENNIFER KAY Associated Press Writer MIAMI May 30, 2007 (AP) Water levels in dried-out Lake Okeechobee matched a historic low Wednesday while firefighters battled a blaze burning on part of the exposed lake bottom. The South Florida Water Management District expected the record of 8.97 feet from May 24, 2001, to evaporate by Thursday as the region's worst known drought continues. The average water level should be around 13 feet this time of year in the second-largest freshwater lake in the contiguous United States. The 12,000-acre fire started Monday in the vegetation left to dry in the sun as waters receded from the lake's northwest rim, said Melissa Yunas, a spokeswoman for the Florida Division of Forestry. "All the water is not there. Now it's just vegetation, all dried out, just sitting on the side of the lake," Yunas said. The cause of the fire was unknown. It was about 50 percent contained, Yunas said. Lake Okeechobee is a backup drinking water source for millions of people in South Florida and the lifeblood of the Everglades. The region is largely dependent on the lake during dry periods, when it can be used as a reservoir. "The Everglades are also in a drought. We've totally lost the backup for the water supply for the east coast" of Florida, said Carol Wehle, executive director of the water management district. An above-average rainy season is needed to replenish the lake and South Florida's groundwater system, officials said. Only about 7-8 inches of rain have fallen on the region in the past five months, about half of normal totals. No significant rainfall was expected over the lake or the Kissimmee River valley to its north before Thursday night, according to the National Weather Service. The drought has forced stringent water restrictions on homes and businesses in 13 counties, and four coastal wells were closed to prevent saltwater contamination. The drought has allowed officials to begin clearing 500,000 cubic yards of rotted plant life and sediment from the southwest portion of the 730-square-mile lake to return its bottom to a more sandy base, improve water quality and restore wildlife habitat. Copyright 2007 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed. Lake Okeechobee Ties Record Low Level Read 3 Comments and Post Your Own WHAT OTHERS ARE SAYING Add to the facts. Tell us what you know. Currently there is no ballot question for this story. Do you have an idea for something to ask? Send it in here! Discuss this topic with the ABC News Community View All Message Boards Citizen Journalists: Click Here To Ask The Newsmakers Questions Check out the video discussion going on now E-mails & News Alerts Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Rights External links are provided for reference purposes. ABC News is not responsible for the content of external internet sites. Copyright &copy; 2007 ABCNews Internet Ventures
