http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-6&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/05/31/africa/ME-GEN-Saudi-Arabia-US-Guantanamo.php&cid=1116827019&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Saudi Arabia identifies apparent suicide victim at Guantanamo Bay prison - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings Saudi Arabia identifies apparent suicide victim at Guantanamo Bay prison Published: Arabia identified the Saudi citizen Thursday who apparently committed suicide recently at the U.S.-run Guantanamo Bay prison camp. Maj. Gen. Mansour al-Turki, spokesman for the Saudi Interior Ministry, identified Abdul Rahman Maadha al-Amry as the man who was found dead in his cell Wednesday at the detention facility. Although the U.S. military has identified the cause of death as "apparent suicide," Al-Turki said that it was too early to judge how al-Amry died. A Saudi human rights society confirmed al-Amry&#039;s identity Thursday and blamed the U.S. for his death. "The U.S. administration is responsible for the recent death of the Saudi national that followed previous similar deaths that took place in the same prison," the Saudi National Society for Human Rights said in a statement. Today in Africa &#038; Middle East Jihadist groups fill a Palestinian power vacuum UN Security Council approves Hariri tribunal Sunni-Kurdish conflict worsens Iraqi disarray The group, which was founded three years ago to defend human rights in the kingdom, called for "an independent and neutral investigation on the circumstances of the death of Abdul Rahman Maadha al-Amry in the Guantanamo detention center." The society also called for "the release of all detainees, who spent five years in the prison without legal evidence and for an immediate closure of the detention camp which has become, because of the continued physical and psychological torture, a mark of shame on the forehead of humanity." "Leaving the detainees in prison for more than five years without trial or release is a flagrant violation of human rights principles," it said. A lawyer for several Saudi detainees in Guantanamo expressed skepticism Thursday about the U.S. military&#039;s claim that al-Amry&#039;s death was a suicide. "At the time, we announce our reservation to the American story and our doubts about its credibility," said Katib al-Shammary in a statement. "We call on the American authorities to quickly unveil the reason behind the death of Abdul Rahman Maadha al-Amry." "We stress on the necessity of carrying out an independent investigation by international and human rights organizations to determine the reasons behind the death of al-Amry and the two other detainees, Mani and al-Zahrani," al-Shammary said. The lawyer was referring to Mani Shaman Turki al-Habardi and Yassar Talal al-Zahrani who apparently committed suicide in the Guantanamo Bay prison in June. He said U.S. authorities have not yet answered questions from a Saudi medical committee about the deaths of the two Saudis. Africa &#038; Middle East French presidency gets a bold new style Man with rare tuberculosis tells his tale Naples&#39;s trash is a challenge politicians are flunking Jihadist groups fill a Palestinian power vacuum Russia worried over UN plans for Kosovo independence Ernst & Young Won&#39;t Face Criminal Charges Thai court orders dissolution of ex-prime minister&#39;s party Gorbachev lends hand to book by Putin critic Turkey masses troops at border with Kurdish Iraq Poison used in China is found in U.S.-made animal feed With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow France&#39;s universities could be first test for Sarkozy Algeria&#39;s quiet revolution: Gains by women How the body (and mind) learns a dance With measure of caution, Europe joins biofuel gold rush Letter From China: China building gigantic cities to offset rural poverty Romania rules at Cannes Film Festival With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Do not neglect culture Jet lag: How to make the best of a bad situation In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy Next venture from Martha Stewart: Groceries The assault on Assyrian Christians U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow The torture of the grave Islam and the afterlife Will oil wealth keep Cambodia afloat, or drown it? IHT.com on the go Listen to IHT articles on your computer, and create custom podcasts for your portable music player. Today's Page One in Europe Today's Page One in Asia Advertise with the IHT Copyright &#169; 2007 the International Herald Tribune All rights reserved
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-0&fd=R&url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/6708609.stm&cid=1116814215&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ BBC NEWS | Americas | US actor will run for president The News in 2 minutes Your news when you want it Also in the news Thursday, 31 May 2007, 15:05 GMT 16:05 UK E-mail this to a friend US actor will run for president Former Tennessee Senator Fred Thompson is a successful actor Fred Thompson, a Hollywood actor and former senator, has said he intends to run for US president in 2008. The 64-year-old, who joins a crowded field of Republican contenders, told newspaper USA Today about his campaign plans, ending months of speculation. He is already well known for his role as a district attorney in TV series Law & Order, and has been polling well. Mr Thompson is expected to launch a "testing the waters" committee in the next few days to start fundraising. The former two-term senator for Tennessee has already been hiring staff, making speeches and setting up a strong internet presence. Reports began circulating on Wednesday that he had decided to make official his informal but already attention-grabbing initiatives towards running for president. "I can't remember exactly the point I said, 'I'm going to do this'," Mr Thompson told USA Today in an interview published on Thursday. "But when I did, that thing that occurred to me: 'I'm going to tell people that I'm thinking about it and see what kind of reaction I get to it'." Mr Thompson has already been attracting attention with speeches He told the paper that his late start to campaigning carried "certain advantages", not least that his use of the internet "has allowed me to be in the hunt, so to speak, without spending a dime". Observers say he could pose a threat to all three of the main contenders for the Republican nomination, Senator John McCain, former New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and former Massachusetts Governor Mitt Romney. Some polls have put him at second or third place among potential Republican voters struggling to decide who to back in a field of almost a dozen candidates. He has strong conservative credentials on issues such as gun control and abortion and, while he voted in 2002 to authorise the Iraq invasion, he is not as closely associated with the war as some of his rivals. His charisma and ability to perform for the crowds are expected to stand him in good stead on the campaign trail. Inevitably, parallels have been drawn between Mr Thompson and another actor-turned-politician, Ronald Reagan. The actor has asked to leave Law & Order, where he has played the astute, fatherly New York District Attorney Arthur Branch for the past five seasons, in order to concentrate on politics. He is also known to viewers for roles in the films The Hunt for Red October, in which he played a US Navy admiral, Last Best Chance and In the Line of Fire. E-mail this to a friend RACE FOR THE 2008 WHITE HOUSE Actor Thompson to run in 2008 Clinton opens song vote Republican hopefuls back war Democrats at one on Iraq Obama fundraising rivals Clinton US states vie for influence by advancing their primaries to 'Super Duper Tuesday' Winning the web war? Republicans' first TV test Hillary impresses in TV debate Guide to the top candidates Why such big war chests? Iraq looms over race How the political system works Quick guide: Presidential elections The BBC is not responsible for the content of external internet sites US urges new greenhouse gas goals US growth weakest in four years Russia blames US in missile row MOST POPULAR STORIES NOW Harry Potter theme park planned German drives down subway stairs US anti-war mother ends protest Most popular now, in detail US actor will run for president Italy inmates seek death penalty US urges new greenhouse gas goals Online and offline worlds merge Washington diary: Seeking a visa Most popular now, in detail Should record number of Everest conquerors be celebrated? What do search engines know about us from our o