pc. Casey Sheehan, also 24 when killed, said she was withdrawing from her leadership role in the anti-war movement. Discouraged by the congressional vote to continue funding the war, Mrs. Sheehan said she was &#8220;going home for a while to try and be normal.&#8221; The harshest reality, wrote Mrs. Sheehan in an online diary, &#8220;was that Casey did, indeed, die for nothing.&#8221; She was wrong about that. The 3,467 military personnel so far killed during the Iraq conflict have died in service to their country, and that alone is a noble cause. And though many, including this newspaper, were critical of the decision to invade Iraq and have questioned the way it has been prosecuted, that does not make the service and sacrifice of our soldiers any less honorable. They were given the task of bringing down a dictator, and they did. They were then commissioned with providing security to a country divided by ancient religious and tribal animosities, so that democracy could take root. They have tried. Lt. Heidtman, we salute you. Leave condolences to the family. For the best site experience, please use a non-beta version of Internet Explorer 6+, set the screen resolution to 1024x768, and enable JavaScript and Cookies. For additional enhancements, install What Do You Think? at 1 (860) 442-2200 | New London, CT | The Day Publishing Co.
