http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-6&fd=R&url=http://keyetv.com/topstories/local_story_150150406.html&cid=1116323345&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ keyetv.com - 18-Month Speaker's Race Begins, With 8 Candidates CBS 42: Austin's Source for Breaking News, Weather, and Sports: 18-Month Speaker's Race Begins, With 8 Candidates May 30, 2007 2:15 pm US/Central 18-Month Speaker's Race Begins, With 8 Candidates Craddick Ally Turner Is Latest To Join The Race CBS 42 Web Producer Cody Garrett Reporting Video: Watch Our Latest News The stage continues to be set for an unprecedented number of candidates attempting to become Texas House Speaker -- after a raucous regular session dominated by a fight over the speaker's chair. The latest addition to the list is Sylvester Turner, D-Houston -- a well-known figure at the capitol and, at least until Wednesday's filing, an ally of Speaker Tom Craddick, R-Midland. Besides Craddick and Turner, three candidates also ran for speaker at the opening of the 80th Regular Session: Rep. Senfronia Thompson, D-Houston, Rep. Brian McCall, R-Plano, and Rep. Jim Pitts, R-Waxahachie. Thompson withdrew her name and endorsed McCall in January -- and then McCall withdrew and endorsed Pitts -- only to see Pitts withdraw his name after a test vote suggested Craddick had the votes to hold onto the chair. Three other Republicans threw their hats in the ring during the end-of-session wrangling over ousting Craddick, including Delwin Jones, R-Lubbock, Fred Hill, R-Dallas, and Jim Keffer, R-Eastland. In total, there are eight candidates for speaker -- an unprecedented number of candidates. Traditionally, candidates for speaker start rounding up 'pledges' from members of the House immediately after the end of the session -- there are 150 representatives -- and many will face bitter primary battles. All must win re-election from their districts. With Turner's entry into the race, the only recognizable truth about the race is that Craddick's support is far from solid, and you can bet that things will change. The next possible speaker's election will occur at the beginning of the next regular or special session. A special session could be called at any time, and the next regular session will begin in January 2009. As a staff member in Rep. Keffer's office said, "It's going to be an interesting 18 or 19 months." (&copy; MMVII, CBS Broadcasting Inc. All Rights Reserved.) Thompson withdrew her name and endorsed McCall in January -- and then McCall withdrew and endorsed Pitts -- only to see Pitts withdraw his name after a test vote suggested Craddick had the votes to hold onto the chair. Speaker Pro Tempore Sylvester Turner, D-Houston, is the latest to enter the crowded race for Texas House Speaker. Session Over; Craddick Remains Speaker Budget Passes Despite Fight Over Craddick TB Patient Arrives In Denver For Treatment Jailed Former UT Professor Facing New Charges Fight Over Northcross Wal-Mart Continues Bush And Putin Plan Maine Summit Bikers Help Bring Vietnam Wall To Pflugerville Parent's Guide to TV Ratings CBS Television Stations Digital Media &copy; MMVII, CBS Stations Group of Texas L.P. All Rights Reserved.
http://www.elpasotimes.com/news/ci_6016444&cid El Paso Times - Immigration services fees rise July 30, so file now Immigration services fees rise July 30, so file now By Louie Gilot / El Paso Times Article Launched: 05/30/2007 12:00:00 AM MDT Immigrants have two more months to file for a variety of services, including naturalization, before paying hundreds of dollars in higher processing fees, Citizenship and Immigration Services officials said Tuesday. The agency on Tuesday announced its new fee schedule and the July 30 deadline. Some of the fees will more than double after the deadline. For instance, filing for permanent residency, or a "green card," will cost $1,010, including biometric fees -- the fees for fingerprinting, photographing and capturing the signatures of applicants -- up from $395. Filing for citizenship will cost $675, up from $400. A complete fee list is available at www.uscis.gov. Immigrant advocates expected a rush of immigrant filing petitions in the next two months to avoid the higher fees. Clara Lugo, a permanent resident and a scheduler for a doctor's office in El Paso, said the new fee structure motivated her to file for naturalization after 25 years in the United States. "I've been procrastinating. My family is always telling me so. Even my dad became a citizen already. I've never felt the urge. But this is it. This is my deadline," she said. Overall, the fee increases are not as high as had been proposed earlier, partly because of a review of more than 3,900 public comments, many of which were critical, agency officials said. "We proposed our new fee structure with the expectation of ongoing discussions with the public on this important issue," said CIS Director Emilio Gonzalez in a written statement. "The volume and value of the comments we received has provided an opportunity to fine-tune our final fee structure that we believe is both fair to our customers and vital to our nation as we continue to build a secure and efficient national immigration service." For instance, filing for permanent residency for a child under 14 filing with his family will cost $360 less than proposed. But it will still be $600 per child, in addition to the $1,010 per parent. "I still worry that a lot of people are not going to be able to afford these fees. A lot of people who are eligible for benefits are simply not going to apply. Right now the number one reason for not applying for benefits is the fees," said Iliana Holguin, executive director of the Diocesan Migrant and Refugee Services of El Paso. CIS officials said the fees are needed to improve service at the agency. Officials said that the new revenue would lead to a 20 percent reduction in average application processing times by the end of fiscal year 2009. Forms are now processed by a paper-based system. Part of the additional revenue from higher fees will be used to process applications electronically. Some will continue to be exempt from paying fees: victims of human trafficking, victims of violence against women, refugees, U.S. citizens filing for their immigrant spouses and members of the U.S. military. The biometric fees rise from $70 to $80, as proposed. Louie Gilot may be reached at lgilot@elpasotimes.com, 546-6131. How costs for some immigration services will increase: I-90 (Replace permanent resident card) I-129F (Petition for alien fiancÃ©) I-485 (Permanent status or adjustment status) N-400 (Application for naturalization) Source: U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services. MORE MORE LOCAL STORIES HEADLINES Delinquent traffic violators have from June 1-9 to pay 11-month-old boy's death ruled accidental strangulation Slayings of JuÃ¡rez officer, agent put police on alert Shooting is officer's 1st; 2 suspects identified Dogs euthanized after attack that killed woman Commissioner asks Thomason board member to leave Police say gang fight led to man's stabbing Family struggles to cope with loss of home to fire Project to improve Lee TreviÃ±o drainage Older