http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.philly.com/philly/wires/ap/news/nation_world/7746552.html&cid=1116617146&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Miss. Murder Cold Case Under Way | AP | 05/30/2007 &#149; 2007 Live Career Fairs &#149; Philly.com Career Fair &#149; Search new & used &#149; Create a free ad , sports venues and more. See a photo you want? Photos of the day Beach and Bay Homes Active Adult 55+ Housing Thursday, on Wed, May. 30, 2007 Miss. Murder Cold Case Under Way Reputed Ku Klux Klansman James Ford Seale, right, is escorted by a Madison County Sheriff's Department deputy to the federal courthouse in Jackson, Miss., Wednesday, May 30, 2007. Seale is charged with kidnapping and conspiracy charges connected to the 1964 slayings of the black teenagers in southwest Mississippi. (AP Photo/Rogelio V. Solis) JACKSON, Miss. - The cold case trial got under way Wednesday in the deaths of two black teenagers who were beaten and dumped still alive into the Mississippi River during the state's dark days of racial brutality. Ku Klux Klansman James Ford Seale faces federal kidnapping and conspiracy charges , along with potentially damaging testimony from a man also charged back in 1964. U.S. District Judge Henry T. Wingate began questioning prospective jurors Wednesday. "We're at the doorstep of justice," said Thomas Moore, the brother of one of the victims, Charles Eddie Moore. For decades, books and news accounts treated the killings of Moore and Henry Hezekiah Dee as footnotes in Mississippi's troubled history. They were 19-year-old friends who were hitchhiking on May 2, 1964, near Meadville when carloads of Ku Klux Klansmen were chasing rumors of a possible armed insurrection by black people in the area. Recent court records said the two were driven to the Homochitto National Forest and beaten, then stuffed into a trunk and driven more than 70 miles to the Mississippi River near Vicksburg. They were weighted down with engine parts and dumped, still breathing, into the Mississippi. Their bodies were found about two months later, when authorities were conducting a massive search for slain civil rights workers Michael Schwerner, James Chaney and Andrew Goodman, who disappeared from central Mississippi's Neshoba County on June 21, 1964. Seale and reputed Klansman Charles Marcus Edwards were arrested in 1964 in the deaths of Dee and Moore. But the FBI was consumed by the "Mississippi Burning" investigation of the three civil rights workers and the Dee-Moore case was turned over to local authorities, who threw out all charges against Seale and Edwards. The Justice Department in 2000 reopened an investigation. Edwards has been granted immunity and is expected to testify for the prosecution. Thomas Moore and two of Dee's sisters , Thelma Collins, 70, of Springfield, La.; and Mary Nell Byrd, 61, of Natchez, Miss. , spoke to The Associated Press on Tuesday in Jackson during an interview arranged by Canadian Broadcasting Corp. documentary maker David Ridgen. Since 2005, Ridgen and Thomas Moore have pushed federal officials to reopen the case. Ridgen's film, "Mississippi Cold Case," is set to air Saturday night on MSNBC. "I try not to think about it so much because, you know, it's done now," Collins said of her brother's death. "But every time I think about it, I shed a tear." Dee and Charles Moore were not troublemakers, their families say. "My thing is, Charles Moore and Henry Dee wasn't bothering anybody," Thomas Moore said Tuesday. "And for them to be butchered, tormented, hassled and drowned in the river , it was pretty bad." Collins and Moore said they're prepared for any outcome in the Seale trial. "I just have it in my heart that they're going to do the right thing," Collins said. Moore has already planned what he'll do after the trial, regardless of the outcome. "The last thing that I'm going to do when I leave Mississippi, I'm going to go to that cemetery, that Mount Olive Cemetery. I'm going to tell Charles Moore, 'I told you that I (would) see it to the end.'" Updated 12:00 PM EDT MOST VIEWED ON PHILLY.COM Time served, deportation for groping on a plane Boy Bags Hog Said Bigger Than 'Hogzilla' At adult recess, workers kick up heels and bond Don&#0039;t have a cow over the calves; he&#0039;s a burner Eagles&#0039; Abiamiri a confident pick Updated 12:00 PM EDT MOST EMAILED ON PHILLY.COM Boy Bags Hog Said Bigger Than 'Hogzilla' Monica Yant Kinney | Haddonfield teens going to extremes N.J., with new agency, steps up fight against fat Stephen A. Smith | Bryant fires back at Lakers At adult recess, workers kick up heels and bond Latest Stories in this Section More Money Sought for Taylor Tribunal TB Patient in Denver for Treatment Lebanese Soldier Killed by Militants Blair: G-8 Must Keep Pledges to Africa Norway Resumes Aid to Palestinians Arkansas Court Ends School-Funding Suit Venezuela Uproar Concerns Carter Center Alabama Gov. Signs Slavery Apology Poll: Coast Not Ready for Hurricanes Putin: U.S. Has Triggered New Arms Race Terms of Use & Privacy Statement
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-0&fd=R&url=http://timesheraldonline.com/ci_6028406&cid=1116770540&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Vallejo Times Herald - The Sheehan saga comes full circle Athlete of the Week Letters to the Editor Bio - Local Profiles The Sheehan saga comes full circle By Times-Herald editorial staff Article Launched: 05/31/2007 07:24:55 AM PDT Any suggestions that Sheehan should simply have kept her concerns and protests quiet are not only misguided, but, well, un-American. An icon to the anti-war left, a lightning rod to many on the conservative right, as well as family members of U.S. troops, Cindy Sheehan has announced her "retirement" from the movement she gave such a public face to. This brings her full circle, back to where this compelling saga first began: Cindy Sheehan, grieving mother. We think that might be just the voice Casey Sheehan's mother is looking for. If that sounds condescending or patronizing to Sheehan, it's not meant to. Any suggestions that the mother of Army Spc. Casey Sheehan, who was 24 when he was killed in an ambush in Baghdad in 2004, should simply have kept her concerns and protests quiet are not only misguided, but, well, un-American. No, Sheehan, formerly of Vacaville, was well within her rights to protest what she saw as the United States making a serious mistake in invading Iraq. And she no doubt takes at least some small comfort from national polls showing most Americans agreeing with the core message of the grass-roots peace movement she helped jump-start. Its infancy came at that makeshift campsite outside President Bush's ranch in Crawford, Texas, where she parked herself for 26 days, demanding the opportunity to discuss her son's death with the president. What she said was her lone, simple question - "Why" - over her son's death ignited a national movement that swelled to thousands of participants. Were it to be kept that simple. Sheehan went from merely being a symbol of the anti-war movement to being its full-time celebrity spokesperson. It was a bumpy road from media darling to activist to shooting duck for pro-military target practice sessions. Was Sheehan smeared, misquoted and unfairly targeted by the right, a victim of what she says were slurs that eventually came from those on the left, as well? Or, with her ill-advised appearances with Hugo Chavez, Venezuela's leftist president, and her reckless rhetoric, filled with increasingly bitter name-calling and careless use of the word "terrorist," did she merely bring it all on herself? The answer likely lies somewhere in the middle. It seemed only fitting that the same traits that marked Sheehan's public persona - sadness and bitterness - were at the heart of her "resignation letter" from the anti-war protest movement, posted in her online diary on the Daily Kos blog. Her frustration at the Democrats' failure - or unwillingness - to get out of Iraq is shared by millions of Americans, but her last posting was all her. "Good-bye America," wrote Sheehan. "You are not the country that I loved ... I finally realized no matter how much I sacrifice, I can't make you be that country unless you want it." With that, the property that Sheehan bought in Crawford for her and fellow protesters - "Camp Casey," she called it - was put up for sale. She's back home in California, where she said she plans to spend more time with her children. The Times-Herald editorial board consists of Publisher Ron Rhea, Editor Ted Vollmer, Managing Editor Jack F.K. Bungart and City Editor Mary Leahy Enbom. She'll do so without her 29-year marriage, which she says she sacrificed to put more energy into stopping the war. And, of course, she'll do so without Casey. Hopefully she'll do it with some peace in her heart. Love her actions or loathe her politics, she's earned that much. Use the comment link provided below to share your thoughts on this story. We ask that readers refrain from profanity, name-calling and derogatory statements. The Times-Herald is not responsible for comments made by readers. We do ask that readers help us police this site by reporting any inappropriate content Nursing & medical scrubs Media News Group partners: - Fort Bragg, CA Lake County Record Bee Red Bluff Daily News - Red Bluff, CA San Mateo County Times - San Mateo, CA - Solano County, CA Inland Valley Daily Bulletin Los Angeles Daily News - Los Angeles, CA - Long Beach, CA - San Bernardino, CA San Gabriel Valley Tribune - San Gabriel, CA TimesHeraldOnline.com is a Copyright Â© 2006 product of The Times-Herald, Vallejo, California, 94590 MNG Corporate Site Map
