http://www.newsday.com/news/local/wire/newjersey/ny-bc-nj--cubanparadedisput0530may30,0,3229832.story%3Fcoll%3Dny-region-apnewjersey&cid Judge rules Cuban Day parade can pass through West New York - Newsday.com New York City News Judge rules Cuban Day parade can pass through West New York May 30, 2007, 5:57 PM EDT JERSEY CITY, N.J. -- A state Superior Court judge on Wednesday ruled that Sunday's Cuban Day Parade can march through West New York, reversing Mayor Silverio Vega's decision to deny a permit to organizers of the annual event. In his ruling, Judge Maurice J. Gallipoli rejected the argument of attorney Daniel Horgan, representing West New York, that parade organizers were running what amounted to "a charitable fraud" that claimed to use the parade to raise money for scholarships and other charities but actually were running a for-profit enterprise. Parade organizers and others had claimed the permit was denied for political reasons, and implied that Vega took the action to avoid having to walk alongside Union City Mayor Brian Stack in the parade. Vega and Stack are opposing one another for a state Senate seat in next Tuesday's primary. "It's been a tremendous ordeal through a mayor who was a little messed up in the head," Emilio Del Valle, the parade's founder, said after the ruling. Vega did not immediately respond to a telephone message seeking comment Wednesday. Attorney Elise DiNardo, representing Del Valle, contended that the denial of the permit amounted to a curtailment of First Amendment rights because it didn't reflect "any governmental purpose or concern" such as crowd control or safety. The parade has passed through West New York since its inception in 2000 and annually draws about 350,000 people. The controversy began two weeks ago when Vega announced he would deny the permit and said he would lie down in front of the marchers to keep them out. The towns of North Bergen and Guttenberg, which the parade also has traditionally passed through, subsequently did not issue permits as they waited for the dispute to be resolved. Attorneys for West New York claimed in court that the Latin American Kiwanis Club, which hosts the parade, was "misusing the Kiwanis name to operate a for-profit, sponsorship operation." The argument didn't sway Gallipoli. "There's a balance to be struck," the judge said. "Let the parade go on and report these people to the appropriate authorities and let them investigate it." Del Valle conceded that the Latin American Kiwanis Club had its charter revoked and would need to pay back dues to have it restored. "They were just doing this now because they have no leg to stand on after what their mayor said," Del Valle said, referring to the charges by Horgan. Subscribe to Newsday home delivery Article licensing and reprint options Post a comment |
