http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-6&fd=R&url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2007/05/31/2007-05-31_sonny_streetname_bid_hits_dead_end.html&cid=1116778683&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Sonny street-name bid hits dead end Sonny street-name bid hits dead end DAILY NEWS CITY HALL BUREAU Thursday, May 31st 2007, 4:00 AM The City Council voted along racial lines yesterday to deny an honorary street-name change for the late Sonny Carson, a black activist who once professed, "I am anti-white." An amendment to add Carson's name to an omnibus street-naming bill was defeated by a vote of 25 to 15, with seven abstentions and four members absent. As votes go in the usually lockstep Council, it was one of the narrowest in many years. And despite the Council's racial diversity, onlyone white Council member - Tony Avella (D-Queens) - voted with the losing pro-Carson side. Similarly, only one nonwhite Council member, Sara Gonzales (D-Brooklyn), sided with thewinning anti-Carson side, led bySpeaker Christine Quinn (D-Manhattan). The seven who abstained all belonged to the Council's 25-member Black, Latino and Asian Caucus. By abstaining, they strengthened Quinn's hand in the showdown vote. Quinn said she would fire any aide who pressured any member on their vote, and she made a no-retaliation vow against members who voted against her position. She argued that honorary street namings are a collective Council decision and should be reserved for individuals who brought the city together. She said Carson had "a record that is without apology a divisive record." She drew an unusual personal attack from Councilman Charles Barron (D-Brooklyn), the most vociferous supporter for naming a section of Gates Ave. in Bedford-Stuyvesant after Carson. Gesturing with his right index finger at Quinn, Barron said, "You have divided us more than Sonny Carson ever divided any people anywhere." He deserves no honor 'Jazz Singer' pulled into Sonny street naming flap Backers rage as Sonny is cut out 