http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-3&fd=R&url=http://www.paloaltodailynews.com/article/2007-5-31-05-31-07-bg-rudy&cid=1116812583&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Palo Alto Daily News Serving Atherton, East Palo Alto, Los Altos, Los Altos Hills, Menlo Park, Mountain View, Portola Valley, Stanford, Sunnyvale, Woodside Local News / Home Page Jobs at the Daily News Do you have a calendar item, brief or newstip? East Bay Daily News Redwood City Daily News San Mateo Daily News Victor Maccharoli / Daily News file Burlingame residents crowded around the Broadway Grill on Wednesday afternoon to shake hands and talk to former New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani. Downtown campaign stop thrills supporters, detractors alike By Will Oremus / Daily News Staff Writer Dan and Laura Escobar and their 6-year-old daughter Ella got to the Broadway Grill in Burlingame at 9:30 a.m. Wednesday to get a good seat for a rare Peninsula public appearance by Republican presidential hopeful Rudy Giuliani. It was well after 11 a.m., the grill was teeming with media types and the Escobars were nursing their last sips of coffee when the popular New Yorker at last swept in with his entourage. With cameras whirring, the candidate briefly sat down with the Escobars, smiled and said he was glad to meet them -- and then he was off to the next table. He was gone too fast for Laura Escobar to snap a picture of the former mayor with Ella, but Escobar said the encounter was still a thrill. "We're definitely fans." Giuliani, who is polling as the leading Republican in the newly important California primary, talked to locals about border security and taxes in his whirlwind visit to Burlingame. But mostly the event was about face time with voters and the local press. Sitting down at a table next to Mike DeMaria and Nicholas Fleres, athletic coaches at Burlingame High School, Giuliani fielded an unscripted question about Barry Bonds' pursuit of Hank Aaron's baseball home run record. The candidate, a famous New York Yankees fan, declined to bash the slugger for his rumored steroid use, saying diplomatically, "Records are meant to be broken." Burlingame residents generally gave Giuliani a warm welcome, cheering his entrance and congregating outside the restaurant's windows and on the Broadway sidewalks to see him. Several identified themselves as die-hard supporters, including some who said they are New York transplants. Mike Murray, a Democrat who was eating at the grill Wednesday, said he doesn't much like Giuliani; he'd prefer Sen. Chris Dodd, D-Conn. But he was drawn to the novelty of having a big-time Republican candidate in liberal San Mateo County. As Giuliani worked the crowd on the right-hand side of the Broadway Grill, Murray heckled, "Hey Mr. Mayor, are you afraid to come over here to the left side of the room?" Burlingame Council Member Ann Keighran, also a registered Democrat, said a public stop from a figure like Giuliani is a good thing for the city regardless of politics: "It puts Broadway on the map." After making the rounds inside, Giuliani stepped onto the sidewalk for a brief press conference in which he struck at leading Democratic candidates Hillary Clinton and Barack Obama for advocating higher taxes. He said his own plan to get rid of the estate tax and cut capital gains taxes would stimulate the Silicon Valley economy. As he headed toward his limousine to scoot over to a private fundraiser at the Burlingame Hyatt, Giuliani stopped to greet a few final residents. The Escobars, now running hours late to take Ella to school, seized the moment and got the candidate to take the 6-year-old blonde into his arms for a photo. "Now at least it'll be easier to explain to the school why she wasn't there," Laura Escobar said. E-mail Will Oremus at woremus@dailynewsgroup.com. Comment on this story Type in your comments to post to the forum (appears on your post) You are currently logged in as (appears on your post) Welcome to Topix Forums! Please fill out the for