g in the front seat, broke a leg, ribs and other bones. NEWS HEADLINES FROM OUR PARTNERS NEW YORK POST is a registered trademark of NYP Holdings, Inc. NYPOST.COM, NYPOSTONLINE.COM, and NEWYORKPOST.COM are trademarks of NYP Holdings, Inc. Copyright 2007 NYP Holdings, Inc. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-1&fd=R&url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,21828422-663,00.html&cid=1116617146&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Jurors shielded from Klan | Herald Sun Welcome to Herald Sun. Send a Letter to the Editor Corporate Photo Sales, Copyright Herald Sun Cartoons & Caricatures Memorabilia & Limited Editions Back Issues & Home Delivery Herald Sun - Sell your car for FREE Place a classified newspaper ad Jurors shielded from Klan June 01, 2007 12:00am JURORS' names in a 40-year-old race murder case will be kept secret at the request of prosecutors who said some might fear Ku Klux Klan retribution. Jury selection began yesterday in the trial of a former Klan member charged over the brutal 1960s murders of two young black civil rights activists in Mississippi. Former policeman James Seale, 71, has been charged with the May 1964 kidnapping of Henry Dee and Charles Moore, both 19. It's alleged Mr Seale and others beat the teens to make them confess to weapons smuggling, then lashed them to an engine and a piece of rail and threw them into the Mississippi. "While the Klan has lost much of its influence in recent years, it is still an active organisation, and it still strikes fear in the hearts of many citizens in Mississippi and elsewhere," prosecutor Paige Fitzgerald said in papers filed in court. One potential juror said one of her cousins was married to one of Mr Seale's cousins. "That makes me nervous, even though I don't know him personally," the woman said, nodding towards Mr Seale. Among 20 others dismissed from the initial jury pool of 76 was a young woman wearing a Confederate battle flag T-shirt. Mr Seale, who has denied Klan membership, faces up to life in jail if he is convicted. The case is the latest of more than a dozen civil rights-era cases prosecuted across the South since the early 1990s. Mr Seale and reputed fellow Klansman Charles Marcus Edwards were arrested in 1964 over the deaths, but the case was thrown out. The case was reopened in 2005 after years of lobbying by the brother of one of the victims. Mr Seale had been believed dead for years until Thomas Moore, 63, tracked him down in southern Mississippi while investigating the murders. Mr Edwards has been granted immunity and is expected to testify for the prosecution. Mr Seale's jail jumpsuit was topped by a bulletproof vest as he left the court. Murdered Russian a 'British spy' Jurors shielded from Klan A fairy tail ending UN court for 'assassins' White tiger no scaredy cat Bad-taste TV for good David Beckham in roo ruckus An 'eksent' spells trouble Desert-jailed Aussie hopes for Monday court date Ex-PM urges calm over ban Passengers in hospital after mid-flight turbulence Trainee nun suspected of strangling newborn Guantanamo inmate found dead after apparent suicide Japan's community whale hunt plan rejected Thaksin and his party banned from Thai politics Search for more stories on this topic on , our news archive service. Custom built PC's - Buy a Dell PC tailored to your needs and only pay for what you want 1st mth best package + install 4 NOTHING*. Love & Relationships - Find a date near you on Match.com - # 1 Online Dating site Worldwide. It won't just be another day at the office. See the full demo. Receive our News Feeds Get your Newspaper Delivered Receive our Email Newsletter Send us your news photos Send us your story tips Place a classified newspaper ad Get your Newspaper Delivered &copy; Herald and Weekly Times. All times AEST (GMT + 10).
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-3&fd=R&url=http://www.centredaily.com/news/nation/story/111534.html&cid=1116552892&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ www.centredaily.com | 05/31/2007 | Spotlight shines on top spellers '[/mi/registration/request/user_run_mode]', regex=>'1', case=>{ '.' => ' | Registration | [/mi/registration/request/user_run_mode]' } --> Letters to the Editor Posted on Thu, May. 31, 2007 Spotlight shines on top spellers National bee begins with record number of contestants By Johanna Neuman - Los Angeles Times WASHINGTON -- The 80th annual Scripps National Spelling Bee began Wednesday with a record field of youngsters spelling words that most adults can't even pronounce. Outside the headquarters hotel, members of the Simplified Spelling Society urged a complete rewrite of the English language, so that the "e" in the word "met" is also used in the words "said" "many" and "jeopardy." Inside, the adrenaline of 286 youngsters who range in age from 10 to 15 filled the hotel with exuberance. "I just want to be on TV," said Zina Ellis, of Moline, Ill. The 13-year-old's mother, Thea, confided that her daughter requested, if she were to win, $1,000 for shoes in different colors to go with every outfit. To get on television, contestants have to make it to the semifinals, which will be carried today on ESPN. To win, they'll have to get to the championship round, carried tonight by ABC. Alas, Ellis was eliminated in the fourth round, on the word "bracteolate" (she spelled it as "brachteolate"). Thanks to recent attention from Hollywood, interest in spelling and spelling bees has spiked, with this year's national contest attracting 10 million contestants. "Children want to be recognized," said Paige Kimball, the event's director and the 1981 champion. "All too often, children who prefer academics to athletics take a back seat." Sala Aouad, of Terre Haute, Ind., said her son Kennyi did not speak until he was 5. By then, he had been reading regularly, memorizing words. In the fourth grade, he entered a local spelling bee -- and lost. "Kennyi never likes to lose," she said. Now 11, he said he's excited at the chance to test himself against the best in the nation. "I like competition," Kennyi Aouad said. "It puts one's skills to the test." Aouad not only advanced to today's competition, but he brought down the house in the third round when confronted with the word "sardoodledom." His first reaction was to burst out laughing. The crowd in the 1,100-seat ballroom burst out laughing too. Every time the judge offered the word, the 11-year-old burst out laughing. With the clock running (contestants get two minutes and 30 seconds to spell the word from the time they hear it), he had to stop the giggles to spell the word. When he did so correctly, the crowd burst into applause. For much of its life, the Bee was a niche event. Then two things happened to change its complexion. In 1985, Balu Natarajan, a 13-year-old son of Indian-American parents, won by correctly spelling "milieu." He became an overnight sensation in his ethnic community, and many first-generation Americans came to see the contest as a passport to acceptance in U.S. culture, encouraging their kids to compete. Then, Hollywood discovered the contest. In 2002 the documentary "Spellbound" won an Oscar nomination, followed by a Broadway musical and last year's film "Akeelah and the Bee," which tracks a Los Angeles girl as she overcomes adversity to compete in the event. The contest also has attracted its share of writers. Myla Goldberg's 2000 novel "Bee Season" was made into a movie starring Richard Gere, and pop culture writer James Maguire wrote a book last year called "American Bee: The National Spelling Bee and the Culture of Word Nerds." But few in the lobby of the Grand Hyatt Hotel carried themselves like nerds. Clustered in groups, mostly with parents, sponsors of coaches, they checked their hair, worried about the competition and traded war stories about previous bees. Kunal Sah, of Green River, Utah, in his second National Spelling Bee, had a special mission. His parents, denied political asylum, have been deported to India while the 13-year-old lives with relatives in a motel and studies words. Hoping to win so he could spotlight his parents' plight, he said his goal was "to get to the top." The first-round written test has 25 questions, each worth one point, and the second-round oral words are worth three points each, for a total of 28 points. Contestants need 18 points to advance to the third round. Sah passed the verbal word -- "hurdle" -- with barely a hiccup. But he missed more than 10 questions on the written exam and will have to wait until next year. About the Real Cities Network About the McClatchy Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm%3Falias%3Dnine-atlantic-hurricanes%26chanId%3Dsa003%26modsrc%3Dreuters&cid=1116729647&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Nine Atlantic hurricanes expected in '07: Scientific American Green Gold in a Shrub Does the length of a baseball player's arm affect the distance of his throw? If so, how? 50, 100 & 150 Nine Atlantic hurricanes expected in '07 Nine Atlantic hurricanes expected in '07 File photo shows Key West resident Gregorio Nodal walks in the flooded North Roosevelt coast boulevard after Hurricane Wilma hits Florida's southern west coast October 24, 2005. A hurricane research team has renewed its forecast for an "above average" 2007 Atlantic storm season. REUTERS/Carlos Barria MIAMI (Reuters) - The Colorado State University hurricane research team renewed its forecast for an "above average" 2007 Atlantic storm season on Thursday and predicted 17 tropical storms, with nine growing to hurricane strength. Of those, five would grow into major hurricanes of Category 3 or higher with winds over 110 mph (177 kph), the team founded by forecast pioneer William Gray said in its revised forecast. The updated forecast issued on Thursday was unchanged from the team's April 3 forecast for the six-month storm season that starts on Friday. ADVERTISEMENT (article continues below) The researchers said there was a 74 percent chance that at least one major hurricane would hit the U.S. coastline in 2007, with a 50 percent chance that would happen on the U.S. Atlantic Coast and a 49 percent chance on the Gulf of Mexico coast. An average season brings 11 tropical storms, with six reaching hurricane wind speed of 74 mph (119 kph) and two growing into major hurricanes. Other private and government weather researchers have also predicted a more active season than average. But so far none have forecast anything like a repeat of record-breaking 2005, when 28 tropical storms spawned 15 hurricanes, including 