http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-5&fd=R&url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/breaking/2007/05/candidates_in_california.html&cid=1116812583&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Newsblog | Candidates in California SignOnSanDiego.com > News > Newsblog The latest local news from the Union-Tribune's newsroom &laquo; S.D. speller advances Small grass fire in SD &raquo; Small grass fire in SD Grand jury slams women's jail Haditha hearing for top Marine National Spelling Bee begins Man in police custody dies Pursuit ends in Logan Heights crash Vista bank robber escapes Gov tells Aguirre 'No' on Sunroad Three presidential candidates are campaigning in California on Wednesday -- none of them in San Diego. If he's on schedule, Republican Rudy Giuliani is greeting voters at the Broadway Grill in Burlingame at this moment. Events such as this are staples of presidential campaigning in Iowa and New Hampshire, but we don't see much retail politicking in California. Democrat John Edwards will be nearby in Mountain View Wednesday afternoon for a town hall meeting with Google employees. And Democrat Hillary Clinton will pick up the endorsement of Los Angeles Mayor Antonio Villaraigosa Wednesday afternoon at a preschool on the UCLA campus. Democrat Barack Obama will be in the state on Saturday for events in Piedmont, Oakland, Sunnyvale and Woodside. Posted by John Marelius May 30, 2007 10:43 AM | Opinions expressed do not necessarily represent those of SignOnSanDiego or The San Diego Union-Tribune Make us your homepage Privacy & Copyright Policy Your California Privacy Rights &copy; Copyright 2007 Union-Tribune Publishing Co. &#149; A Copley Newspaper Site
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-6&fd=R&url=http://www.heralddemocrat.com/articles/2007/05/28/texas_news/state02.txt&cid=1116323345&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Submit Letter to Editor Letters to the Editor Place a Classified Ad Shop Best Buy Online Friends of the Family This poll is for entertainment purposes only. It is not scientifically valid information. &deg Submit Letter to Editor &deg Change of Address Rep. Jim Pitts, R-Waxahachie, speaks during a news conference before the session in the Texas House of Representatives Sunday in Austin. Rep. Pitts is one of several who have announced they would seek to unseat House Speaker Tom Craddick, R-Midland. House rebellion continues, Craddick unwavering AUSTIN &#8212; Embattled House Speaker Tom Craddick clung unwavering to his leadership Sunday as he entered day three of a showdown with House rebels who want to kick him out of office. The session ends Monday and if Craddick can maintain the post until then, he&#8217;ll have won this round. But getting through Sunday could be tumultuous for the troubled House. That&#8217;s because they have to pass the &#036;153 billion two-year state budget &#8212; the only legislation they&#8217;re legally required to pass. And anti-Craddick forces want to reject the budget when it comes up for a vote later Sunday, forcing 30-day special session to reconsider it. &#8220;I believe we owe it to Texans to do that,&#8221; said Rep. Jim Pitts, a Waxahachie Republican. &#8220;We&#8217;re here to be conservative with the people&#8217;s money.&#8221; Pitts, who has announced his candidacy to replace Craddick as speaker, says Craddick is using his power to insert pork in the budget to influence the speaker&#8217;s race. &#8220;This budget has grown our of control. It is full of wasteful and unnecessary spending,&#8221; Pitts said. The 150-member House elected Craddick to be their leader when the session started in January. But many have grown increasingly disenchanted with his win-at-all-costs approach to leading the chamber. Tensions peaked Friday night when Craddick announced that he would not recognize anyone to make a parliamentary motion to vote him out of office 18 months before his third term expires. When Craddick cut off discussion, chaos broke out and sergeants-at-arms restrained insurgents trying to overtake the speaker&#8217;s podium and the House parliamentarian resigned on the verge of tears. Since then, proceedings have been a parliamentary battle of wills &#8212; as long as Craddick didn&#8217;t recognize opponents to kick him out of office, the 150-member chamber couldn&#8217;t vote to do so. That didn&#8217;t stop opponents from trying again Sunday. Craddick listened to questions from the back microphone, but repeatedly cited the same House rule that he&#8217;s been using since Friday to support his refusal to recognize lawmakers to make a parliamentary motion to oust him. &#8220;I hope the speaker will reconsider his position on that,&#8221; said Democratic Rep. Mark Strama, an Austin Democrat. It &#8220;undermines the fundamental principles of government in this country.&#8221; Craddick&#8217;s supporters pleaded for an end to the gamesmanship, reminding House members that time was running out for them to finish passing legislation. &#8220;Is there any way we can get on with doing the people&#8217;s business as opposed to some people&#8217;s personal agendas?&#8221; asked Rep. Bill Zedler, an Arlington Republican. &#8220;That&#8217;s up to the members Mr. Zedler,&#8221; Craddick replied. Copyright &copy; 2007 All Rights Reserved The Herald Democrat
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-1&fd=R&url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_6017304&cid=1116617146&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ The Denver Post - Victim's brother sees 'doorstep of justice' in cold-case trial 3 10 14 18 28 33 7 23 35 54 55 (28) pp-2 Denver & The West Economy / Real Estate Subscribe / Customer Care Denver & the West Victim's brother sees 'doorstep of justice' in cold-case trial By EMILY WAGSTER PETTUS Associated Press Writer Article Last Updated: 05/30/2007 12:04:52 AM MDT JACKSON, Miss.- For decades, books and news accounts treated the killings of Charles Eddie Moore and Henry Hezekiah Dee as footnotes in Mississippi's troubled history of racial brutality. Now, reputed Ku Klux Klansman James Ford Seale is about to stand trial in Jackson on the first-ever federal kidnapping and conspiracy charges connected to the 1964 slayings of the black teenagers in southwest Mississippi. Jury selection is scheduled to start Wednesday. "We're at the doorstep of justice," said Charles Moore's brother, Thomas Moore, a 63-year-old Army veteran who lives in Colorado Springs, Colo. Thomas Moore and two of Dee's sisters&mdash;Thelma Collins, 70, of Springfield, La.; and Mary Nell Byrd, 61, of Natchez, Miss.&mdash;spoke to The Associated Press on Tuesday in Jackson during an interview arranged by Canadian Broadcasting Corp. documentary maker David Ridgen. Since 2005, Ridgen and Thomas Moore have pushed federal officials to reopen the cold case. Ridgen's film, "Mississippi Cold Case," is set to air at 10 p.m. Saturday on MSNBC. Collins said Tuesday that her younger brother, a quiet teenager, spent two weeks with her at her home in Albany, La., shortly before he disappeared. She is the oldest of five siblings and Henry was the youngest; she still calls him "the baby." She moved away from the family home in Mississippi when she was 17 and he was still small. During their last visit, she said Dee quickly became friends with young people who lived nearby. Collins said the family had a pleasant two weeks together. Then, he was gone forever. "I try not to think about it so much because, you know, it's done now," Collins said of her brother's death. "But every time I think about it, I shed a tear." Byrd, like her brother, is quiet. During the interview Tuesday, she spoke barely above a whisper. All three relatives say it's possible they'll testify during the Seale trial. Dee and Charles Moore were not troublemakers, their families say. They were just two 19-year-olds&mdash;friends from school in Franklin County and from Mount Olive Baptist Church in the tiny Kirby Community&mdash;who happened to be in the wrong place at the wrong time. On May 2, 1964, Dee and Moore were picked up while hitchhiking near Meadville when carloads of Ku Klux Klansmen were chasing rumors of a possible armed insurrection by black people in the area. Recent court records said Dee and Charles Moore were taken to the Homochitto National Forest and beaten, then they were stuffed into a trunk and driven more than 70 miles to the Mississippi River near Vicksburg. They were weighted down with engine parts and dumped, still breathing, into the Mississippi River. Their decomposing bodies were found more than two months later, when authorities were conducting a massive search for civil-rights workers Michael Schwerner, James Chaney and Andrew Goodman, who disappeared from central Mississippi's Neshoba County on June 21, 1964. "My thing is, Charles Moore and Henry Dee wasn't bothering anybody," Thomas Moore said Tuesday. "And for them to be butchered, tormented, hassled and drowned in the river&mdash;it was pretty bad." Seale and reputed KKK member Charles Marcus Edwards were arrested in 1964 in the deaths of Dee and Moore. But the FBI was consumed by the "Mississippi Burning" investigation from Neshoba County, and the Dee-Moore case was turned over to local authorities, who promptly threw out all charges against Seale and Edwards. The Justice Department in 2000 reopened an investigation. The FBI has said the case was closed in 2003 and opened again in 2005. Edwards has been granted immunity and is expected to testify for the prosecution. Thomas Moore said he asked his mother in 1964 what she wanted him to do about the death of his brother, 13 months younger, whom he called "Nub." "She said, 'Don't you do anything because ... the Lord will provide,'" Moore said. She died in 1977, and Thomas Moore over the years tried to interest authorities in reopening an investigation. "I think my mom is dancing in glory," Thomas Moore said. "I think Charles Moore and Henry Dee are walking among the flowers saying, 'Thank God for Thomas Moore and David Ridgen.'" Collins and Moore said they're prepared for any outcome in the Seale trial. "I just have it in my heart that they're going to do the right thing," Collins said. Moore has already planned what he'll do after the trial, regardless of the outcome. "The last thing that I'm going to do when I leave Mississippi," he said, "I'm going to go to that cemetery, that Mount Olive Cemetery, I'm going to tell Charles Moore, 'I told you that I see it to the end.'" More Denver & The West headlines Colo. speller slips on consonant TB patient at National Jewish Evans gets 4 more years Season wraps Sunday at A-Basin TB patient arrives in Denver Suburban pet peeve: coyotes Record bond plan in the works 14-to-life for former priest AFA grads cheer diplomas, duty Uncertainty surrounds man thought swept away State Patrol put on road to nowhere Superior girl cruises into national semis at spelling bee Cleanse your conscience as you wet your whistle Just a drive on Colo. 5 free of fee 22 troopers complete immigration training In rarely used quarantines, public health trumps liberties CSU a favorite of feds in TB fight Tuberculosis in Colorado history Colo. legislators try to steer EPA Gas-tax alternatives suggested to increase highway funds Salazar gathering views in Mideast Day-labor gathering a sore spot Crashes claim 4 lives in 2 days Woman beaten, dragged in Centennial carjacking Briefs: 13 felony charges for Evergreen teacher Denver & the West TB patient at National Jewish Evans gets 4 more years Season wraps Sunday at A-Basin Rockies streak strikes out Touching all the bases Pahlsson a big piece of puzzle Weakest economic growth since 2002 "Potter" theme park to open in Florida Gay Chorus sets tone of harmony She shoots horses, doesn't she? Deadly disease needs to be eradicated now Lunch menu: Carrots, sticks A sign of the times in Iran Listener helps save ailing disc jockey Wal-Mart cashier: I was fired for joking 'Faith-healing' brothers charged in scam Colo.&#39;s speller slips on consonant TB patient at National Jewish Evans gets 4 more years Season wraps Sunday at A-Basin TB patient arrives in Denver Suburban pet peeve: coyotes Personal - Injury - Lawyer Luxury Denver Real Estate Reverse Osmosis Water Filters Cabin Kits & Building Cabins Printers & Printer Supplies Lasik Denver eye surgery All contents Copyright 2007 The Denver Post or other copyright holders. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed for any commercial purpose. E-mail Newsletters & Breaking News Alerts Subscribe / Customer Care MNG Corporate Site Map
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-3&fd=R&url=http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/content/may2007/db20070530_660667.htm%3Fchan%3Dtop%2Bnews_top%2Bnews%2Bindex_businessweek%2Bexclusives&cid=1116788973&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ A Diplomat for the World Bank BusinessWeek B-Schools: 2007 Winner, National Magazine Award for Interactive Service Car Care & Safety May 31, 2007, 12:01AM EST A Diplomat for the World Bank Robert Zoellick will have to soothe hard feelings generated by Paul Wolfowitz, whose style and role in Iraq policy rankled allies Bloggers Zero In on Zoellick It was a rare experience for George W. Bush: A major Presidential decision was greeted with bipartisan praise and international congratulations. By picking former U.S. Trade Representative Robert Zoellick on May 30 to replace Paul Wolfowitz as president of the World Bank, Bush made a symbolic and substantive statement that he hoped to unify the controversy-wracked institution and put Wolfowitz's divisive, two-year tenure quickly behind him. Wolfowitz resigned his position, effective June 30, amid ethics questions raised by his role in securing a generous compensation package for his girlfriend (see BusinessWeek.com, 5/17/07, "More Problems After Wolfowitz" An Expert in Diplomacy Zoellick, like Wolfowitz, is known as an accomplished academic and a demanding boss. But unlike the combative Wolfowitz, the prospective bank president has a reputation as an expert in diplomacy and international banking. Zoellick, 53, served as a top State Dept. official under President Bush, and the top Treasury Department official on international economic matters. He was also President George H.W. Bush's top adviser for two Group of Seven international economic summits, as well as a managing director at Goldman Sachs ( ) and chairman of the company's international advisers department. His global economic expertise includes work on issues from Latin American debt relief and German reunification to Chinese entry into the World Trade Organization and restructuring U.S. aid programs for Africa. Democratic Senator Max Baucus (D-Mont.), chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, lauded Zoellick as "the right person for this job." Said Baucus: "It's hard to imagine a more intelligent, hard-working, and capable person to assume the bank's leadership at this difficult point in its history. Bob has the skills and the integrity to put the bank back on the right path." Not Much of a Honeymoon House Speaker Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.) praised Zoellick's efforts to bring peace to war-torn Darfur, calling him a sensitive and caring person. Even Senator John Kerry (D-Mass.), Bush's vanquished 2004 Presidential rival, says Zoellick "brings a diverse range of skills and international experience to the position" and hopes he "can regain the confidence of employees and donor nations that was lost under the previous leader." Kind words aside, Zoellick can't expect much of a honeymoon in his new job as the bank's 11th president in its 60-year history. Bank-watchers say he has a lot of work to do to soothe the hard feelings generated by Wolfowitz, whose role as an architect of the Bush Administration's Iraq policy rankled European allies and bank staffers. "His major initial challenge is to rebuild the morale of the organization and to bring someone with a strong management background in to put things back together again in a better way than before," says Edwin "Ted" Truman, senior fellow at the Peter G. Peterson Center for International Economics. During the White House announcement ceremony, Bush and Zoellick both alluded to the recent divisions and the challenges ahead. Zoellick, said Bush, "has earned the trust and support of leaders from every region of the world." Zoellick declared that "we need to approach this task with humility and creative minds." He praised the World Bank staff that warred with Wolfowitz as "many fine professionals from all over the world." "The World Bank has passed through a difficult time for all involved," Zoellick said during the nine-minute event in the Roosevelt Room. "There are frustrations, anxieties, and tensions about the past that could inhibit the future. This is understandable, but not without remedy. We need to put yesterday's discord behind us and to focus on the future together." Post a comment about this story in Reader Discussion&#8230; CEO Guide to Tech Byte of the Apple Dawn of the Ultra Mobile PC Apple TV + YouTube = What's Next Don't Call It a Bubble S&P Picks and Pans: Apple, EMC, Viacom, CNOOC, Polo RL U.S.-India Trade at Risk? RSS Feed: Most Read Stories Apple TV + YouTube = What's Next Big Blue Wields the Knife Again U.S.-India Trade at Risk? A Cell Phone for Baby Boomers How Flash Will Change PCs RSS Feed: Most E-mailed Stories U.S.-India Trade at Risk? Dawn of the Ultra Mobile PC India's Car Design Guru Wants to Pass It On Gates Digs Surface Computing RSS Feed: Most Discussed Stories Intel's Think Thin Laptop The World's 50 Most Decadent Hotels Best Affordable Suburbs 2006 The Biggest Metro Areas with the Lowest Rents Immigration and the Visa Maze RSS Feed: Most Popular Slide Shows BW Mall - Sponsored Links Mortgage Rates at 3.0% - Refinance Now! $150,000 loan for $391/month - refinance, home equity and purchase. Webroot Spy Sweeper â The BEST antispyware Stay safe online. Webroot Spy Sweeper detects 97% of spyware â 40% more than the competition! Merrill Lynch 3 & 6-Mo CDs Two Great Offers. 1) High-Yield FDIC Insured CDs 2) Home Equity Line of Credit. Limited Time. Home Equity and Mortgage Loans - E-LOAN Low Rate Mortgage, Refinance & Home Equity Loans. Approval in Minutes. No Lender fees. Apply Now. Discover iShares. More Tools. More strategies. More possibilities. Buy a link now! Copyright 2000-2007 by The McGraw-Hill Companies Inc. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-3&fd=R&url=http://www.tcpalm.com/tcp/local_news/article/0,,TCP_16736_5561977,00.html&cid=1116758582&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Subscription Services &#150; Home Delivery Specials! Letters to the Editor As Lake O level falls, so does business Lake O 'waiting for the rain' Okeechobee fishing guide and bait and tackle store owner discuss the effects of low water levels on the area. OKEECHOBEE &#151; Bubba Helton wonders how long he can keep his doors open. Larry Wright would love to take someone fishing. Wendy Woodman figures it's going to be a slow Fourth of July holiday. Lake Okeechobee tied a record low water level Wednesday &#151; 8.97 feet above sea level. But the water level isn't the only thing hitting bottom in this part of Central Florida. Businesses around the northern rim of the nation's second- largest freshwater lake also are seeing record lows. Retail sales, dinners served at area restaurants, motel/campsite bookings and rentals are well off the mark following a slower than average season &#151; January through April. And the summer slowdown might spell the end for some businesses. Helton blames a large portion of his lost business on mismanaged water and mis-modeled weather forecasting. "The Army Corps of Engineers and South Florida Water Management District don't know how to run the business they're in," said Helton, owner of Garrard's Bait and Tackle on 441 in Okeechobee. "For 18 months they dumped water out of the lake, and then we went into a natural drought." The low water levels have prevented anglers from taking fishing trips on Florida's most famed fishing lake. Although the fishing is good for bass and bluegill, almost no one can get out onto the lake since the waters have receded to the point where boat ramps empty onto dry ground. Helton said he knows of three tackle shops around the lake that already have closed their doors because of waning customer traffic, and he might not be that far behind if business doesn't pick up soon. Wright, a captain who has guided anglers to lunker largemouth bass for 26 years, hopes he can continue to make a living despite what he estimates as a 75 percent drop in charters. "In May last year, I worked 26 days," said Wright, 55. "This year, I had 10." He had 21 trips last June, but has only three on the books this year. Wright said few customers are coming from other states to fish because of the low water. "We get quite a few anglers from South Carolina, Georgia and Alabama who come here to fish this time of year," he said. "The moms and dads will get their high school kids fishing trips. They're just not coming. "They may think the lake is just completely dried up." Woodman, general manager of the K.O.A. Campground in Okeechobee, said the Memorial Day weekend wasn't too bad for bookings; however, Fourth of July reservations are off quite a bit. "Our business is impacted a little bit," Woodman said, "but we have guests who come here for activities besides fishing and boating." The way Helton sees it, the entire economy of Okeechobee is tied directly or indirectly to the level of the lake. "This doesn't only affect me," Helton said. "Motels, gas stations, grocery stores, even Wal-Mart has slower sales when the traffic is down." And Helton's unhappiness doesn't end with the water managers. "We've been let down by our county commissioners, congressmen, senators and governor," Helton said. "I don't care if there's a three-legged dog running in the next election, I'm voting against all of them." 3 (bookings to date) 41 bass, 48 bluegill and shellcracker 31 bass to 8 pounds Forecasters with the National Weather Service predict a roughly 40 percent chance of rain on Friday and a 50 percent chance of rain on Saturday. The South Florida Water Management District says even if it does rain, it would have to fall directly over the lake to help it rebound. Bubba Helton wonders how long he can keep his doors open. Larry Wright would love to take someone fishing. Wendy Woodman figures it's going to be a slow Fourth of July holiday. As Lake O level falls, so does business Build an ad with PHOTOS Free ad - Classified items under $500 Advertise and only pay for clicks - $50 free to start Our new real estate search engine has more local listings than anyone else &raquo; The most local job listings to get your new career search in high gear &raquo; Deals on wheels galore. You can search local dealer inventories 24/7 &raquo; Shop through our newspaper ads online&raquo; Scripps Treasure Coast Newspapers . Site Users are subject to our Contact TCPalm.com at Feedback@tcpalm.com Other E.W. Scripps Web sites:
