http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-5&fd=R&url=http://www.wsav.com/midatlantic/sav/news.apx.-content-articles-SAV-2007-05-29-0009.html&cid=1116783089&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ WSAV.com - Savannah / Hilton Head - News - President Bush Talks Immigration in Brunswick President Bush Talks Immigration in Brunswick Tuesday, May 29, 2007 - 11:25 AM To watch video online please click to download the latest version of the Flash plugin. Georgia played host to President Bush on Tuesday. The purpose of his visit was to talk about a new compromise on immigration reform. President Bush stopped on Tuesday morning to speak at the Federal Law Enforcement Training Center, FLETC, in Glynco, which is near Brunswick. President Bush toured the country's largest federal law enforcement training center, known as FLETC. Afterwards, he spoke to the more than 2,000 people about his immigration reform proposal. The crowd was made up of FLETC students, law enforcement officials, as well as immigration and customs officials. &ldquo;I hope that it will build the support that we need to continue the fight that we are so desperately trying to do here." Says Victor Watson a Program Specialist, Counter Terrorism Division at FLETC. 3 On Your Side's Randi Hempel was at Tuesday's presidential visit President Bush's is trying to sell the immigration plan as conservative critics say the bill is too soft on those who break the law. But, the proposal is not an amnesty plan. The 12-million people living in the U.S. illegally have to acknowledge that they're breaking the law and to pay a fine. Those people can apply for a Z visa, which will grant them temporary legal status. In addition to paying a fine, illegal immigrants will have to pass a background check, remain employed and maintain a clean record. Immigrants aren't the only ones who face big changes. Employers who hire illegal workers will face stiff penalties. "The message to employers is if you hire somebody here that you know is illegal. There is a consequence to be paid." The President said. Those penalties are going up, with maximum fines rising to $5,000 for first time offenders, $25,000 for the third offense. The maximum criminal penalty carrying a $75,000 fine per violation. President Bush says he wants both parties to stop the political bickering. "The fundamental issue is will elected officials have the courage necessary to put a comprehensive immigration plan in place that makes it more likely that we can enforce our border and at same time uphold great immigrant traditions of the United States of America.&rdquo; President Bush talked about how the illegal immigrants are doing jobs Americans aren't, like working on farms here in Georgia, but that if they want to work in this country, they must follow the law. The Bush Administration's border security plan has already doubled funding for border security...spending $10.4 billion this year. When he took office in 2001, $4.6 billion was spent. The bill calls for expanding the number of border patol agents. In 2001, there were 9,000, today there are 13,000 and by the end of 2008, there will be more than 18,000 agents. The bill calls for more border fencing, building 370 miles of fencing and 200 miles of vehicle barriers. There are already measures in place to secure the border, but they will be increased. What we already have is 5290 sensors on the southern border, 687 nighttime cameras on the southern border, 449 daytime cameras and 1 unmanned aerial system, with another to be added by July of this year. President Bush says he knows Americans are skeptical about immigration reform because they don't think the problem can be fixed...he just asks that they give it a chance. For more information on the Comprehensive Immigration Reform Proposal, Click on these links. Fact Sheet, Securing the Border First Immigration Fact Check: Responding to Key Myths News 3 - On Your Side Copyright Â© 2007 Media General, Inc. All Rights Reserved Terms, Conditions & 