http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-2&fd=R&url=http://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/story/75013.html&cid=1116693177&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Three more from Fort Lewis die | TheNewsTribune.com | Tacoma, WA Saves you time. Saves you money. Makes you smarter. The News Tribune, Tacoma, WA - Thursday, May 31st, 2007 9:50 AM BLOG: The Prep Blog Wall Street Journal Sunday Letters to the editor BLOG: Inside the Editorial Page Nation & World Photos Bars & night life BLOG: Bring the Noise With the Strykers in Iraq Inside the Editorial Page Online in the South Sound Riding Around the Sound Open House: Real estate Today's full text obituaries Place an In Memoriam Three more from Fort Lewis die MICHAEL GILBERT; The News Tribune Published: May 31st, 2007 01:00 AM Three more Fort Lewis soldiers have been killed in Iraq, the Department of Defense announced Wednesday. They were identified as: &#8226; Staff Sgt. Thomas M. McFall, 36, of Glendora, Calif. &#8226; Pfc. Junior Cedeno Sanchez, 20, of Miami. &#8226; Pfc. Charles B. Hester, 23, of Cataldo, Idaho. McFall and Cedeno Sanchez were killed in Baghdad on Monday, Memorial Day, when a bomb exploded nearby as they patrolled on foot, according to a Pentagon news release. Hester was killed two days earlier when a bomb detonated near his vehicle. The deaths bring to 19 the number of soldiers the post has lost in Iraq this month, more than in any other month since the invasion in March 2003. The May casualty total is now more than double Fort Lewis&#8217; previous worst month since the invasion: December 2004, when nine soldiers were killed. Fort Lewis has 10,000 soldiers in Iraq &#8211; likewise more than at any time in the war. Nearly all are deployed in two Stryker brigades in Baghdad and in Diyala province just to the northeast of the capital, scene of some of the deadliest insurgent attacks the past two months. Hester was assigned to the 2nd Battalion, 3rd Infantry Regiment, which is part of the 3rd Brigade, 2nd Infantry Division &#8211; a Stryker brigade that&#8217;s been in Iraq since last June. It&#8217;s expected to remain there into October. McFall and Cedeno Sanchez were assigned to the 1st Battalion, 38th Infantry Regiment, a part of the 4th Brigade, 2nd Infantry Division. It left Fort Lewis in April and arrived in Iraq early this month. The brigade has lost nine soldiers now in the first month of what is expected to be a 15-month deployment. Twenty-eight soldiers from the 3rd Brigade have been killed in nearly a year. McFall&#8217;s wife, Emily, in a statement through the post public affairs office, described her husband as &#8220;a proud dad, a great son and a friend to many.&#8221; He was renowned for his barbecued ribs and his fondness for classic rock and cold beer, she said. They had soldiers over often, especially at the holidays. &#8220;He would go into a bar, bathroom, store, anywhere, and someone would start talking to him like they knew him,&#8221; she said. &#8220;He could always put a positive spin on anything. He made me and a lot of other people better just by knowing him. &#8220;He loved the brotherhood, and his heart beat red, white, and blue,&#8221; Emily McFall said. &#8220;There was only one exit for him.&#8221; A post spokesman said McFall joined the Army in 1994 and was assigned to Fort Bragg, N.C. He then spent a year in South Korea and was at Fort Lewis in the late 1990s before going to Hawaii and deploying to Afghanistan for a year in 2004-05. Cedeno Sanchez joined the Army in November 2005 and arrived at Fort Lewis the following June. Hester enlisted in May 2004 and arrived at Fort Lewis that September and deployed with the 3rd Brigade last June. Hester and Cedeno Sanchez were serving on their first combat tours. Two other soldiers suffered minor injuries in the attack that killed Hester, but they returned to duty, officials said. No memorial ceremony at Fort Lewis has been set for the three Stryker soldiers. Brig. Gen. William Troy, the acting post commander, last week wrote a memo saying that memorials now would be consolidated once a month, so presumably these three men will be memorialized together in late June. Car museum might alter first phase Cue choirs! New bridge set to open July 15 Three more from Fort Lewis die Domestic violence: &#8216;Act Now&#8217; Couple killed on Highway 7 Appeals court rules against ferry workers Fife&#8217;s farming roots remembered Do donations from tribes affect politics? Send a winner out in style this Saturday Report: Long-time deputy to lead King County prosecutors MLS for the Northwest? Here come the Sonics, Oklahoma Way too much Guerrero Sharapova shoulders opening win Lleyton Hewitt advances at French Open NBA title could elevate James to stuff of legend No. 2 pick for Kobe? No thanks Answers to your questions, vol. 157 Now The Mariners Know Where They Stand New title, familiar role for Neuheisel Longtime Washington High track coach Smith retiring Alaska Airlines adding nonstop flights to Hawaii Fresh Wild Waves on the horizon Car museum might alter first phase New online store caters to oversize shoppers A pricier T-bone this summer? &#8216;All-cap&#8217; keeps funds from being too specific Fed appears content to leave interest rates alone, May 9 minutes suggest Qatar Airways orders 20 more Airbus A350s, but 787 still far ahead Precious metals prices climb He makes the Y go round Alaska Air heads for sunny beaches Something we can all relate to It&#8217;s a long day up Mount Whitney Map shows trails ravaged by storms Education heads to the beach Series of hikes, clinics focuses on families Nature camps teach about animals, environment This little piggy - A local farmer and a local chef cook up something special Lohan's dad: Lindsay hooked on OxyContin Flower and garden show, here we come! Dr. Strangebrew or: How I Learned to Stop Ordering Beer and Drink Wine Beastie Boys, Interpol and more scenes from Sasquatch A look at Carnival Games 1950 South State Street, Ta