tatement. Thompson joins a crowded Republican field with no dominant choice. President George W. Bush, prohibited from running for a third term in November 2008, is set to leave office in January 2009. The current front-runners include former New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Sen. John McCain, of Arizona, and former Massachusetts Gov. Mitt Romney. Ingram said Thompson held a conference call with fund-raisers on Tuesday and it was decided that he would "test the waters" by setting up a preliminary committee. Ten men are already running for the Republican nomination and former House of Representatives Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia also is weighing a campaign. Thompson was first elected to the Senate in 1994 to fill Democrat Al Gore's seat when he became vice president. He maintained a solid conservative voting record. Besides having been a U.S. senator and working as an actor, Mr. Thompson was also worked as an attorney for the Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee during its impeachment hearings of former President Richard Nixon. You can read this article by Reuters correspondent Richard Cowan, reporting from Washington, D.C., in context here: Additional reporting for this article was provided by Reuters correspondents JoAnne Allen, in Washington, D.C., and Dean Goodman, in Los Angeles, California. Add your own comment. Original materials on this site (c) Free Internet Press. Any mirrored or quoted materials (c) their respective authors, publications, or outlets, as shown on their publication, indicated by the link in the news story. Original Free Internet Press materials may be copied and/or republished without modification, provided a link to is given in the story, or proper credit is given. Please email editor@freeinternetpress.com there are any questions. Our Privacy Policy can be viewed at
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-4&fd=R&url=http://www.caller.com/news/2007/may/30/session-began-ended-with-craddick-challenge-to-a/&cid=1116323345&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Session began, ended with Craddick challenge : Corpus Christi Caller-Times - Editorials : caller.com Subscribe to the paper LETTERS TO THE EDITOR Once a day in your inbox. You are not logged in: Session began, ended with Craddick challenge Before coming to a rancorous close, the 80th session of the Legislature managed to pass a budget and important bills. More Opinion - Featured Letters to the Editor: 05.31.07 The U.S. and Iran, after a long silence, are tentatively talking The county fritters away crucial diabetes money The 80th Texas Legislature ended pretty much as it had started, with House Speaker Tom Craddick having to fend off a challenge to his leadership. In between, the House and Senate managed to pass some meaningful legislation, but few legislators, particularly Craddick, will remember this tumultuous and tendentious session as memorable for its accomplishments. Craddick is a survivor, but being the longest serving member in the House and the first Republican House speaker since Reconstruction has not taught the Midland legislator much about using the levers of power in the service of a great vision for the people of Texas. Instead, Craddick has used the power of the post to punish political opponents, reward sycophants and force anyone else who doesn't get in step with his conservative agenda to knuckle under. Now the fight to remove him from what is considered to be one of the three most powerful offices in state government moves to the 2008 elections in which those who have openly declared their opposition now may face challengers funded by Craddick supporters. It is likely that the fight over who controls the House gavel is only being postponed until the 2009 session. This session, however, wasn't all political brawls. Texas legislators did move the state forward by restoring the false savings in the Children's Health Insurance Program that had been made by the 2003 session. Likewise, Texas state parks, whose treatment under state budgets has been all but shameful, will get new money as a cap on the sporting goods tax was loosened. The cause of open government was advanced with the passage of a constitutional proposal, to be on the November ballot that would record individual legislators' votes on final passage of bills. And the session dealt decisively with a sex scandal at the Texas Youth Commission. As in any Texas legislative session, some measures failed that merited passing, such as a statewide smoking ban in public places, and a shield law for Texas journalists. Some measures passed to the detriment of open government, such as allowing the sealing of some search warrants and making private the names of holders of concealed weapons permits. Some measures fully merited their demise, such as yet another school voucher program and requiring photo IDs for voters at the polls. Left simmering at the end of this session was highway funding. When state legislators return in 2009, they will have to face the question of whether to raise the gasoline tax or find alternative funding for the state's massive transportation needs. And left on a rolling boil was the question of Crad-dick's leadership. He clearly deserves to go, but a creaky system that favors incumbents through open balloting and the power of the budget serves to keep him as speaker of a rebellious House. PASSED, AWAITING GOVERNOR ACTION Sets out a $153 billion two-year spending plan for the state covering major programs such as K-12 education, public universities, health and human services, state parks and criminal justice. Establishes mandatory random steroid testing for Texas public high school athletes in all sports as early as the 2007 football season. Imposes a possible death penalty for sex offenders who are twice convicted of raping children under 14. Increases the Texas marriage license fee from $30 to $60 but waives the fee and a 72-hour waiting period for couples who take a premarital education course. Freezes most new privately financed toll road projects for two years. Allows judges to seal some search warrant information from the public for up to 60 days. Creates the Texas State Railroad Authority, intended to keep an East Texas tourist train running between Palestine and Rusk by allowing the venture to be leased to a private operator. Requires state pension funds to divest from companies doing business with Sudan, where more than 200,000 people have been killed and 2.5 million been chased from their homes since 2003 because of civil strife. Makes dog owners whose pets attack people subject to a third-degree felony with possible prison time of two to ten years and a possible $10,000 fine. If the victim dies, the charge could become a second-degree felony, punishable by up to 20 years in prison. Calls for the state to assist in plans for the humane evacuation, transport and temporary sheltering of pets during times of disaster, such as a hurricane. Adds the words âunder Godâ to the Texas pledge of allegiance. Puts an executive commissioner in charge of the Texas Youth Commission for two years. Improves staff-to-inmate ratios, creates new investigative powers to check abuse claims and prohibits courts from sending youths to state lockups for misdemeanors. Allows high schools to offer elective Bible courses. Provides Texas students greater freedom to express their religious views on school campuses by treating studentsâ religious viewpoints in class assignments the same as secular expression. Charges strip club patrons a $5 admission fee, with money going to help sexual assault victims. Replaces the stateâs high-stakes high school exit exam, known as the Texas Assessment of Knowledge and Skills, with end-of-course tests. Rewards Medicaid recipients for adopting healthy lifestyles and encourages them to seek treatment at doctorâs office instead of a hospital emergency room. Revises the stateâs new business tax to fix errors and loopholes in last yearâs franchise tax overhaul and giving many small businesses a discount. Changes enrollment rules for the Childrenâs Health Insurance Program to allow more than 127,000 children to be added to a low-cost state insurance program. Strengthens protections for foster children and repeals much of the privatization lawmakers ordered two years ago in the foster care system. Establishes a 30-minute-per-day physical education requirement, of moderate to vigorous activity, for middle school students. Implements the first major water policy in a decade, designed to protect rivers and streams and setting aside areas for up to 19 new reservoirs. Helps direct more money and resources to Texas-Mexico border security. Allows lawmakers to spend more money on improvements to Texasâ 600,000-acre state park system. PASSED, BECOMING LAW WITHOUT GOVERNORâS SIGNATURE Blocks state officials from following Gov. Rick Perryâs order requiring the vaccine against the human papillomavirus for sixth-grade girls. The vaccine protects against strains of the sexually transmitted virus that cause most cases of cervical cancer. Expands HIV testing in the state prison system to establish mandatory testing of inmates when they report to prison. PASSED, VETOED BY GOVERNOR Would have required the Texas Department of Criminal Justice to notify former inmates of their eligibility to vote. Would have limited the number of students automatically admitted to public universities under the stateâs top 10 percent law. Would have banned smoking in workplaces and many other public places statewide. Would have required voters to show photo identification or two other forms of ID, not just a voter registration card. Would have sold the state lottery to a private firm for at least $14 billion and used the proceeds for cancer research, education and health insurance, a proposal made by Gov. Rick Perry. Would have created full-scale destination resort casinos in major cities and some coastal tourist spots. Would have allowed video slot machines, known as video lottery terminals, at horse and dog race tracks. Would have allowed limited casino gambling on the stateâs American Indian reservations. Would have created a pilot program to allow some parents to send their children to private schools using taxpayer money. Would have created limited immunity for journalists from revealing their confidential sources in court cases. Would have required doctors to perform ultrasounds on pregnant women seeking an abortion. Would have allowed police to set up checkpoints to see whether motorists exceed the legal blood-alcohol level for driving. Would have extended the 10-day time limit for medically futile patients before hospitals can cut off their life support. Would have allowed private schools into the Texas public school athletic league. Would have required motorists to give bicyclists at least three feet of space when passing. Would have allowed couples applying for a marriage license or couples already married to designate theirs a âcovenant marriage,â making divorce more difficult. PASSED, HEADED TO TEXAS VOTERS A proposed constitutional amendment allowing the state to borrow up to $3 billion over the next decade to fund cancer research aimed at finding a cure. A proposed constitutional amendment requiring the Texas House and Senate to record individual lawmakersâ votes on final passage of bills. Posted by stff on May 30, 2007 at 9:55 a.m. ( Thank goodness the "Shield Law' for Texas journalist s failed! The last thing the partisian press needs in this state and this country is extra protection over and above what they already have in the Constitution. They would hide behind this to allow their interests (the Democrat party and liberal special interests) to go after the Republicans and Conservatives. Unitl the partsian press shows