http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-2&fd=R&url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/education/bal-bee0531,0,635714.story%3Fcoll%3Dbal-home-headlines&cid=1116552892&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Two Md. Spelling Bee contestants advance - baltimoresun.com Become a mySun member Two Md. Spelling Bee contestants advance Eighth-graders from Arnold, Prince Frederick survive first semifinal round Originally published May 31, 2007, 12:13 PM EDT Maryland's two remaining National Spelling Bee contestants advanced through the semifinal round of competition this morning. Selena Grace Roper, an eighth-grader at Severn River Middle School in Arnold, correctly spelled bialy -- a Jewish-American roll similar to a bagel -- and Izaak Baker, an eighth-grader at Calvert Middle School in Prince Frederick, correctly spelled melioidosis -- a bacterial disease that affects lymph nodes and internal organs. To reach the semifinal round, Roper passed a multiple-choice spelling test and previously spelled primitive, requisite and oleic correctly on stage. Baker also passed the multiple-choice test and had correctly spelled argumentative, theologaster and lambdacism. The finals will take place tonight from 8 p.m. to 10 p.m. Baltimore's first national spelling bee contestant in 25 years, David Brokaw, a sixth-grader from the Friends School, successfully spelled the word "marathon" on stage in the first round but did not pass the 25-question test. Get Sun home delivery Maryland's National Spelling Bee entrants National Spelling Bee round results The run ends for city speller Written test takes Friends School boy out of Bee reporters weigh in on news and issues in education Poor schools, rich targets Readers have audience that's all ears Officials scramble to exterminate chiggers City school's infestation a first for most On Campus: Live & Learn Our guide features profiles of Maryland's colleges and universities, campus photo galleries, event listings, student survival tips and more. The run ends