http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-4&fd=R&url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/31/nyregion/31street.html&cid=1116778683&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Council Rejects Street Name for Black Activist - New York Times Council Rejects Street Name for Black Activist Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 31, 2007 In a racially divisive hearing, the City Council yesterday rejected a measure that would have named a street after Sonny Carson, a radical black activist who more than once described himself as &#8220;antiwhite.&#8221; The Council rejected the amendment in a 25-to-15 vote that was divided along racial lines, as protesters in the balcony hissed at each vote cast against it. The loudest jeers were reserved for Council Speaker Christine C. Quinn, the amendment&#8217;s most prominent opponent, and seven black or Hispanic council members who abstained from voting. But while the outcome was widely expected, the high-decibel meeting, preceded by a rally on the steps of City Hall, was a stark contrast to the normally subdued process the Council goes through once or twice a year in choosing people to honor with street names. It was also one the most divisive issues to confront Ms. Quinn, the council&#8217;s first openly gay speaker and an ardent supporter of civil rights causes, in her year and half as speaker. At one point, Councilman Charles Barron, a Brooklyn Democrat and a former Black Panther, refused to stop talking after his two-minute comment period. Wagging a finger in Ms. Quinn&#8217;s direction, Mr. Barron said, &#8220;You have divided us more than Sonny Carson ever did.&#8221; For her part, Ms. Quinn said of Mr. Carson, &#8220;He was not an individual who sought to bring our city together.&#8221; Mr. Carson, who died in 2002, was an ex-convict who became a community advocate and antidrug crusader. Some saw him as a community leader, but others saw him as a thug and a bigot. Once asked about charges of being anti-Semitic, he said: &#8220;That&#8217;s absolutely absurd, &#8216;anti-Semitic.&#8217; And so you don&#8217;t ask the question, I&#8217;m antiwhite. Don&#8217;t limit my antis to just one group of people.&#8221; He was convicted in 1974 of kidnapping in a case prosecutors described as a vigilante-style attack that left one person dead and another near death. He was sentenced to seven years in prison. He re-emerged in the 1980s to crusade against drugs and police brutality. &#8220;Sonny Carson got more crack houses closed than the entire Police Department,&#8221; Mr. Barron said during the premeeting rally. In 1990, Mr. Carson led a boycott of Korean-owned delis in black neighborhoods, carrying picket signs that said, &#8220;Don&#8217;t shop with people who don&#8217;t look like us.&#8221; Michael C. Nelson, chairman of the Council&#8217;s Jewish Caucus, recalled the time when Mr. Carson first received national attention as a militant protester during the struggle for community control of public schools. &#8220;Thirty-seven years ago, Sonny Carson walked into my wife&#8217;s classroom and said he didn&#8217;t want any white Jews teaching his children, and he also said he would carve his initials on her chest if she didn&#8217;t leave,&#8221; he said. &#8220;I am voting no.&#8221; has said of Mr. Carson that there is probably no one who less deserves a street named after him. Councilman Albert Vann, a Brooklyn Democrat who introduced the amendment, said that whether you agreed or disagreed with Mr. Carson&#8217;s tactics, the community should have the right to decide whom to name streets after. Community Board 3 of Brooklyn had voted in favor of renaming four blocks of Gates Avenue in Bedford-Stuyvesant to Sonny Abubadika Carson Avenue. Community Board support is required to rename a street, for which Council approval is usually little more than a formality. There were 51 names on the Council&#8217;s list this year, including the actor Jerry Orbach and the modern dance pioneer Alvin Ailey. Next Article in 