 who had been honored by the city in the past and supported by the local African American community. Spectators in the crowded City Hall chambers chanted Whose streets? Our streets. Whose streets? Sonnys streets? and self-determination, but the council voted against adding Sonny Carson Avenue with 15 in favor of the amendment, 25 against and 6 abstaining.  Some councilmembers voiced concerns about the process as they voted no, while others cited allegedly hateful comments by Carson as they emphatically voted no.  By Sydney Beveridge | May 30, 2007, 5:31 pm In a year of special elections, next Tuesday offers another one: Residents of Manhattans East Side will chose a member of the State Assembly to replace , who left the legislature to become Governor Eliot Spitzers environment commissioner. The race has revived the debate over how undemocratic (small d) special elections for the legislature are as select candidates with little to no involvement by rank and file members. The lopsided party edge in many city districts  including this one, where Democrats Republicans three to one &#8212; make the elections little more than a formality. , before the seat was even officially vacant. And hes considered the odds-on favorite. is trying to make a horse race of it. For one thing, the reports, he is pushing to debate Kellner. But Kellner has declined a June 4 debate citing that old standby schedule conflicts. And Camp won the of Citizens Union (whose sister organization, , publishes Gotham Gazette). The groups executive director, Dick Dadey, told the that Camps perceived independence helped him win the support. &#8221;Unlike his opponent, [Camp] didn&#8217;t come out of the political clubs and the current political establishment. He would be a fresh voice,&#8221; Dadey said. But longtime political consultant Joseph Mercurio thinks Camp has an almost insurmountable handicap: George Bush. Unfairly or not, Mercurio , voters will link Camp to Bush and the war. Democ