http://www.azstarnet.com/metro/185325&cid Higher immigration fees loom | www.azstarnet.com Â® Make us your home page Thu, May 31, 2007 Register now, it's free! For more information about the new immigration fee structure, which is effective on July 30, go to: www.uscis.gov. Jr. High School Math Teacher Academy of Math & Science Higher immigration fees loom Tucson, Arizona | Published: 05.30.2007 The cost of becoming a U.S. citizen or legal permanent resident will increase substantially two months from today. The fee hikes â the largest dollar increases since 1985 â become final today in the U.S. government's Federal Register following a mandatory 60-day public comment period that drew criticism from immigration attorneys, immigrants' rights groups and some legislators. In response to more than 3,900 public comments, U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services officials decided to lower a few fees from the original proposal, including green-card renewal for children under 14, and to expand the availability of fee waivers and exemptions, but the rest of the increases remain as proposed. The exceptions announced by the USCIS won't make much of a difference and don't change the fact the fees represent a very steep increase, especially for working-class families, said Tucson immigration attorney Patricia Mejia. "They are just going to have balance it out and figure it out if it's worth it," Mejia said. "I think most will still file and just do away with other things." The final fee structure â which includes increases of more than 100 percent in some categoriesâ goes into effect on July 30 for all applications postmarked or filed on or after that date. "There's going to be a massive surge of people filing before the deadline," Mejia said. "It will be akin to the April 15 deadline for taxes." That surge has already begun. At least 6,129 immigrants submitted citizenship applications in Arizona from January through April, a 49 percent increase from the 4,094 who started the process in the same time period in 2006, figures from Citizenship and Immigration Services show. Nationally, at least 118,600 immigrants took the first step to request citizenship in March, compared to about 74,200 a year before, a 60 percent increase. The increase can be attributed not only to the upcoming fee increases but also to anxiety about a new citizenship test, ongoing immigration reform debate and more efforts nationwide to encourage eligible candidates to apply for citizenship, said Marie Sebrechts, U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services spokeswoman. "We have seen a steady increase in the past year but we can't really tie it to the fees because we have had so many things going on," Sebrechts said. "It's really a combination, it's hard to pin it on one thing." Citizenship officials say the increases are necessary for the fee-based agency â which doesn't receive funding from Congress â to recover its costs and reduce backlogs. The agency established the new fee structure after an eight-month internal review suggested by a 2004 Government Accountability Office report that found that current fees weren't covering costs. The agency expects the increased fees to lead to a 20 percent reduction in average application processing times by the end of fiscal year 2009. It is promising reductions by the end of fiscal year 2008 for people filing to become a legal permanent residents or U.S. citizens, renewing a green card or petitioning for an immigrant worker. An application for citizenship, including biometric encoding, would climb to $675 from $400; an application to become a permanent resident would rise to $1,010 from $395. The latter would be partially offset by the elimination of fees applicants have to pay while waiting for the green cards, officials said. The revisions from the February proposal include: â A 25 percent reduction to the filing fee to become a legal permanent resident for children under 14, which officials say will mean a $360 decrease from what was proposed for a family of two adults and two children filing together. â A one-time free extension of approved orphan petitions for prospective adoptive parents. â The expansion of availability of fee waivers for some cases that arise from asylum or other humanitarian categories, and for certain juvenile immigrants. â The ability for the agency to waive the $80 biometric costs of getting fingerprints, photographs and signatures on an individual basis. Contact Brady McCombs at 573-4213 or bmccombs@azstarnet.com The Associated Press contributed to this report. $1 Sunday delivery - Subscribe to the Arizona Daily Star Letter to the editor â¢ sign up now U of A basketball coverage
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-5&fd=R&url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/N29204105.htm&cid=1116770540&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Reuters AlertNet - US activist Sheehan ends campaign against Iraq war Thu May 31 02:42:10 2007 Central African Republic troubles Georgia, Abkhazia, S. Ossetia Intense tropical cyclone Jaya Severe cyclonic storm Akash South Sudan fragile peace Child danger poll 2006 Diamonds and resource wars Democratic Republic of Congo St Vincent & Grenadines United States of America Take the AlertNet Quiz US activist Sheehan ends campaign against Iraq war 29 May 2007 15:37:59 GMT 29 May 2007 15:37:59 GMT ## for search indexer, do not remove--> WASHINGTON, May 29 (Reuters) - Activist Cindy Sheehan announced she was ending her public campaign against the Iraq war with an angry blast at Democrats, Republicans and "cowardly leaders" who have abandoned U.S. troops indefinitely in Iraq. "This is my resignation letter as the 'face' of the American anti-war movement," Sheehan said in a Memorial Day posting Monday on the Web site Daily Kos. Sheehan became a leading voice against the Iraq conflict after her son, Casey, was killed in combat in 2004. She was a frequent protester in President George W. Bush's adopted hometown of Crawford, Texas. She began visiting Crawford in the summer of 2005 when she wanted to meet with Bush while he was vacationing at his ranch. Bush had met with her after her son died but did not see her again, although he sent two top aides to talk to her. The White House had no comment on Sheehan's announcement. Sheehan said she had reached the conclusion over the Memorial Day holiday that her son "did indeed die for nothing" and was "killed by his own country which is beholden to and run by a war machine that even controls what we think." "Our brave young men and women in Iraq have been abandoned there indefinitely by their cowardly leaders who move them around like pawns on a chessboard of destruction," she wrote. Sheehan criticized Democrats, saying they had turned against her when she tried to hold them to the same standards she held Republicans. And she expressed frustration with an anti-war movement that she said "often puts personal egos above peace and human life." "I am going to take whatever I have left and go home," she wrote. "I am going to go home and be a mother to my surviving children and try to regain some of what I have lost." "Good-bye America ... you are not the country that I love and I finally realized no matter how much I sacrifice, I can't make you be that country unless you want it," she said. "It's up to you now." Democrats have been under increasing pressure from liberal groups to turn the tide against the Iraq war since they took control of Congress this year. news is provided by Zoom to full size map Facts & Figures - Landmine casualties (2004) Nicaragua latest to grab tainted Chinese toothpaste Drug-resistant TB patient hopscotched across Europe Russia, U.S. spar on Kosovo, missile shield US says 2 companies recall tainted feed additives Seven dead in NATO helicopter crash in Afghanistan Catholic Relief Services commends President's call to double PEPFAR funding Source: CRS - USA World Vision Lauds Bush Global AIDS Funding Proposal Source: WV - USA Iraqi refugee children begin education programmes Source: WV MEERO - Cyprus Catholic Relief Services urges Congress to preserve US long-term development food aid initiatives that fight chronic hunger Source: CRS - USA Annual report &#8211; ICRC boosts aid in face of growing conflict and displacement Source: ICRC - Switzerland The International Red Cross helps Australian-Palestinians, who were visiting family in the Nahr al-Bared refugee camp, retrieve their belongings in northern Lebanon May 30, 2007. Jihadists battling the Lebanese army in north Lebanon were either on their way to or from Iraq, Palestinian political sources believe, a sign that the shadow of Sunni militancy there has started to fall over Ar