http://www.newsday.com/news/local/wire/newyork/ny-bc-ny--sonnycarsonstreet0530may30,0,4396904.story%3Fcoll%3Dny-region-apnewyork&cid New York City Council says no to black activist street name honor - Newsday.com New York City News New York City Council says no to black activist street name honor May 30, 2007, 6:01 PM EDT NEW YORK -- A racially charged debate erupted at a City Council meeting on Wednesday over a proposal to name a street after a militant black activist who some celebrate as a community hero but others say was divisive and not deserving of the honor. The argument divided councilmembers and the audience along racial lines and grew so heated that there were numerous calls for order. Afterward, as the crowd dispersed, there were chants of "Whose streets? Our streets!" and "Black power!" Tempers had been simmering since last month, after a measure was introduced to rename a Brooklyn street after Sonny Abubadika Carson, a local leader who once called himself "anti-white." His name was initially part of a package of 51 street renamings, alongside New Yorkers such as actor Jerry Orbach and firefighters killed in the line of duty, but it was stricken from the group last month when objections were raised over his history. Carson, who died in 2002, was an important figure in the city's black community throughout the 1980s. He led protests against police brutality and founded the Black Men's Movement Against Crack, among other things. His autobiography, "The Education of Sonny Carson," was turned into a movie. Carson also served 15 months in prison after his arrest in 1974 on murder, attempted murder and kidnapping charges. He was convicted of the kidnapping charge; prosecutors said he had ordered two shootings as acts of revenge. Mayor Michael Bloomberg and City Council Speaker Christine Quinn were among those who opposed honoring Carson. Quinn said Carson had a long history of being "divisive," and Bloomberg said it was difficult to think of anyone less worthy of the tribute. "We as a City Council have an obligation," Quinn said, "to make sure that when we honor New Yorkers with our vote on street renamings that we do it for individuals who meet the core values of the city of New York, for individuals who were united, not divisive." The 51-member council, which typically rubber-stamps street renaming bills without fanfare, was scheduled to vote on the package Wednesday without Carson's name. But during the meeting, Councilman Al Vann, who is black, proposed an amendment to put Carson back into the bill. The move was defeated by a vote of 25 to 15, with seven abstentions and a few members absent. No black councilmembers voted against the amendment, although some abstained, and just one of the 15 "yes" voters was white. Carson supporters framed the moment not as a decision about an amendment but as a symbol of something larger after decades of racial strife. "A street naming sounds so innocuous, so routine," Vann said. "And yet ... you've hit a nerve, you harken back to a time that we've already overcome _ you're infringing upon our human right." Those pushing for the amendment said the City Council should not have authority to decide who a community can honor. Some said the racial split would last beyond the day. Councilman Charles Barron, who is black, suggested that white councilmembers who voted "no" and have aspirations for future citywide office would "remember this day" when they need black support for their campaigns. "You have divided us more than Sonny Carson ever divided anything," Barron told Quinn, who is white and is among the potential candidates for mayor in 2009. Like all street renamings that reach the council, a community board preapproved the measure that sought to designate a few blocks along Gates Avenue in Bedford-Stuyvesant as Sonny Abubadika Carson Way. Many of the figures honored in the names of the city's streets, parks and squares have questionable pasts that include slave ownership, anti-Semitism and adultery. There was Peter Stuyvesant, director general of New Netherland in the 1600s, who sought to prevent Jews from entering the colony; Revolutionary War general Horatio Gates, who owned slaves, and Austin Corbin, a real-estate developer and owner of the Long Island Rail Road in the late 1880s, who reportedly excluded Jews from his hotels. There is also Al Jolson, an entertainer who appeared in blackface. The question of how to honor historical figures is a familiar one. In the South, for example, there has been debate about streets, schools, parks and government buildings named for slave owners or others with Confederate ties. Alice Bowsher, a Birmingham, Ala., historic preservationist and adviser to the National Trust for Historic Preservation, said it is difficult to imagine any figure passing every test, and she said controversial namesakes can present opportunities for learning and healthy debate. "It's hard to find a perfect person, and if someone has flaws in their life or character, that's not necessarily a reason that something shouldn't be named after them," she said. "All of the Founding Fathers, and plenty of others _ we're all in the same boat of not leading perfect lives." Subscribe to Newsday home delivery Article licensing and reprint options Post a comment |
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.news8austin.com/content/your_news/default.asp%3FArID%3D185072&cid=1116323345&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ News 8 Austin | 24 Hour Local News | LOCAL NEWS Craddick remains in power as session wraps up The house wraps up with Craddick still in the Speaker's chair. The Texas Legislature adjourned Monday night after last-minute budget squabbles and uproarious rebellion against Republican House Speaker Tom Craddick. The Senate adjourned early in the evening, and the House went until the midnight deadline in the 140-day session. The House had a last-ditch round of tense debate over water, border security and electric deregulation. The embattled Craddick finished the session as the man in charge of the House. Opponents from both political parties tried all weekend to oust him from power, with no success. News 8 Austin's Catie Beck takes us to the Capitol during the hectic last day of session. The House yesterday passed bills including mandatory high school steroid testing; required daily physical exercise for middle school students; and strengthened protections for foster children. Lawmakers also approved the stage budget, the one bill they are legally required to pass. Despite some threats in the Senate to filibuster the budget bill, the House and Senate signed off late Sunday night and early Monday on a compromise $153 billion two-year spending plan. It's the state's largest ever. Lawmakers walk out in protest of Speaker Craddick Craddick unwavering as House rebellion continues House resumes business after attempt to oust Speaker Craddick facing coup attempt in Texas House McCall, Hill join race to unseat Craddick Copyright 2007 Associated Press, All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Email this Story to a Friend Stories from the past week --Select An Event Type-- Do you think the United States should drop the trade embargo with Cuba Yes, it's a good market and destination for travelers. Not while it's communist. Maybe after Castro dies. No, there's no reason to let them do business with us. Bikers guide in memorial wall... Schools fill dumpsters with furniture... Wilco officials tour Fort Hood... Austin has Cajun flavor... Republic of Texas Biker Rally... Copyright &copy;2007TWEAN News Channel of Austin, L.P. d.b.a. News 8 Austin
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-0&fd=R&url=http://news.enquirer.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070531/NEWS01/705310396/1077/COL02&cid=1116552892&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ The Enquirer - Good speller makes semifinals Community Press & Recorder &raquo; Good speller makes semifinals Last Updated: 7:01 am | Thursday, May 31, 2007 Good speller makes semifinals - Thirteen-year-old Marissa Shoji makes spelling look easy. As the Symmes Township eighth-grader approached the microphone for the third time Wednesday at the Scripps National Spelling Bee, she clasped her hands and smiled sweetly. It's a wonder that she kept smiling when she heard her word: "circumbendibus," a Latin noun that means a roundabout or indirect way. Marissa took the direct way, spelling the word correctly to earn her spot among the nation's top 59 spellers, They will compete in this morning's semifinals, which will be broadcast live on ESPN. "I was able to piece it together through the roots," she said. Marissa correctly spelled "particular" and aced a 25-question written exam to be among the 107 spellers who advanced to Wednesday's quarterfinals, where she also correctly spelled "inertia." "It's always a little nerve-wracking, but I just try to focus on the word and on the judges," she said. Tony Otten of Erlanger, Ky., also a 13-year-old eighth-grader, spelled his first word correctly - "optimism" - but was eliminated after the morning round because of his score on the challenging written test. &raquo; Good speller makes semifinals Baker ends extradition battle Good speller makes semifinals Sales tax hike approved Ohio 4 Bypass fixup OK'd 'They were good girls and good friends' Lifeguard revives baby at pool 'It is insane that he did this' Anderson tackles sexual predators How did steel beam kill boy? Injured firefighter heading home Bridge shuts down for search Crash closes highway overnight Judge: 'sociopath' deserves 28 years Crash shows teen-driver law isn't being observed Def