http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-5&fd=R&url=http://www.thestamfordtimes.com/stamford_templates/stamford_story/339560931676461.php&cid=1116795329&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ stamford times - News briefs Serving the Town of Stamford, Connecticut Thursday, May 31, 2007 means you can email that writer and we've also added to print the stories and read them later. House votes to legalize medical use of marijuana HARTFORD &#151; The House of Representatives, after six hours of debate that touched on many lawmakers' own experiences with debilitating illness, approved a bill Wednesday that would legalize the medical use of marijuana for certain patients. The bill passed on a 89-58 vote. It moves to the Senate, where a similar bill passed in 2005. That bill then failed in the House. Rep. Toni Boucher, R-Wilton, tried in vain to change the bill. She had filed about 50 amendments, but called only eight. They ranged from requiring the Department of Agriculture to set up a pilot program for medical marijuana patients to providing local police departments with the names of people using the drug for palliative purposes. "This should not be compared with other medications that doctors prescribe," said Boucher, who warned lawmakers they are embarking on "a dangerous direction." She voted against it. Connecticut lawmakers have grappled with the issue for the last five years. Supporters say it's needed to legally protect people who try to obtain the illegal drug to help stem the draining effects of diseases such as cancer and multiple sclerosis. Tribune's deal to sell some papers to Gannett called off CHICAGO &#151; Tribune Co. disclosed Friday afternoon that its earlier agreement to sell two Connecticut newspapers to Gannett Co. for $73 million has been called off in the wake of an unfavorable arbitrator's ruling regarding Gannett's plan not to honor an existing union contract at one of the papers. Tribune announced in March that it had agreed to sell the Advocate in Stamford and the Greenwich Time to Gannett, which is based in McLean, Va. Nearly 40 of the editorial employees at the Advocate are represented by the United Automobile, Aerospace and Agricultural Implement Workers of America union; when Gannett said it did not plan to honor the contract with the unionized reporters and photographers, the workers got a federal judge to temporarily block the sale of the operations, pending an arbitrator's ruling. Last month, the arbitrator ruled that Tribune couldn't sell the company unless the buyer agreed to assume the existing union contract as a condition of the sale. Gannett declined to do so, however, and on Friday the two companies announced the deal had been terminated. Tribune, which is in the process of going private through a heavily leveraged $8.2 billion transaction, said it will "immediately" begin soliciting new offers for the two newspapers. Tribune owns the Chicago Tribune, Los Angeles Times, WGN-Ch. 9 and other media properties. Norwich soldier dies in helicopter crash in Iraq NORWICH &#151; The month of May is ending as the deadliest month of the year for U.S. troops in Iraq. That grim reality hit home for a Norwich family, who learned their son was killed when his helicopter crashed on Memorial day. Army 1st Lt. Keith Heidtman, 24, was the 37th military member with Connecticut ties to die since the war began in 2002. Two Connecticut civilians have also been killed. "It's all a shock to us," said Chris Heidtman, the soldier's uncle. Heidtman was one of 10 U.S. soldiers who died in roadside bombings and the helicopter crash on Monday, the military reported. As of late Tuesday, there were at least 113 U.S. deaths in Iraq so far in May, with two days left in the month. Eight of the soldiers were from Task Force Lightning &#151; six killed when explosions hit near their vehicles and two in a helicopter crash. The military did not say if the helicopter was shot down or had mechanical problems. Heidtman was a 2001 graduate of Norwich Free Academy and a graduate of the University of Connecticut. His parents were notified Tuesday morning. He was the son of Kerry Heidtman and Maureen Robidoux. His stepfather is Art Robidoux. "If you had to pick your son, this is who you would pick. He was handsome, he was bright," Chris Heidtman said. Heidtman arrived in Iraq in December and was scheduled to come home for leave in July. "We're sending our finest, and we're losing them," Chris Heidtman said. Gov. M. Jodi Rell ordered all state and U.S. flags lowered to half staff in Heidtman's honor. "Lt. Heidtman made the ultimate sacrifice for all of us, and he did so to protect the freedom that we so often take for granted," Rell said in a statement. "To have given his life on Memorial Day is especially poignant." Funeral arrangements have not been announced. Mail to a friend
