llion state budget, and decide whether to sign, veto or allow bills to become law without his signature. But he indicated legislators need some time away. "I'm glad legislators are leaving town so that there is time for the wounds to heal," Perry said. The GOP governor had his share of policy scuffles, from lawmakers' decision to overturn his order for girls to be vaccinated against the virus that can cause cervical cancer to disagreements over transportation and budget issues that led to changes in legislation. But those disputes were overshadowed at session's end by a Senate battle over a voter identification bill and the failed, sometimes surreal effort in the House to oust GOP Speaker Tom Craddick that included a Democrat quoting Humpty Dumpty from a Lewis Carroll tale. Despite the interruptions and distractions, lawmakers passed 1,480 bills, according to the Legislative Reference Library, and most still await Perry's decision. Chief among them is the budget, which is needed to fund state government programs from education to prisons to transportation to health care for the needy. Lawmakers delayed completing the plan as they sought to satisfy Perry's call for incentive funding for universities and for a format that would better allow him to exercise his line-item veto power. Perry, while finding its priorities good, contended the budget "continues to erode a governor's constitutional line-item veto authority" and includes some "higher education pork ... added to the budget in the last week of this session." Told of Perry's concerns, Appropriations Chairman Warren Chisum, R-Pampa, said: "I'm glad he wasn't a member of the House. I think he would have voted 'no.'" Chisum said the budget showed restraint, corrected funding deferrals from past years and paid for priorities. As for Perry's movie comparison, Chisum had a different take on what he described as a "crazy, crazy session." "Maybe like 'Spider-Man,'" Chisum said. "There was stuff that happened there we had never seen before." View All Top Jobs View All Top Homes View All Top Vehicles Subscribe to the Express-News today and save for one year! Portions &copy; 2007 KENS 5 and the San Antonio Express-News.
http://www.mercurynews.com/localnewsheadlines/ci_6026690&cid San Jose Mercury News - Giuliani works Peninsula crowd san jose / valley start / stop paper (From the last 24 hours) Prosecutors: Aptos woman lived high life on &#36;1.5 million stolen... ACLU targets planner of so-called CIA torture flights Kawakami: Bryant reveals a tortured soul Spector defense targets forensic errors Rivals Steve Jobs, Bill Gates talk like old pals Giuliani works Peninsula crowd TOUGH TALK : HE ATTACKS CLINTON TAX PLAN Article Launched: 05/31/2007 01:34:05 AM PDT Edwards woos voters at Google Editorial: Presidential candidates should talk about more than our cash Presidential candidates seek support from ethnic networks BURLINGAME - A day after his 63rd birthday, Republican presidential front-runner Rudy Giuliani celebrated Wednesday at a Hyatt fundraiser, but not before blasting Hillary Rodham Clinton, the Democrat leader, for "looking toward the past." "I think the way a Republican should run is toward the future," the former New York City mayor told reporters at the Broadway Grill, where he signed autographs and chatted it up with customers. He criticized Clinton's proposal - which she pitched Tuesday in New Hampshire - to let President Bush's tax cuts for top earners expire. He supports eliminating the estate tax and reducing the capital gains tax. Playing to his audience, Giuliani said higher taxes would mean less venture capital for the high-technology industries that keep the Bay Area's economy afloat. There's "a dramatic difference ... between a philosophy of more government" espoused by Clinton and Democrat Barack Obama and his own support for "lower taxes, less government Giuliani then headed to a birthday-celebration fundraiser, heavy with Silicon Valley venture capitalists and corporate executives, at the Burlingame Hyatt. Tickets cost up to &#36;2,300, with the top price bringing a VIP reception and photo op with the candidate. From there, he was heading to a similar event in Beverly Hills. Nick Bovis, the owner of the downtown Burlingame eatery, presented Giuliani with an autographed photo of New York Yankee legend Joe DiMaggio. "We want you to redecorate the White House," Bovis told him. He signed a copy of the U.S. Constitution for local campaign coordinator Vic Marani, 47, of Santa Cruz, and accepted a &#36;200 campaign contribution check from George Yerby, 67, of Hillsborough; Giuliani quipped it might have been "the first time I think one's been given directly to me." Yerby, who said he's semi-retired from real estate, said Giuliani's policies are "perfect for this area. ... He's going to be the next president." After a slow circuit of the restaurant, Giuliani, with a cup of coffee in hand, took a seat between regulars Mike DeMaria and Nicholas Fleres, both of whom described themselves as "New York Italians." The conversation ranged from the Yankees to California's early primary to immigration policy. On the latter, Giuliani said he doesn't support the plan drawn up by the Senate and Bush, in part because it doesn't include issuing tamper-proof ID cards or require a database of all foreigners entering and leaving the country. Bob Mayer, 56, a self-employed wholesaler from Millbrae, said he supports Giuliani for precisely this reason. "It's not a time to quibble over abortion or to quibble about gay marriage," Mayer said. Immigration, border security and homeland security are paramount, he said. "Everything else is just window-dressing." On the way to his waiting car, Giuliani kissed the forehead of 11-month-old Daniel Caruso of Burlingame, whose mother, Lindsay Caruso, 30, said they had been out for a walk and stopped to see what all the hubbub was about. "I don't know a ton about him at this point," she said of Giuliani. "But I'm interested, definitely, and learning more." Contact Josh Richman at jrichman@angnewspapers.com or (510) 208-6428. The Mercury News is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end o