http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-0&fd=R&url=http://www.star-telegram.com/legislature/story/120647.html&cid=1116323345&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Star-Telegram.com | 05/31/2007 | Democratic ally says he will seek Craddick's post and all of North Texas Find Sales & Deals DFW Find a Home The Flower Mound Messenger DFW Find a Home Posted on Thu, May. 31, 2007 Democratic ally says he will seek Craddick's post By Jay Root and Anna M. Tinsley Democratic ally says he will seek Craddick's post AUSTIN -- Another close ally of embattled House Speaker Tom Craddick, R-Midland, has announced his own bid for the powerful job. And this time it's a Democrat. Rep. Sylvester Turner, D-Houston, was elevated to the No. 2 spot in the House leadership -- speaker pro tempore -- when Craddick came to power in 2003. Turner is one of several members of the Democratic minority who have helped Craddick stay at the helm. But that job got much harder last weekend when a rebellion against Craddick morphed into a full-blown mutiny. And now Turner, after repeatedly defending Craddick's claim to "absolute" power to stop the insurgency, said Wednesday that he wants to be speaker himself and presented himself as a peacemaker. "I don't ever want to have another legislative session like the one just completed," Turner said in a statement. "The people's business took a back seat to political agendas." The 140-day legislative session ended Monday, but a potentially brutal campaign season has just begun. The outcome of state House races could determine whether Craddick will stay in the race to be speaker in 2009 during the next legislative session. Rep. Warren Chisum, chairman of the powerful House budget-writing committee, said he expects Craddick to be active during the 2008 elections and seek early support for another two-year term as speaker. He was unclear beyond that. "He's pretty resilient," said Chisum, R-Pampa, who spoke at a news conference in Mesquite on Wednesday. "I suspect he'll run a tough campaign to be speaker again." But Chisum said he didn't know whether Craddick, who has filed the required paperwork, would actually go through with it. Chisum told reporters that he has not discussed the issue with the speaker. At least five Republicans are running for speaker. Rep. Senfronia Thompson, D-Houston, previously announced a run, but Turner is the first "Craddick D" -- or a Democrat on the speaker's leadership team -- to jump in. Many analysts predict that the bitterness and conflict of the session will lead to electoral upheaval in 2008. Turner did not return phone calls from the Some are already suggesting that his bid may be more about his re-election campaign than a genuine effort to become speaker. Many of the Democrats who joined Craddick's team, including former Rep. Glenn Lewis of Fort Worth, have paid for it with their careers, losing to other Democrats who said they sold out. "It is protectionism," said Rep. Lon Burnam, D-Fort Worth, describing Turner's move. "This is definitely a proactive offense for Sylvester in his district. Many of the 'Craddick D's' will be opposed by real D's." Craddick, the longest-serving member of the Legislature, was chosen as speaker in 2003. That was the year the GOP took the House for the first time since the Civil War era. But after presiding over several years of bruising policy battles and personal conflicts, Craddick, known for iron-fisted rule, drew a challenge from fellow Republicans in January. He prevailed, but the insurgents wouldn't give up. A messy fight turned into a chaotic mutiny last weekend. After Craddick asserted complete authority to remain in power, two top aides quit and more loyalists defected. Yet Craddick was still on his feet when the gavel came down, and now there is talk of punishing the traitors. A new political organization, called We Won't Forget PAC, has been organized for that purpose. Republican Jon Taylor, a political scientist at the University of St. Thomas in Houston, said the Republicans could "easily lose the House" as a result of the bitter infighting. The GOP has an 81-69 majority in the House. Although lawmakers enacted significant reforms, the speaker drama dominated the session, which began in January. Lt. Gov. David Dewhurst, the Republican who presides over the Senate, told Capitol reporters that he and several senators were glued to their laptops, watching streaming video of the shenanigans in the House during the session's final days. He likened the events to a reality TV show "for political junkies." Dewhurst called the political assaults on Craddick "unsettling," but he declined to comment directly on the speaker's handling of the ordeal. Asked whether he, as the Senate's presiding officer, could claim the same absolute power to control who could be recognized to speak, Dewhurst chose his words carefully. "I don't know that you have ever heard me say in three regular [legislative] sessions and four special sessions that I had an unappealable right not to recognize someone," he said. Staff writer John Moritz contributed to this report. Jay Root, 512-476-4294 Anna M. Tinsley, 817-390-7610. About the Real Cities Network About the McClatchy Company Terms of Use & Privacy Statement
