http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-5&fd=R&url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/nation_world/7760017.html&cid=1116803877&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Justice is widening its probe to other hirings | Inquirer | 05/31/2007 &#149; 2007 Live Career Fairs &#149; Philly.com Career Fair &#149; Search new & used &#149; Create a free ad , sports venues and more. See a photo you want? Photos of the day Beach and Bay Homes Active Adult 55+ Housing Thursday, May 31, 2007 Posted on Thu, May. 31, 2007 Justice is widening its probe to other hirings WASHINGTON - An internal Justice Department investigation into the firing of eight federal prosecutors has broadened to examine whether the department used political considerations in hiring career employees for its Civil Rights Division. Glenn Fine, the department&#0039;s inspector general, and H. Marshall Jarrett, head of the Office of Professional Responsibility, told the House and Senate Judiciary Committees in a letter yesterday that the review also would focus on hiring for the department&#0039;s honors program for entry-level attorneys and on summer internships. The expansion followed the May 23 acknowledgment by the department&#0039;s former White House liaison, Monica Goodling, that she had "crossed the line" by inquiring into the party affiliations of people applying for nonpolitical jobs. Fine and Jarrett said they were looking at "allegations regarding Goodling&#0039;s and others&#0039; actions" in hiring and personnel decisions. The Justice Department began investigating in March to assess whether the U.S. attorneys had been fired for improper reasons, such as a way to meddle in cases, and whether department officials had misled Congress when testifying. Both Judiciary Committees are also probing the firings and the White House&#0039;s role in them. On May 2, the Justice Department disclosed that investigators also would probe whether Goodling had relied on improper political considerations in reviewing the applications of people seeking to become assistant U.S. attorneys. Last year&#0039;s firings touched off a political furor over Attorney General Alberto Gonzales&#0039; management of the department and his close ties to President Bush. Many Democrats and several Republicans have called for Gonzales&#0039; ouster, although Bush has repeatedly expressed support for him. Senate Judiciary Chairman Patrick J. Leahy (D., Vt.) said in a statement that he welcomed the expanded review. Goodling, who quit in April, told the House Judiciary Committee under a grant of limited immunity that she sometimes considered lawyers&#0039; political views when reviewing them for positions as immigration judges or assistant U.S. attorneys. Both jobs are covered by civil-service laws barring such assessments. Updated 9:00 AM EDT MOST VIEWED IN THIS SECTION Russian says U.S. renewing arms race Obama offers health-care plan to widen access and cut costs Former senator exploring campaign Cindy Sheehan quits as activist Abdullah the Butcher takes a cut Updated 9:00 AM EDT MOST VIEWED ON PHILLY.COM Time served, deportation for groping on a plane Eagles&#0039; Abiamiri a confident pick Two: Had drinks, woke being raped Stephen A. Smith | Bryant fires back at Lakers N.J., with new agency, steps up fight against fat Updated 9:00 AM EDT MOST EMAILED ON PHILLY.COM N.J., with new agency, steps up fight against fat Monica Yant Kinney | Haddonfield teens going to extremes Boy Bags Hog Said Bigger Than 'Hogzilla' Stephen A. Smith | Bryant fires back at Lakers Teamsters still foaming over ejection by brewer Yuengling Latest Stories in this Section National bee tests spellers&#0039; &#0039;Bewusstseinslage&#0039; Kevorkian to leave prison, but not past, behind Former senator exploring campaign By Michael D. Shear and Dan Balz Marine tells hearing of civilian killings New Orleans stymied on high-rises U.S. to admit more refugees from Iraq Faulty repair, weak rules blamed in plane crash By Michael J. Sniffen Troops l