then the formal U.N. discussions, by solving the biggest impediments to a deal, namely the lack of participation by emerging giants like China, India and Brazil, which aren't covered by Kyoto." Earlier this week, Asian foreign ministers, including those from China and India, expressed support for the European Union's plea for a new treaty by 2009, although " " over emissions standards remain between negotiators from industrialized and developing countries. is expected to make forging a compromise on climate change and emissions standards a major goal on the G-8 agenda. On a trip to Germany this week, House Speaker to keep an open mind on the issue at the summit next week. , head of the White House Council on Environmental Quality, the European Union's suggested emissions target Tuesday, saying the United States supports setting goals, but "has different sets of targets" for specific sectors rather than the blanket requirements proposed by Europe. "Budget Battles" by Stan Collender "Off Message" by William Powers "Off to the Races" by Charlie Cook "Opening Argument" by Stuart Taylor Jr. "PolitiScope" by John Mercurio "Rules of the Game" by Eliza Newlin Carney "Social Studies" by Jonathan Rauch "Wealth of Nations" by Clive Crook Play Of The Day Markup Reports By Committee Polling On Key Issues Polling On National Figures Search The Policy Council About The Policy Council Contact The Policy Council Reprints, Permissions And Back Issues Make NationalJournal.com Your Homepage About National Journal Group Inc. Copyright 2007 by National Journal Group Inc. 600 New Hampshire Avenue, NW, Washington, DC 20037 202-739-8400 &#183; fax 202-833-8069 NationalJournal.com is an Atlantic Media publication.
