http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-2&fd=R&url=http://www.silive.com/news/advance/index.ssf%3F/base/news/118061283048400.xml%26coll%3D1&cid=1116778683&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Racial uproar over naming a city street for radical - SILive.com More From Staten Island Advance Subscribe To Staten Island Advance Racial uproar over naming a city street for radical The City Council rejects tribute to Sonny Carson after a raucous debate Thursday, May 31, 2007 ADVANCE CITY HALL BUREAU Racial tensions reached a fever pitch in the City Council yesterday, during a loud, antagonistic debate over renaming a Brooklyn street after Sonny Abubadika Carson, a black activist regarded both as a key civil rights leader and an anti-white, anti-Semitic provocateur. As Council members took turns speaking on the issue, crowds booed, hissed and cheered, and the meeting was called to order several times. Adding to the drama, Council Speaker Christine Quinn, who is white, was chastised by Councilman Charles Barron, a Brooklyn Democrat and a former Black Panther, for her opposition to the measure. The Council voted down the measure 25-15, with seven abstentions. Staten Island's three-member contingent rejected the Carson street renaming. The tally broke down largely along racial lines, with only one vote to rename the street coming from a white member and all black members either voting for the renaming or abstaining. "This fairly innocuous bill, a street renaming ... sounds so innocuous, so routine, and yet now it's not that," said Councilman Albert Vann, a black Democrat from Bedford-Stuyvesant who spearheaded the measure. "You've hit a nerve. You're harking back to a time that we've already overcome. You're infringing upon our human right." Ms. Quinn, a Democrat, called Carson "divisive" in explaining her "no" vote. "If you look at the life and the full record of who Sonny Carson was, it was divisive. It is a record that is without apology. It is not a record which stood in full support and full solidarity for all New Yorkers of all races and religions," Ms. Quinn said, while the crowd fired jeers of "You didn't know him!" Carson, a Korean War veteran who died in 2002, led protests against police brutality, among other things. He was criticized for calling himself "anti-white," a quote Barron said was taken out of context by the media. Carson was arrested in 1974 on charges of murder, attempted murder and kidnapping -- prosecutors claimed he had ordered the revenge shootings of two men -- and convicted of kidnapping. Sentenced to seven years in prison, he served 15 months and became politically active following his release. Ms. Quinn, who is openly gay and is regarded as having liberal views, was on the end of a harangue by Barron and other black Council members. "You brought us to a place of divide that this City Council has never experienced," Barron said, often pointing a finger at her during his speech and refusing to stop when his two-minute time allotment ended. Car vandals on a rampage Racial uproar over naming a city street for radical MOVIE VET'S OPENING BOW AT FILM FEST Copyright 2007 The Staten Island Advance. Used with permission. Talk News In Our Forums Search for Colleges and Schools Cool Contests and Giveaways The Best Local Classifieds Have The Advance delivered to your home or business. Save 26% off the newsstand price with EZPay. Use of this site constitutes acceptance of our &copy;2007 Staten Island Live LLC. All Rights Reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-5&fd=R&url=http://www.amsterdamnews.com/news/Article/Article.asp%3FNewsID%3D79292%26sID%3D4&cid=1116778683&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Amsterdam News - Article - new york news Part of the BlackPressUSA Network Carson supporters come out in force by LESLIE ANN MURRAY Special to the AmNews A sea of Kente cloth, batik fabrics and natural hair flooded the steps of City Hall, demanding that Sonny Abubadika Carsons name be reassigned on the ballot to be voted as a street name. You cant determine to a people who their heroes are, Reverend Herbert Daughtry shouted from City Hall steps. Wearing a pinstripe suite and a cabana hat, Councilman Albert Vann, who represents District 36 in Bedford Stuyvesant, said renaming parts of Gates Avenue in Brooklyn to Sonny Abubadika Carson Avenue was an issue of self determination for the Black community. This is not just disrespect for Sonny Carson, its disrespect for the struggle of Black people. You are infringing upon our rights, Vann expressed. Supporters of the name change want Gates Avenue from Classon to Marcy Ave. to be renamed Sonny Abubadika Carson Avenue. The news conference was a spirited gospel of community activists, educators and elected officials all demanding in unison that a hero comes in different shades, genders and ideologies. City Council Speaker Christine Quinn withdrew Carsons name from the street naming ballot because she considered him anti-white and divisive. If you are going to sit here and tell me that Gates, Fulton and all of these slave holders and racists [can have a street] you need to shut up, Councilman Charles Barron yelled. Barron said Carson was the least divisive of the people commemorated with streets named after pervious slave owners, and that Carson deserves a street named after him. How many of you would want your life judge by a few words that you might have uttered in anger? Rev. Daughtry preached. No one, and therefore we want our life judged not only on a word but on the totality of everything. This city owes him a debt of gratitude instead of denying him as a hero. Back to Previous Page Email This Story to a Friend Click here for an Copyright 2007 All Rights Reserved :: Legal and Privacy Policy
