http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-1&fd=R&url=http://www.naplesnews.com/news/2007/may/31/lake_o_hits_record_low_today/%3Fbreaking_news&cid=1116758582&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Lake O hits record low today Thursday, May 31, 2007 It took 15 years, but Bonnie Turner achieves her goal See our latest videos See our audio slideshows Lake O hits record low today Thursday, May 31, 2007 Lake Ockeechobee hit a record low of 8.94 feet today. Wednesday, water levels of the second largest freshwater lake in the contiguous United States tied record lows at 8.97 feet, a record previously set during a drought in May 2001. âThere is no joy over this record breaking event,â said Carol Ann Wehle, Executive Director of the South Florida Water Management District in a release. âAs these extreme weather conditions continue, we are focused on the challenges ahead to best protect drinking water supplies, meet agricultural needs and safeguard our natural resources.â Water levels historically have fluctuated by almost ten feet, according to record keeping dating back to 1931. This year, rainfall directly over the lake has been low enough to quality the current drought as a 1-in-100 year event, according to the South Florida Water Management District. Read more about Lake O's low water levels This site does not necessarily agree with comments posted below &#8212; responsibility lies with the relevant reader alone. Read our blog agreement &copy; 2007 Naples Daily News. All rights reserved. Published in Naples, Florida, USA by the E.W. Scripps Co. Send Letters to the Editor Site Help & FAQ Word Puzzles & Games
