ind something they don&#8217;t like. If you want to kill the bill, if you don&#8217;t want to do what&#8217;s right for America, you can pick one little aspect out of it, you can use it to frighten people.&#8221; The president contends that the measure is not amnesty because it requires illegal immigrants to pay fines, learn English and wait for years before they can become permanent legal residents. Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, ranking member of the House Judiciary Committee also objected to Bush&#8217;s &#8220;narrow slice&#8221; comment. &#8220;It doesn&#8217;t matter how you slice it, the Senate amnesty bill is a raw deal for American workers and the rule of law&#8230;according to a law dictionary or common sense, the Senate bill is amnesty,&#8221; he said. May 31, 2007 2:55 AM | According to Robert Rector of the Heritage Foundation the Presidents amnesty program would result in 100 new American voters whom by 80% would vote democrat, bankrupt social security, and END his own republican party. This President has lost his mind. Time to impeach his derelict derriere. He will guard IRAQs borders but now ours. Take a look at what is going on in Venezuela, it is coming to a town near you. By the way are Linda and Hugo Chavez related? May 31, 2007 3:14 AM | This is the right time for a rational and realistic approach to immigration. President Bush and the Senate are on the right path. Commenting is open from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. M-F *HTML not allowed in comments. Your e-mail address View all Top Jobs Subscribe to the Newspaper . By using this site, you accept the terms of our Copyright 2001-2007 Cox Texas Newspapers, L.P. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-5&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/local/317850_bee31.html&cid=1116552892&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Auburn teen comes up dry in bid to win spelling bee Skip ads and navigation Thursday, May 31, 2007 Last updated 8:59 a.m. PT Auburn teen comes up dry in bid to win spelling bee 'Rambla' ends quest in national spelling contest WASHINGTON -- In a competition in which contestants proceed alphabetically by state, Jason Pu's burden in the 80th Scripps National Spelling Bee was to wait. Pu, an eighth-grader from Auburn, was No. 277 of 286 spellers in this year's bee, which forced him to wait on stage for 45 minutes during Round 2 and nearly two hours for round three while others faced the ultimate challenge in spelling. Pu made it to the third round Wednesday but tripped on the word "rambla," which means dry ravine. Pu, who admitted he wasn't familiar with the word, spelled it "rombla." The disappointing end was in direct contrast to his strong and confident performance earlier in the day. Despite waiting for nearly 100 spellers to finish in round two, Pu didn't waste any time when his name was called. He stepped to the microphone. He heard the word, asked for a definition then barely hesitated before correctly spelling "shindig." The success pushed him through to the third round of the nation's premier -- and most difficult -- spelling competition and a step closer to a grand prize of $35,000 cash, a $5,000 scholarship, a $2,500 savings bond and a complete set of reference works. He was in the third round with 106 other spellers, along with much tougher words and immense pressure. All 107 qualified by scoring high enough on a 25-word written test and spelling a word to a large audience. Pu admitted the wait was tough. "It's true. Because you're waiting for your turn and you don't really pay much attention to the other people, and then when it's your turn, you get really nervous," said Pu, who attends Federal Way Public Academy. He was sponsored by the Seattle P-I. In past years, spellers from Washington state have grown apprehensive as they watch competitors spell easy words. The fear, they have said, is that the quota of manageable words will end, leaving them with brutally difficult words. Pu had no such thoughts: "I like to think optimistically." Pu wasn't the only one who breezed through the early rounds only to fall in round three. The round eliminated 13 of the 107 who began. With more free time than expected, Pu said he will watch the bee, go sightseeing in Washington, D.C., and concentrate on one other goal. "I want to convince my sister to start spelling," he said. The oral round was hardly taxing for the top spellers. Tia Thomas, 12, of Coarsegold, Calif., back for her fourth national bee, correctly spelled "flagrant." The audience laughed when pronouncer Jacques Bailly defined "ninety" as "being one more than 89" for 13-year-old Mary Harrington of Vineyard Haven, Mass. Aishwarya Pastapur of Overland Park, Kan., made her feelings known by wearing a T-shirt with the words "mishpelt werds eeritate me." She displayed no irritation whatsoever when correctly spelling "enumerated." Kate Weir, 13, of Christchurch, New Zealand, traveled far to participate, and she must have thought the wait was even longer when she was kept at the microphone while the judges conferred over her Kiwi-accented spelling of "eeriness." Her spelling was eventually declared correct. The bee concludes Thursday night with the champion being crowned during a prime-time broadcast. This report includes information from The Associated Press. P-I Washington correspondent Charles Pope can be reached at 202-263-6461 or What do you think? Webtowns, your guide to Seattle neighborhoods, for more headlines and info from Add P-I Local headlines to Show of hands and more Don't start watching 'The Starter Wife' Read the Great Books by CASA Latina's unlikely ally -- Asian Americans 'Spam King' suspect seized Recent grads offer real-world perspective to Class of 2007 Dying vet planned a final mission Should state pay for divorce lawyer? It's back! The wait for 'the Interurban' is over Three more Stryker soldiers killed in Iraq $32 million deal saves historic church Haq pleads insanity in shootings Auburn teen comes up dry in bid to win spelling bee Schools streamline how math is taught Columbus the exploring bear trapped at Federal Way Washington emergency officials update tsunmi plan Hastings assailed on immigration, Yakima bishop seeks compassion Smoker starts small fire at Harborview Medical Center in Seattle Spokane teenager found dead in Montana likely was strangled Gov. calls for sage grouse summit Powerball winners create foundations to help kids, poor, vets New Hawaii lab plans to send satellites into space in two years Former James Bond helping island school kids Tourism off in April P-I staff on Seattle politics Obama trailing field in key states Joel Connelly: Uncle Ted and the Feds Satterberg named acting King Co. Prosecutor Economy nearly stalled in first quarter TB patient ID'd as Atlanta attorney, 31 N.H. governor signs civil unions law Iraq residents rise up against al-Qaida Putin: U.S. has triggered new arms race Listener helps save ailing disc jockey Wal-Mart cashier: I was fired for joking Promotional fax mistaken for bomb threat Musician canned for focus on wrong organ Couple sue Wal-Mart over slip in vomit New breed of cat retails for $22,000 Dying vet planned a final mission 'Spam King' suspect seized Recent grads offer real-world perspective to Class of 2007 Pre-Draft Notebook: Halperin says 'no' to Sonics Microsoft Surface brings computing to the table Ancestry.com puts 90M war records online New breed of cat retails for $22,000 Where car thieves love to tread Dying vet planned a final mission A city with no Sonics: How life will change if NBA leaves Seattle Viaduct-free plan on the table $6 tolls proposed for new 520 Bridge Where car thieves love to tread Co