http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-4&fd=R&url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/13412144/detail.html&cid=1116552892&ei=jv1eRvLfMoey0AGI75nMDQ Walnut Creek's O'Dorney Advances To Sixth Round - News Story - KTVU San Francisco Make KTVU.com Your Homepage Sign up for E-News Test Your Spelling Ability QUIZ: Test Your Own Spelling Ability Walnut Creek's O'Dorney Advances To Sixth Round POSTED: 8:40 am PDT May 30, 2007 UPDATED: 7:41 am PDT May 31, 2007 Walnut Creek eighth grader Evan O'Dorney entered his second day Thursday at Scripps National Spelling Bee, aiming for a national prime appearance in the event's finals. O'Dorney -- stumped by the word "mirliton" in 2006 -- finished 14th last year and was 17th as a spelling bee rookie in 2005. This year, he has advanced through a written test and four rounds to be one of three California students remaining in the event. In round five, O'Dorney spelled "affiche" correctly. Two other contestants from the Bay Area were out by Wednesday's fourth round. John Doner from San Francisco misspelled "ursigram" to be eliminated in the fourth round while Kyle Rogacion of Salinas did not advance to the third round. O'Dorney told the Contra Costa Times that he wasn't feeling any pressure coming into the bee. "I'm not hoping for anything," he told the paper. "I'm just going to do my best." While O'Dorney wasn't feeling any outward pressure, all eyes were focused on 13-year-old Samir Patel is trying to avoid becoming the Dan Marino of spelling. Samir, a Dallas Cowboys fan from Colleyville, Texas, knows all about Marino's 17-year Hall of Fame career as the Miami Dolphins' quarterback, in which he set records but never won a championship. This week, Samir is one of the favorites to win as he makes his fifth and final appearance in the bee. Samir breezed through "decor" without a hitch. Tia Thomas, 12, of Coarsegold, Calif., back for her fourth national bee, correctly spelled "flagrant." Both advanced to the quarterfinals. "Having come for five years, I'm a lot more prepared than I was the first year," said Samir, who has finished third, 27th, second and 14th. "I'm not as nervous, and I already know sort of the routine, so I'm not so much worried about 'Am I going to be there on time?''Am I going to make a mistake in walking down the stage?'" Aishwarya Pastapur of Overland Park, Kan., made her feelings known by wearing a T-shirt with the words "mishpelt werds eeritate me." She displayed no irritation whatsoever by correctly spelling "enumerated" and advanced to the quarterfinals. Kate Weir, 13, of Christchurch, New Zealand, traveled far to participate, and she must have felt the wait was even longer when she was kept at the microphone while the judges conferred over her Kiwi-accented spelling of "eeriness." Her spelling was eventually replayed over the loudspeakers before it was declared correct. There were a few flubs. Ten-year-old Seher Sethi of Rhinebeck, N.Y., let out a sigh after misspelling "pallbearer." Christian Wilks, 10, of Freeport, Ill., tried to put an "a" and an extra "l" in "felony." During the breaks, the ballroom was vibrant with spellers who have become fast friends during their short time in Washington  and some who have formed a camaraderie over the years. Matthew Evans, a 12-year-old from Albuquerque, N.M., who is also appearing for the fourth time, excitedly compared notes with Tia following the multiple choice test. Matthew said he got 24 correct. The semifinals and finals take place Thursday, with the champion crowned in prime time on ABC for the second consecutive year. The winner receives $35,000 cash, a $5,000 scholarship, a $2,500 savings bond and a complete set of reference works. . The Associated Press contributed to this report. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Name Released Of TB Patient A Denver hospital that specializes in treating tuberculosis gets a patient under federal quarantine. SLIDESHOW: Cathedral Near Lake Merritt Taking Shape SLIDESHOW: Coit Tower's Hidden Wonders Father Says Lohan Hooked On Alcohol And OxyContin Paula Abdul Found Her Purpose on 'Idol' Mother Pleads No Contest To Richmond Baby Abandonment Officials Plan Documentary On Bay Bridge Construction 'Guru Of Ganja' Convicted Of Marijuana Charges Again Resisting Arrest Charges Dropped Against Redwood City Bodybuilder Petaluma Dog Owner Arrested After Child Attacked Porter Raiders Jersey Number Change Too Expensive Giuliani Says California Not Just A Political ATM Georgia Traveler Causes Global TB Scare Man Sentenced To 40-To-Life For SF Slaying Obama: Tax Wealthy To Pay For Health Care Clinton Picks Up LA Mayor's Endorsement Romney Pledges Salary To Charity If Elected McCain Urges Approval Of Immigration Overhaul "Law And Order" Star Set To Shake Up Republican Race Four Defendants Convicted Of Murdering 17-Year-Old In 2003 Suspect Arrested In Oakland Police Officer Shooting Menlo Park Police Warn Of Suspected Prowling Predators Coroner Says Actress' Death Was A Homicide US Supreme Court Rejects 'Night Stalker' Appeal 70-Year-Old Injured In San Francisco Hit-And-Run Petaluma Farmer Discovers Heifer Gunned Down In Pasture War-Protester Sheehan Bows Out Of The Limelight SLIDESHOW: Bike May Be Clue To Oakland Shooting Spears Says She Had "Hit Rock Bottom" Oak Moth Infestation Stripping Santa Cruz Trees Dance Teacher Jailed After New Victims Allege Sexual Assault Lost Whales Apparently Return To Ocean Petaluma Dog Owner Arrested After Child Attacked Mother Pleads No Contest To Richmond Baby Abandonment Police Chase Leads To Fatal 7-Car Pileup Is Your Cholesterol In Check? Millions of Americans you are watching your cholesterol, but how do you make sure you get it right? Get tips on diet, exercise, healthy living and working with your doctor to keep your cholesterol in check. Top Employers For Working Mothers You can have the best of both worlds. Check out which companies do the most to help working mothers