she flew to Panama: "I do not see how closing down an opposition (TV station) literally because they have taken you on and taken on your policies can be seen as anything but anti-democratic," "The unfettered public discussion of ideas is the greatest guarantee for the rule of law and the surest protection against the whims of rulers," she then told OAS officials, singling out Venezuela for its closure of RCTV. Chavez took RCTV off the air on May 27, silencing what had been a major opponent to reforms that have given the leftist leader greater control over the judiciary, the military and the oil sector of the OPEC member. Two days later, he called news channel Globovision -- the last main opposition media in Venezuela although it does not have nationwide coverage -- an enemy of the state and said he would do what was necessary to stop it from inciting violence. &copy; Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. Editors Choice: Best pictures from the last 24 hours. Notes by Napoleon, Churchill found in laundry room Tiananmen Square, 18 years later" /> Tiananmen Square, 18 years later Feeling blue? Study says marriage might cheer you up START News Content Page Tags 'Text' | 'Picture' | 'Slideshow' | 'Video' ie. headline for article ie. headline for article END News Content Page Tags Thousands of revellers take part in one of Bolivia's most important festivals, the Feast of the Lord of Great Power. Iran president sees "countdown" to Israel's end I'm the world's only true democrat, says Putin U.S., NATO call Putin missile remarks unhelpful Iraq Qaeda group says killed captured U.S. troops DUBAI (Reuters) - An al Qaeda-led group in Iraq signaled in a Web video on Monday that it had killed three U.S. soldiers after capturing them last month, showing only pictures of ID cards of two missing U.S. soldiers. Loews in $4 billion deal for Dominion gas assets Paris Hilton begins jail term a day early Strikers have new gripe--no sex Apple says iPhone to go on sale June 29 Watch this week's