http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-2&fd=R&url=http://www.centralvalleybusinesstimes.com/stories/001/%3FID%3D5309&cid=1116945842&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg Central Valley Business Times Letters to the Editor Southwest Airlines plane makes emergency landing June 4, 2007 5:18am &bull; No injuries reported in Oakland incident &bull; Had taken off from Sacramento Investigation into the cause of a landing gear failure on a Southwest Airlines Boeing 737 jet continues Monday as efforts get underway to move the damaged plane from the main runway of Oakland International Airport. Flight 3050 was en route from Sacramento to San Diego on Sunday when the pilot noticed a problem with the nose wheel just after takeoff. The plane was diverted to Oakland where it landed, with the nose wheel collapsing as it touched down. There were no injuries. The 119 passengers and crew evacuated the plane on an inflatable slide. A crane was being brought in from Phoenix to lift the plane off the runway. Because the main runway remains blocked until then, passengers with flights from Oakland International have been told to check with their airlines about any delays. A spokeswoman for Southwest (NYSE: LUV) says the cause of the landing gear failure is not known. Copyright Central Valley Business Times &copy; 2007 Central Valley Business Times is an online unit of BizGnus, Inc. All rights reserved. No content may be reused without written permission.
