http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7007541816&cid AHN | Video Shows ID's Of Two Missing U.S. Soldiers In Iraq | June 4, 2007 global news for the digital world Video Shows ID's Of Two Missing U.S. Soldiers In Iraq June 4, 2007 12:45 p.m. EST Julie Farby - AHN News Writer Baghdad, Iraq (AHN)-The Sunni insurgent group, the Islamic State of Iraq, produced a video on Monday reportedly showing the military identification cards of two missing U.S. soldiers. The video, which was not independently verified, featured a still image of the photo identifications of Spc. Alex R. Jimenez , 25, of Lawrence, Massachusetts, and Pvt. Byron W. Fouty, 19, of Waterford, Michigan, as well as personal items belonging to the two missing soldiers. While the Pentagon spokesman did not confirm the authenticity of the video, a spokesperson did tell the BBC that the ID cards on the video did appear to be genuine. Jimenez and Fouty were seized with Pfc. Joseph J. Anzack Jr., 20, of Torrance, California, following a May 12 ambush south of Baghdad. While the both Jimenez and Fouty's whereabouts remain unknown, on May 23, Anzack's body was found in the Euphrates River, south of Baghdad. While U.S. and Iraqi forces continue their hunt for the missing soldiers, the U.S. government has also offered rewards of up to $200,000 for the safe return of the two men. Copyright © AHN Media Corp - All rights reserved. Redistribution, republication. syndication, rewriting or broadcast is expressly prohibited without the prior written consent of AHN. © 2007 by AHN Media Corp.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-6&fd=R&url=http://www.montereyherald.com/opinion/ci_6056298&cid=1116849505&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg MontereyHerald.com : - Libby debate won't go away Send Us a News Tip (From the last 24 hours) Google maps raise privacy concerns Driver hits utility pole; several injured ROCKIN' & ROLLIN' ON THE ROW Letters to the editor Libby debate won't go away Article Last Updated: 06/04/2007 01:45:30 AM PDT Dick Cheney's former chief of staff, Scooter Libby, convicted of perjury and obstruction of justice in the investigation of CIA agent Valerie Plame Wilson's blown cover, is expected to learn his fate here Tuesday. Federal Judge Reggie B. Walton is scheduled to respond to the recommendation of the special prosecutor, Patrick J. Fitzgerald, that Libby spend from 30 to 37 months in prison. Libby's lawyers have urged the judge to reject jail time on grounds he had done nothing illegal in leaking the identity of the agent. Ever since Libby's conviction, a steady buzz has circulated in political circles about whether President Bush would give a presidential pardon. Doing so would rekindle the long dispute on whether the story of the unmasked CIA agent was a mountain or a mole hill. The mole-hill devotees have argued that Libby was never charged with breaking any national-security law because Wilson's identity was not clearly applicable, and that in Fitzgerald's tenacious pursuit of tangential allegations, the prosecution was politically motivated. Others seeing the case as mountainous have said Libby was the hit man in trying to discredit the CIA employee's husband, former Ambassador Joseph C. Wilson IV, in retaliation for his public questioning of Bush's justifications for invading Iraq. In any event, Libby's false testimony denying he had leaked the agent's identity led Fitzgerald to prolonged and costly efforts to get reporters to testify that Libby had told them about Plame Wilson. The prosecutor has argued that this history warrants the stiff sentence he has recommended for Libby. Somewhat obscured was the White House disclosure in 2003 that the president on his own had declassified CIA information in a National Intelligence Estimate relating to the Wilsons, authorized Cheney to use it and Libby thereupon passed it on reporters. If so, Bush's action was a clear politicization, legal or not, of classified material at the highest level. Bush early in the case told reporters that anyone in the White House involved in leaking classified information would be dealt with. He apparently sidestepped that issue simply by declassifying the agent's status so it could be disclosed by Libby or anyone else. Plame Wilson continues to be embroiled in a dispute with the CIA. On Thursday, she sued the agency in another federal court for refusing to give clearance to a memoir that Simon and Schuster had planned to publish next fall. The CIA's grounds were that, by disclosing her starting date at the CIA, she had breached the agreement required of employees not to make public details of her agency service. Her lawyers have argued that the information was already in the public domain. In any event, the story of the uncovered CIA agent continues to have legs. Either a stiff sentence for Libby from the judge or no jail time at all can be expected to keep it alive, all the more so should Bush intervene with a pardon that would light a match anew to the whole controversy. Jules Witcover's latest book, on the Nixon-Agnew relationship, "Very Strange Bedfellows," has just been published by Public Affairs Press. You can respond to this column at juleswitcoverearthlink.net. sax Libby debate won't go away Listen to what Gore says Letters to the editor Voters looking for basic competency in next president Water the real issue Salinas shines on its own Cringing over Measure C He would have voted no Terms of Use & Privacy Statement MNG Corporate Site Map
