n attack south of Baghdad last month. "As you refuse to hand over the bodies of our killed, we shall not deliver the bodies of your dead," the off-camera speaker said on the video which also showed credit cards and what it said were other belongings of the two soldiers. The U.S. military has said it believed the three had been taken by al Qaeda or others associated with the militant group, after the Islamic State in Iraq group said it was holding the soldiers. The video also showed a group of masked insurgents planning an attack and shaky night footage of what it said was the raid on a U.S. patrol which led to the capture of the three. The insurgent group, formed last year by al Qaeda's wing in Iraq and several smaller Sunni insurgent groups, has claimed responsibility for mass kidnappings and a series of major attacks. news is provided by Zoom to full size map Facts & Figures - Landmine casualties (2004) Nigeria seeks $6.95 bln in new suit against Pfizer Iraq Qaeda group says killed captured U.S. troops Mauritania Islamist suspects were tortured -lawyer Insurgent video shows IDs of missing U.S. soldiers Omega-3 fatty acids reduce blood pressure -study InterAction Statement on President's Renewed AIDS Plan Source: InterAction - USA American Red Cross Promotes Prevention and Control of Tuberculosis Along U.S. - Mexican Border Source: American Red Cross - USA Leader of AJWS Grantee Wins Prestigious Human Rights Award Source: AJWS - USA Catholic Relief Services commends President's call to double PEPFAR funding Source: CRS - USA World Vision U.S. Welcomes President's Global AIDS Funding Proposal Source: WV - USA The U.S. commander in Iraq, General David Petraeus, speaks during an awarding ceremony for helicopter crews in Camp Anaconda, north of Baghdad June 4, 2007. Three U.S. helicopter crews were honoured on Monday for bravery under fire for coming to the aid of a helicopter that was shot down, which killed 12 soldiers in one of the worst crashes of the Iraq war. For