http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-5&fd=R&url=http://www.thenewstribune.com/news/nationworld/story/76714.html&cid=1116817877&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg Cheering costs grads diplomas | TheNewsTribune.com | Tacoma, WA Saves you time. Saves you money. Makes you smarter. The News Tribune, Tacoma, WA - Monday, June 4th, 2007 11:38 AM BLOG: The Prep Blog Wall Street Journal Sunday Letters to the editor BLOG: Inside the Editorial Page Nation & World Photos Bars & night life BLOG: Bring the Noise With the Strykers in Iraq Inside the Editorial Page Online in the South Sound Riding Around the Sound Open House: Real estate Today's full text obituaries Place an In Memoriam Cheering costs grads diplomas JAN DENNIS; The Associated Press Published: June 2nd, 2007 01:00 AM KENT KRIEGSHAUSER/THE (GALESBURG, ILL.) REGISTER-MAIL Caisha Gayles waits with classmates for commencement ceremonies to begin Sunday at Galesburg High School in Galesburg, Ill. Gayles and four other students were denied diplomas after enthusiastic friends or family members cheered for them during commencement. GALESBURG, Ill. &#8211; Caisha Gayles graduated with honors last week, but she still is waiting for her diploma. The reason: the whoops of joy from the audience as she crossed the stage. Gayles was one of five students denied diplomas from the public high school in Galesburg, Ill., after enthusiastic friends or family members cheered for them during commencement. About a month before the May 27 ceremony, Galesburg High students and parents had to sign a contract promising to act in dignified way. Violators were warned they could be denied their diplomas and barred from the after-graduation party. Many schools across the country ask spectators to hold applause and cheers until the end of graduation. But few of them enforce the policy like Galesburg has. &#8220;It was like one of the worst days of my life,&#8221; said Gayles, who had a 3.4 grade-point average and officially graduated, but does not have the keepsake diploma to hang on her wall. &#8220;You walk across the stage and then you can&#8217;t get your diploma because of other people cheering for you. It was devastating, actually.&#8221; School officials in Galesburg, a working-class town of 34,000, said the get-tough policy followed a 2005 ceremony where hoots, hollers and even air horns drowned out much of the ceremony and nearly touched off fights in the audience when the unruly were asked to quiet down. &#8220;Lots of parents complained that they could not hear their own child&#8217;s name called,&#8221; said Joel Estes, Galesburg&#8217;s assistant superintendent. &#8220;And I think that led us to saying we have to do something about this to restore some dignity and honor to the ceremony so that everyone can appreciate it and enjoy it.&#8221; The issue has taken on added controversy with accusations that the students were targeted because of their race: four are black and one is Hispanic. Parents say cheers also erupted for white students, and none of them was denied a diploma. Principal Tom Chiles said administrators who monitored the more than 2,000-seat auditorium reported only disruptions they considered &#8220;significant,&#8221; and all turned in the same five names. School officials said they will hear students and parents out if they appeal. Meanwhile, the school said the five students still can get their diplomas by completing eight hours of public service work, answering phones, sorting books or doing other chores for the district, situated about 150 miles southwest of Chicago. Gayles&#8217; mother said she plans to fight the school board &#8211; in court if necessary &#8211; to get her daughter&#8217;s diploma. The noise &#8220;was like three seconds. It was like, &#8216;Yay,&#8217; and that was it,&#8221; Carolyn Gayles said. Copyright 2007 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed. Mauyak&#8217;s calf heads home to Tacoma Bright idea from area teens could save lives Nisqually members coming home Rental cars could have transponders, too Filing period opens for November vote City plans new attack on algae Banter and the beasts Long political campaigns warp notion of news Do-it-yourself kitchen remodel tests civility More on reinstatement of death penalty for King County murderer Ryan Moore finishes runner-up at the Memorial, but collects $648,000 6-2 record can&#8217;t gauge McLaren&#8217;s loyal friendship UW goes beyond expectations Bullpen gets relief from Feierabend NFL suspends Tank Johnson for 8 games Upon further review, we have it good 6-2 record can&#8217;t gauge McLaren&#8217;s loyal friendship Everywhere Alex Goes, There He Is Longtime Washington High track coach Smith retiring 1950 South State Street, Tacoma, Washington 98405 253-597-8742 Copyright 2007 Tacoma News, Inc. A subsidiary of The McClatchy Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-5&fd=R&url=http://www.sctimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070603/OPINION/106030041/1006/NEWS01&cid=1116869188&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg St. Cloud Times | Opinion More discussion needed to reach middle ground in abortion debate Published: June 03. 2007 12:30AM Another battle in the endless war about abortion rights recently concluded with the U.S. Supreme Court's judgment regarding Gonzales v. Carhart. The ruling held a federal ban on so-called "partial-birth abortion" as constitutional unless this procedure was essential to preserve a woman's life. Activists in the pro-life camp regarded the decision as a victory, one of the few enjoyed by abortion foes since 1973 when Roe v. Wade held laws allowing abortion do not violate the Constitution. Unfortunately, the rhetoric and political posturing surrounding "partial-birth abortion" have done little to further a meaningful discussion regarding the place of abortion in our society. The term "partial-birth abortion" was crafted by pro-life advocates as an evocative description of a procedure otherwise known as dilation and extraction, used to terminate pregnancies in the late second and third trimesters. The Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003 claimed "factual findings" established a "moral, medical and ethical consensus" that "D&X" was a "gruesome and inhuman procedure." Speaking as a doctor, the aforementioned "consensus" is fabrication. Space constraints prevent vivid descriptions of D&X and an alternative procedure still regarded as legal, dilation and evacuation, D&E. Either procedure can qualify as "gruesome" with D&E offering more potential risk to the mother. Truth be told, the debate between the relative merits of D&E versus D&X has little to do with the underlying purpose of the Partial Birth Abortion Ban. This legislation and similar efforts, such as the Unborn Child Pain Awareness Act, are components of the long-range strategy created by abortion opponents to ultimately overturn Roe v. Wade and allow individual states to determine the legality of abortion within their borders. Abortion supporters fully understand the intent of their adversaries. Given the makeup of the Supreme Court and the knowledge that one of its four remaining liberals is 87-year-old Justice John Paul Stevens, their fears regarding the demise of abortion rights may have some justification. Advocates of abortion rights realize a consensus will never be established regarding when a fetus becomes a human being. Horror stories of women dying from illegal septic abortions or unwanted children marginalized by society provoke accusations of moral relativism from abortion foes and are dismissed as irrelevant. The right of "choice" is also ridiculed by conservatives. However, given the traditional place of women in our society and their susceptibility to violence and oppression by males, the argument granting the right of "choice" to terminate a pregnancy inflicted on a woman has merit. Also, one can justify abortion to preserve a woman's health throughout the course of pregnancy. The issue of preserving health may be the most vexing to pro-life activists. Abortion may be performed prior to fetal viability and whenever pregnancy presents a health risk. Abortion opponents argue this latter parameter allows abortion to be "legal at any time, for any reason." It is easy for abortion foes to sound righteous on this issue, but they do not occupy the moral high ground. A substantial number of these individuals are hardly pro-life and exhibit their own brand of moral relativism given their positions on other matters, such as the environment, gun control, government-provided social services, homosexuality and U.S. military activity. Also, many abortion adversaries regard abstinence as the single acceptable method of contraception, a completely unrealistic position that can only foster more unwanted pregnancies. There are two facts regarding abortion in the United States that neither side of the debate wants to consider together. First, the majority of us support use of abortion in some restricted fashion. Second, the United States, as compared with other Western countries such as Finland, France, and Germany, has some of the least restrictive abortion regulations. Rectifying the above realities through frank discussion of the appropriate limits of this procedure would require each camp to appreciate its own fallibilities and drop its all-or-nothing positions. The controversy surrounding the Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act did nothing to promote this discussion. The focal point of the abortion issue, the life of the fetus versus the right of the pregnant woman and her physician to terminate a pregnancy, represents a complex, emotionally charged dilemma that is difficult to solve in a pragmatic fashion. Unfortunately, as each side in the abortion war has some validity to their arguments, our society cannot reach a consensus as to which position is more principled. Given the above, a middle ground has to be established that allows the concerns of each faction to be heard and addressed. Perhaps then, with time, we will discover the most moral solution. This is the opinion of St. Cloud resident Dave Shuster. SUBSCRIBE TO THE TIMES Our view: Legislators end session with mixed report card Times Writers Group: 'Infidel' gives controversial look at Islam Letter: America's tax system helps the rich get richer Letter: Business owners should decide rules on smoking Graduates: Define success for yourselves Special sections and contests Copyright &copy; Users of this site agree to the Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Rights (Terms updated March 2007) .Build 0: 15 ms (Misc) .Build 3: 219 ms (Article) .Build 9: 31 ms (Content) .Build 16: 16 ms (NewsList)
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/03/us/politics/03fred.html&cid Thompson Makes Strong Pitch to Conservative Republicans - New York Times Thompson Makes Strong Pitch to Conservative Republicans Fred D. Thompson in Richmond, Va., Saturday. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: June 3, 2007 RICHMOND, Va., June 2  In a preview of the themes he is likely to emphasize in a presidential campaign, tossed some red meat to here Saturday night, assailing the bill in Congress and warning of a mushroom cloud he said radicals around the world were waiting to see rise over the United States. Skip to next paragraph Excerpts From Fred D. Thompson's Speech in Virginia ( The TV Watch: In Casting for President, Will Actor Rate a Callback? Stir in G.O.P. as Ex-Senator Moves to Run The latest political news from around the nation. But Mr. Thompson spoke in a soft Southern cadence, weaving in his biography as a homespun, small-town lawyer with a belief in basic principles and a desire to bring people together. Mr. Thompson, 64, a former senator from Tennessee, has all but announced that he will be announcing his candidacy for president, probably within several weeks. He filed preliminary papers on Friday that allow him to start raising money and hiring staff. He did not directly address his intentions here Saturday, but he made several allusions about the country needing new leadership and said at one point in his 35-minute speech, Were going to cut some new ground over the next year or so. In a brief interview afterward, he said he was just testing the waters, but added, The waters feel pretty warm, to tell you the truth. Mr. Thompsons appearance at the event, a previously scheduled fund-raising dinner for the Virginia Republican Party, was his first since he and his supporters indicated a few days ago that he was preparing to enter the race. His supporters say he can fill what they see as a void for a true conservative who can also get elected. The speech was both a call to arms and a declaration to conservatives that he is one of them. Mr. Thompson paid homage to Barry Goldwater as his political inspiration. He denounced the so-called death tax. He took a swipe at Democrats for what he said was hanging out a surrender sign in the war in Iraq. Believe it or not, we still have many friends around the world, Mr. Thompson said. But he said those friends needed convincing that this is a battle between the forces of civilization and the forces of evil and weve got to choose sides. He was short on specifics, offering instead a broad conservative approach toward smaller government, lower taxes and a bigger defense budget. It was his views on immigration that brought the diners to their feet with sustained applause. Youve got to secure the border first before you do anything else, he said, adding, This is our home, and we get to decide who comes into our home. Supporters have said Mr. Thompsons plan is to become the plausible alternative to the 10 Republicans who are already running for president but have failed to excite the broad base of conservatives who dominate the partys primaries. At the same time, he wants to appear nonthreatening to general-election voters. The Republican candidates include Senator of Arizona, long a Thompson ally, who helped draw up the immigration bill currently under debate in Congress. Mr. Thompson, who spent eight years in the Senate, took several jabs at Washington, where he still lives. Referring to his acting career, he said he had left the Senate because after eight years in Washington, I longed for the realism and sincerity of Hollywood. More Articles in National &#x00bb; Love the Op-Ed columnists?  Try TimesSelect free for 14-days. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. THE TV WATCH; In Casting for President, Will Actor Rate a Callback? Stir in G.O.