http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-6&fd=R&url=http://www.axcessnews.com/index.php/articles/show/id/11170&cid=1116913869&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg Bomb plot at JFK airport foiled Bomb plot at JFK airport foiled (AXcess News) New York - A bomb plot to destroy JFK airport was foiled after authorities broke up a jihadist terrorist cell planning to blow up a jet fuel pipeline, New York City police commissioner Ray Kelly said in a radio broadcast interview. Kelly said the terrorists were plotting to blow up a 40-mile pipeline that takes fuel from a facility in Linden, New Jersey through Staten Island, Brooklyn and Queens to the JFK airport. Experts appearing on broadcast television said the terrorists plot to destroy the JFK airport by blowing up the pipeline was foiled, but their fantastic vision of the ensuing explosion wiping out everything was more like a science fiction movie than reality, claiming the destruction would have been contained and most of the damage localized. The FBI has arrested three of the suspects in the JFK bomb plot, a fourth is still at large in Guyana. The US Department of Justice for the Eastern District of New York said two of the four suspects included a former member of the parliament of Guyana and a former airport cargo worker at the airport. Russell Defreitas is a former JFK employee who was arrested in Brooklyn. Abdul Kadir served as a member of the Guyanese Parliament and is now in custody in Guyana. Two other men, Kareem Ibrahim of Trinidad, is in custody in Trinidad and will likely be extradited to the U.S. after court hearings. A fourth man, Abdel Nur of Guyana is still being sought by authorities there. Authorities in Trinidad and Tobago say Kadir and Nur are longtime associates of a Trinidadian radical Muslim group, Jamaat al Muslimeen, which launched an unsuccessful rebellion in 1990 that left 24 dead. The United States plans to seek their extradition. Commissioner Kelly said that authorities need to pay closer attention to the Caribbean as an area that needs more focus from counterterrorism officials. The Justice Department said the plot tapped into an international network of Muslim extremists from the United States, Guyana, and Trinidad. A Muslim informant helped U.S. authorities foil the plot. His identity has not been revealed. The four began plotting to blow up JFK airport in January, 2006, according to the criminal complaint. The terrorists were allegedly plotting to destroy buildings, fuel tanks, and fuel pipelines at JFK airport with explosives. JFK handles on average over 1,000 flights daily, approximately half of which are international flights, and handles annually, approximately 45 million passengers and over 1.5 million tons of cargo with an estimated value of $120 billion. The fuel supply for these operations are linked primarily to the Buckeye Pipeline, which distributes fuel and other petroleum products to various sites in Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and Staten Island, Brooklyn, and Queens, New York, among others. In tapped conversations, the ex-JFK employee, Defreitas, was recorded saying, "the attacks would result in the destruction of the whole of Kennedy, that only a few people would survive the attack, and that because of the location of the targeted fuel pipelines, part of Queens would explode." Kadir and Nur were supposedly reaching out to other terrorist organizations in South America and the Caribbean in the hopes of pulling together more support in attacking the United States when authorities swooped in to arrest the members of the terrorist cell. The FBI said that one of the contacts was a senior leader of the Jamaat Al Muslimeen (JAM) terrorist group. Mark J. Mershon, Assistant Director-in-Charge, Federal Bureau of Investigation, New York Field Office, stated, &ldquo;The defendants had the connections to present their terrorist plot to radical groups in South America and the Caribbean." Mershon went on to say, " Kadir and Nur were longtime associates of JAM leaders. Kareem was also preparing to send an emissary overseas to present the plan to extremist networks there when law enforcement stepped in to disrupt it." According to FBI tapes of the defendants, Defreitas exulted over JFK airport's symbolic importance saying, "Anytime you hit Kennedy, it is the most hurtful thing to the United States. If you hit that, this whole country will be in mourning. It's like you can kill the man twice." In a later recorded conversation with his coconspirators in May 2007, Defreitas compared the plot to attack JFK airport to the attacks on the World Trade Center on September 11, 2001, stating, "even the Twin Towers can't touch it," adding that, "this can destroy the economy of America for some time." In discussing the plans, Kadir stressed the goal of causing economic damage and suggested minimizing the killing of innocent men and women. In one conversation, Kadir and Defreitas discussed the need to disable the airport control tower from which airport security monitors the fuel tank locations. Kadir, an engineer by training, explained that the tanks were, most likely, double tanks, requiring two explosions to provide enough oxygen to ignite the fuel inside the inner tank. Kenneth L. Wainstein, Assistant Attorney General for National Security at the Justice Department credited authorities cooperative work in foiling the JFK airport bomb plot to that of the Fort Dixon terrorist plot several weeks ago, saying, "this plot highlights the evolving nature of the terrorist threat we face, and our investigation into both plots highlights how our agents and prosecutors are refining their capability to detect and pre-empt such plots before they advance to a dangerous stage." Roslynn R. Mauskopf said, "Had the plot been carried out, it could have resulted in unfathomable damage, deaths, and destruction." The four terrorists face life behind bars without the possibility of parole if convicted, Mauskopf added. Your text ad here - This could be your ad, find out more about it here. - Email Marketing Software Prom Dresses exclusive Bridesmaid Gown at $49 5oz Pure Silver Bars - The only 5oz silver bar made in America - Get Home Mortgage Quotes - Discount press release service © 2007 NetAct America, Inc. &#8729; All Rights Reserved &#8729;
