http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-2&fd=R&url=http://www.thestar.com/News/article/221294&cid=1116960165&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg TheStar.com - News - Video promised of U.S. soldiers captured in Iraq Full Text Article Archive TheStar.com - News - Video promised of U.S. soldiers captured in Iraq Video promised of U.S. soldiers captured in Iraq Jun 04, 2007 09:29 AM CAIRO, Egypt &ndash; An Islamic militant website said Monday it soon would release video clips showing the capture of a Michigan soldier and two other Americans who disappeared in Iraq in mid-May. The body of a California soldier later was found, but soldiers from Michigan and Massachusetts remain missing. The Washington-based SITE Institute said it had obtained the 10-minute, 41-second video that shows the planning stages and kidnapping operation as well as footage from after the attack. The institute, which monitors militant websites, said the video also shows the identification cards of two of the soldiers. A prominent Islamic website said in a banner headline that it soon would show the video, but it was not yet posted. The three U.S. soldiers were captured west of Baghdad on May 12 in an ambush later claimed by an insurgent umbrella group, the Islamic State of Iraq, which includes Al Qaeda in Iraq. The body of one of the soldiers was found on May 23 in the Euphrates River and later identified by the U.S. military as Pfc. Joseph Anzack Jr., 20, of Torrance, Calif. The two other soldiers &ndash; Spc. Alex R. Jimenez, 25, of Lawrence, Mass., and Pvt. Byron W. Fouty, 19, of Waterford Township, Mich. &ndash; remain missing. The three are from the 10th Mountain Division based out of Fort Drum, N.Y. A Fouty family friend said the military briefed Fouty&#39;s father, Mick Fouty, about the video on Saturday night. &#34;From what I hear, it shows the soldier&#39;s uniforms and dog tags and warns the U.S. to back off on the search,&#34; Cathy Conger said. Byron Fouty lived with her family in Oakland County&#39;s Commerce Township for 14 months before he left for Iraq. &#34;What it does not show one way or another is if they&#39;re alive or not,&#34; Conger said. &#34;I just feel really bad about it. I hope that he&#39;s still alive. My prayers are with him.&#39;&#39; Fouty&#39;s stepfather, Gordon Dibler of Oxford, Mich., said the military told him Saturday that the video showed personal identification items from the soldiers. &#34;They prepared me in a very proper and considerate way,&#34; he told WWJ-AM. Horse, heiress and a hurdle Charities worthy of donations Great home delivery subscription deals here! More in the news A tale of two schools Killed sister in self-defence, accused murderer says Grieving families demand answers McGuinty promises no tax hikes Trump not expected at Black trial: Lawyers Harper talks green ahead of G8 WWF rips U.S., Canada environment records Aviation security suspect, Air India probe told Four guards guilty of beating prisoner MOST POPULAR ON THESTAR.COM Grieving families demand answers Man out of 19-year coma Horoscopes for Monday, June 4 Paris Hilton goes to jail Highrise fall kills toddler Interest sags in nude retreats Man out of 19-year coma Grieving families demand answers Napoleon's love letter found in laundry room What they got: June 2 Careers at the Star Pages of the Past Star Store & Photo Sales &copy; Copyright Toronto Star 1996-2007
