http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-4&fd=R&url=http://www.nola.com/newsflash/louisiana/index.ssf%3F/base/news-32/1180893243132500.xml%26storylist%3Dlouisiana&cid=1116869188&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg Louisiana moves to ban 'partial-birth' abortions - NewsFlash - NOLA.com Louisiana moves to ban 'partial-birth' abortions 6/3/2007, 1:46 p.m. CDT BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) &#151; Louisiana is on track to become the first state to outlaw a rare late-term abortion procedure, following a U.S. Supreme Court ruling that upheld a federal ban. A state Senate committee is expected to debate two bills this week that would ban so-called "partial birth" abortions, a surgical procedure that has become the center of angry debate between pro-choice and anti-abortion forces. Other states are expected to consider similar bans, though Louisiana is the first to take action on legislation. A bill to criminalize the procedure has been introduced in Michigan's Legislature, but lawmakers have not acted on it. Supporters of a ban in Louisiana call the procedure barbaric, and said they hope the Supreme Court's ruling is an indication that the nation's high court is moving toward overturning the 1973 Roe v. Wade ruling that makes abortion legal. Rep. Danny Martiny, R-Kenner, said Louisiana needs a partial-birth ban in addition to the federal ban. "I think it is important for this state, if we believe this is illegal, that we not rely on the federal government, which might have other priorities," said Martiny, chair of the House Criminal Justice Committee. The Louisiana measures appear to have little or no opposition, despite complaints from pro-choice groups who said a state ban is pointless. The House unanimously approved one measure, by Rep. Gary Beard, R-Baton Rouge. That bill and another, by Sen. Ben Nevers, D-Bogalusa, will be debated this week in the Senate's health committee, Nevers said. Anti-abortion activists call the procedure partial-birth abortion and doctors call it "dilation and extraction." It involves partially removing the fetus intact from a woman's uterus, then crushing or cutting its skull to complete the abortion. The procedure is rare, though pro-choice and anti-abortion groups disagree over how often it's performed. According to the Guttmacher Institute, a nonprofit research center on reproductive health, 1.3 million abortions were performed in 2000 nationwide. Of those, 2,200 were partial-birth procedures, the group said. La. House OKs plan to ease insurance rates in hard hit parishes 6/4/2007, 3:59 p.m. CDT Casino owners make storm plans 6/4/2007, 3:55 p.m. CDT Zachary native killed in Iraq 6/4/2007, 3:47 p.m. CDT Copyright 2007 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed. Subscribe to the Times-Picayune &copy; 2007 New OrleansNet LLC. All Rights Reserved. Use of this site constitutes acceptance of our
