n unacceptable increase in homicides or other violent crimes." With the critics hounding Gonzales to resign over the recent firings of U.S. Attorneys, Gonzales told the Associated Press that he would spend his final 18 months of his tenure "in a sprint" to curb the violent crime. As of Sunday, ATF Violent Crime Impact Teams are in 29 cities. The FBI, which has 180 Safe Streets Task Forces all around the country, is sending one to which has been engulfed with gang violence recently. Barbara Jones a spokeswoman for the Department told the Associated Press that the department "welcomes any additional federal support in our efforts to combat violent crime." Justice officials have made it perfectly clear that there are no additional funds or grants are going to be given to communities to bolster their own law enforcement efforts. Gonzales is also hoping for new laws that strengthen the penalties against criminals. He also would like to see a mandatory minimum sentence on federal convicts, the Associated Press reported. Between 2003 and 2006, Justice Department Inspector General Glenn A. Fine's report showed that in 256 cities all across the nation, 210 Justice Department task forces were working. ATF Director Michael J. Sullivan told the Associated Press that each of the Violent Crime Impact Teams cost 1.5 million dollars in personnel, expenses and equipment. He is also hoping that since the recent budget cuts, Sullivan is hoping that with the new teams comes money and bodies. Although violent crime did go up, property crimes such as burglary, car theft and arson dropped. The official FBI data is set to be released Monday, June 4, as reported by the Associated Press. SOURCE : Anti-Crime Teams Sent to Four More Cities - Laura Jakes Jordan - Associated Press More by Jeanne Marie Kerns Violent Crime Spikes in Four Major Cities Peter Gotti's Conviction Upheld Two Children Found Caged Inside of Apartment $200,000 Bond Set for Mother Who Bagged Her Newborn Son Comments - 1 tot