http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-1&fd=R&url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp%3Fedition_id%3D10%26categ_id%3D2%26article_id%3D82699&cid=1116935262&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg The Daily Star - Politics - ElBaradei fears 'crazy' strike on Iran Send to a friend Save to My Web ElBaradei fears 'crazy' strike on Iran Compiled by Daily Star staff Saturday, June 02, 2007 The United Nations nuclear watchdog chief warned on Friday against the "new crazies" advocating military action to halt Iran's nuclear program and said he did not want to see another war like that in Iraq. The scathing attack by Mohamed ElBaradei were swiftly dismissed by US Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice, who accused the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) chief of "muddying the message." "I wake every morning and see 100 Iraqis, innocent civilians, are dying," ElBaradei said in an interview for BBC Radio. "I have no brief other than to make sure we don't go into another war or that we go crazy into killing each other. You do not want to give additional argument to new crazies who say 'let's go and bomb Iran,'" he said in a documentary, excerpts from which were published on the BBC's Web site in advance. He said a nuclear-armed Iran would be terrible but added that the jury was still out as to whether the country even wanted atomic weapons. He warned that one could not "bomb knowledge." Asked who the "new crazies" were, he replied: "Those who have extreme views and say the only solution is to impose your will by force." It was ElBaradei's strongest warning yet against the use of force. To question the value of binding UN resolutions was unacceptable, Rice said, alluding to ElBaradei's remarks. Exploratory talks between the EU's foreign policy chief, Javier Solana, and top Iranian negotiator Ali Larijani on Thursday yielded no breakthrough on the core dispute - Iran's refusal to suspend enrichment as a condition for negotiations. On arrival in Madrid, Rice said: "The only question is: are we getting to a point where the Iranians are prepared to suspend [sensitive nuclear work] so that negotiations can begin?" "I don't see any evidence of it but I frankly haven't had a chance to speak to Javier [Solana] since the talks concluded," she added. But a spokeswoman for Solana said Friday Iran pledged to end years of stonewalling and provide answers on past suspicious activities to the IAEA. "Iran is ready to discuss outstanding questions with the agency which are linked to information access and cooperation with the agency," she said. "This is the first time they made such a serious offer" without preconditions, a UN official told The Associated Press on condition of anonymity. The official said, without elaborating, that Larijani had offered "a short timetable" for providing the answers sought by the IAEA. Rice rebuked ElBaradei after talks in Madrid with Spanish Foreign Minister Miguel Angel Moratinos. "We have a diplomatic choice ... that is only going to succeed if we are absolutely clear with the Iranians, not muddying the message in any way," she said. "If we are absolutely clear that Iran's obligation is to live up to Security Council resolutions that have been passed, that means to suspend their activities on enrichment and reprocessing, that means to enter negotiations on a package of incentives and a civil nuclear program that would be compliant with the international community's demands. "But we aren't going to get to that favorable diplomatic outcome if we muddy the message for the Iranians. The Iranians need to hear it loud and clear. They are hearing it loud and clear from the Security Council," she said. "They are hearing it loud and clear from the international community. I expect them to hear it loud and clear from the IAEA and from its director." Rice, asked whether hawkish Vice President Dick Cheney wanted an attack against Iran, said President George W. Bush had made clear Washington was sticking to a diplomatic course. "But it is a diplomatic course that is backed up by disincentives for Iran to continue its activities." she added. Adding pressure on the Islamic Republic on a different front, Bush on Friday strongly condemned Tehran's detention of American citizens and called for them to be freed "immediately and unconditionally." Tehran has accused dual US-Iranian citizens Haleh Esfandiari, an academic, Kian Tajbakhsh, a social scientist, and Parnaz Azima, a journalist, of espionnage. The State Department said on Thursday that a fourth Iranian-American, California businessman Ali Shakeri had also been detained. "Their presence in Iran - to visit their parents or to conduct humanitarian work - poses no threat," Bush said in a statement. "I strongly condemn their detention at the hands of Iranian authorities. They should be freed immediately and unconditionally," Bush said. Bush also demanded to know the whereabouts of Robert Levinson, a former FBI official who went missing in early March while on a visit to the Iranian island of Kish. - Tags: Bush, Iran, Iraq, Negotiation, Nuclear, Official, Resolution, Tehran, War Send to a friend Save to My Web Your feedback is important to us! We invite all our readers to share with us their views and comments about this article. Click here NOW to Comment on this Article . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 'No negotiations:' Olmert rules out cease-fire deal proposed by Hamas Ahmadinejad: Countdown to Israel's end has begun Turkish artillery hits Kurdish rebel bases in northern Iraq Libyan rights group demands official probe into slaying of journalist Tehran sees 'capacity' to resolve nuclear row Insurgents kill 15 Iraqis in attacks north of Baghdad Iraqi legislator denies mediating in abduction Four dead in Algerian violence tied to rebels Saudis arrest five members of religious police Libya confirms talks on deal over six medics Egyptian textbooks give short shrift to disastrous 1967 war Israeli ministers assail boycott moves in Brita