http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/news/worldnews.html%3Fin_article_id%3D459897%26in_page_id%3D1811&cid Islamic militant Website to release video showing the capture of three American soldiers | the Daily Mail Make us your homepage Islamic militant Website to release video showing the capture of three American soldiers Last updated at 17:25pm on 4th June 2007 City executive who battered 2-year-old daughter was 'stressed' Murder inquiry as police find body of woman who disappeared after date One million could see their mortgage bill soar by up to a third London Olympics new £500,000 logo unveiled - to widespread derision 'Gangsters ran our estate better than the police' More detailed results » City executive who battered 2-year-old daughter was 'stressed' Posh and Cameron Diazs embarrassing fashion double up Madeleine's father and the hardest birthday of his life Revealed: Paris Hilton's glamorous police mugshot JK Rowling and Anna Friel in red carpet frock horror More detailed results » Katie Nicholl's showbiz diary Should Des Browne resign as defence secretary? An Islamic militant Website has said it will soon release video clips showing the capture of three American soldiers who went missing in Iraq in mid-May. The body of one soldier was later found in Iraq's Euphrates River, but the other two remain missing. A family friend of one of the missing soldiers said the U.S. military has briefed the soldier's father about the video, which does not show if the men are alive. The Washington-based SITE Institute, which monitors militant Websites, said it had obtained the 10-minute, 41-second video that shows the planning stages and kidnapping operation as well as footage from after the attack that was shown on the pan-Arab satellite channel Al-Jazeera. The institute said the video also shows the identification cards of the missing soldiers. SITE released a still shot of the identification cards video that also displays the headline: "Bush is the reason of the loss of your POWs" written on the screen above the cards. SITE did not say how it obtained the video. A prominent Islamic Website, which commonly posts videos from militant groups, said in a banner headline that it would show the video within hours, but it was not yet posted. The three U.S. soldiers were captured south of Baghdad on May 12 in an ambush later claimed by an insurgent umbrella group, the Islamic State of Iraq, that includes al-Qaida in Iraq. The body of one of the soldiers was found on May 23 in the Euphrates River and later identified by the U.S. military as Pfc. Joseph Anzack Jr., 20, of Torrance, California. The two other soldiers - Spc. Alex R. Jimenez, 25, of Lawrence, Massachusetts, and Pvt. Byron W. Fouty, 19, of Waterford, Michigan - remain missing. On Sunday, the U.S. military said the search was continuing, with a joint U.S.-Iraqi force conducting what it called Operation Polar Charade near Rushdi Mullah, south of Baghdad. Nineteen suspected militants were detained during the effort, the military said, although it did not give more details about possible links to the missing soldiers. Officials have said many wanted men not connected to the ambush have been rounded up as a side benefit of the search. It said the suspects were taken to a detention facility for further questioning. A family friend of Fouty said the military briefed his father, Mick Fouty, about the video on Saturday night. "From what I hear, it shows the soldier's uniforms and dog tags and warns the U.S. to back off on the search," said Cathy Conger of suburban Detroit. "What it does not show one way or another is if they're alive or not," Conger said. "I just feel really bad about it. I hope that he's still alive. My prayers are with him." Fouty's stepfather, Gordon Dibler of Oxford, Michigan, told a suburban Detroit radio station that the military told him that the video showed personal identification items from the soldiers. "They prepared me in a very proper and considerate way," he told WWJ-AM radio. In Massachusetts, the Jimenez family had not seen the video, said family friend Wendy Luzon, who spoke with Jimenez's father, Ramon "Andy" Jimenez. "He said it was a good sign for the family," Luzon said. The three are from the 10th Mountain Division based out of Fort Drum, New York. No comments have so far been submitted. Why not be the first to send us your thoughts? Your email address will not be published make text area bigger Remember me - this will save you having to type out your name, location and email address when you next leave a comment. Email me a link to these comments. Mail to a friend
