http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-4&fd=R&url=http://www.myfoxkc.com/myfox/pages/News/Detail%3FcontentId%3D3377863%26version%3D2%26locale%3DEN-US%26layoutCode%3DTSTY%26pageId%3D3.1.1&cid=1116484449&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg MyFox Kansas City | Reservist Faces Panel After Anti-War Protest In Uniform MyFox Network --> | Reservist Faces Panel After Anti-War Protest In Uniform Last Edited: Friday, 01 Jun 2007, 10:37 PM CDT Created: Friday, 01 Jun 2007, 10:31 PM CDT What Do You Think? Blog About It! or just enabling jstl so that we can just write ${bean.property} and jsp takes care of the new lines. --> A reserve Marine, on his way to Kansas City, was in the center of a political storm on Friday. Sgt. Adam Kokesh was making his way from D.C. for a hearing Monday questioning his patriotism. Sgt. Kokesh could face charges of misconduct after attending an anti-war protest in uniform. Veterans and military agencies were divided over the whether Kokesh has the right as a reservist to exercise his freedom of speech while in uniform. On March 29 Sgt. Kokesh was told he was being investigated for taking part in an anti-war protest while in uniform. "They asked for a fight on this, were going to give it to them," Sgt. Kokesh said. Sgt. Kokesh served as a Marine in Iraq, and is now a part of the Independent Ready Reserve, or the IRR. "That after having served honorably," Sgt. Kokesh said. "If you're in that IRR on that list and you're only responsibility is to maintain a proper address and you're a civilian, until you are called back then you have at least the rights of every American citizen. No less. No more." The Veterans of Foreign Wars agree. In a response released recently, a VFW spokesperson supported Kokesh by saying, "trying to hush up and punish fellow Americans for exercising the same democratic right we're trying to instill in Iraq is not what we're all about." Some Metro veterans strongly disagree. "He has every right to an opinion but he should have not done it in uniform," Jay Hyde, retired US Airforce, said. Even a veteran who opposes the war in Iraq felt Kokesh stepped out of line. "I wouldn't have in uniform, nor would I have said anything that would have demoralized the services in any way," James Connor, retired US Navy, said. On Monday morning, a marine panel in Kansas City will decide if Kokesh should be dishonorably discharged. , FOX 4 News Email to a friend Executions May Resume in Missouri A federal appeals court on Monday opened the way for Missouri to resume executing condemned inmates, ruling the state's lethal injectio... Al-Qaida Group Claims Captured Troops Were Killed Al-Qaida linked insurgents killed three American soldiers after capturing them last month in Iraq, according to a militant video released Monday that clai... Informant Helped Bust Alleged JFK Plot An informant who helped break up an alleged plot to bomb a fuel pipeline feeding the city's busiest airport was so convincing to the suspec... Missing Liberty Girl Found Taylor Young, missing since Sunday, has been found safe. Police said Taylor went across the street from her home to pick up her iPod, then disappeared. Many pages in this Fox Television Stations, Inc. web site feature links to other sites, some of which are operated by companies unrelated to Fox Television Stations, Inc. Fox Television Stations, Inc. has no control over the content or availability of any linked site. TM and (c) 2007 Fox Television Stations, Inc., and its related entities. All rights reserved. Any reproduction, duplication, or distribution in any form is expressly prohibited Powered by Fox Interactive Media
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-2&fd=R&url=http://www.itv.com/news/index_1d2a7d52fc28703890e3cbf6fc4024ca.html&cid=1116936276&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg ITV News - Presidential hopefuls clash over Iraq Each candidate will be hoping to win back the White House held by the Republican George Bush since January 2001 Presidential hopefuls clash over Iraq 10.57, Mon Jun 4 2007 The eight US Democrats seeking their party&#39;s presidential nomination have clashed over Iraq during a two hour TV debate. Featuring some strong words, Iraq topped the agenda, with other hot topics including Iran&#39;s nuclear ambitions, ending the bloodshed in Darfur, immigration, and health care reform. Each candidate will be hoping to win back the White House held by the Republican George Bush since January 2001. Hilary Clinton, who was criticised by the party for supporting a congressional war resolution in 2002, was attacked for voting, along with Illinois Senator Barack Obama, against an Iraq war funding bill last month that did not include a troop pullout date. North Carolina Senator John Edwards, the Democratic vice presidential nominee in 2004, said the votes by Mrs Clinton and Mr Obama, while the right thing to do, were done too quietly and without firm leadership. Mrs Clinton tried to deflect the attack by blaming President Bush, saying: "This is George Bush&#39;s war," while Obama said he had opposed the war from the outset: "So you&#39;re about four and a half years late on leadership on this issue," Mr Obama responded to Mr Edwards. The front-runners in the battle to win the Democratic nomination were joined by the other contenders: J Biden, Chris Dodd, Mike Gravel, Dennis Kucinich and Bill Richardson. Analysts say that for the lesser-known candidates it is vital that they use the debate to impress voters to overcome their lack of funds and media attention to stay in the election campaign. On Tuesday, New Hampshire will host the ten Republicans seeking their party&#39;s nomination, with many of the issues expected to be the same. May 10: US presidential hopefuls to meet on MySpace Mar 4: Presidential hopefuls hit town Zimmers storm the charts A group of pensioners have outperformed expectations, gliding to 26 in the singles chart with a cover of The Who&#39;s "My Generation". Fire kills father and children A father and his two children have died in a fire at their home in North Tawton, Devon. Boy killed in Komodo dragon attack An eight-year-old boy has been killed by a Komodo dragon in a national park in the east of Indonesia. ITV News wants to recruit &#39;Citizen Correspondents&#39; If you&#39;d like to get involved, and see your opinions feature in our programmes then click here to send us your details. We will contact you directly with more information on how to get your views on air. AOL: Free guide to great food and drink, health, parenting and more. Save Â£20 on our 3 month online plan. Cosmetic Surgery and Treatments Book a free consultation and you could win Â£2,000 worth of cosmetic treatments from Ultralase Aesthetics. Content &copy; ITV Network Limited. All rights reserved. Registered office: 200 Grays Inn Road, London WC1X 8XZ Registered in England number: 603893
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-4&fd=R&url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/03/AR2007060300322.html&cid=1116942406&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg Fred Thompson Edging Toward 2008 Bid - washingtonpost.com Find Bars & Clubs View a Sample and Sign Up Today's Headlines & Columnists Daily Politics News & Analysis Obama Starts Throwing Elbows House Majority Leader Tom DeLay Indicted Fred Thompson Edging Toward 2008 Bid Sunday, June 3, 2007; 1:17 PM RICHMOND, Va. -- Fred Thompson says the country faces different challenges now than it did when he spurned overtures to run for president in 2000, leading him to consider a return to politics. "I think that everybody was kind of sitting back, taking it easy and thinking that, you know, peace and prosperity were going to kind of last forever. I think we know better than that now," the former Tennessee senator told The Associated Press. Actor and former U.S. Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., speaks at a fundraiser in Richmond, Va., Saturday, June 2, 2007. Thompson took the first formal step toward a widely expected bid for the presidency, establishing a preliminary campaign committee on Friday. (AP Photo/Steve Helber) (Steve Helber - AP) In Today's A Section More in Today's Print Edition Save & Share Article "We live in a more dangerous (time of) things that threaten our very existence, things that threaten our peace, things that threaten our economic stability." In an interview Saturday night before speaking to the Virginia GOP, Thompson would not talk in detail about why he believes he might make a good president or what his priorities would be. "I'd do lots of things," he said, declining to elaborate. During his 1994-2002 Senate tenure, he was considered a reliably conservative vote. But he had few significant legislative achievements and established a reputation as a less-than-hard worker. "That's one rap that you can cure," Thompson said. When pressed, he struggled to name his greatest accomplishment in the Senate. He said he managed the homeland security bill in the full Senate and added: "There were a lot of things. ... It doesn't always have to do with putting your name on a piece of legislation. There was an awful lot of bad legislation that I helped to stop for one thing." But, he said with a smile, "We'll have a chance to get into all that when I start telling everybody what a wonderful person I am. But we're not quite at that stage." At least not yet. After flirting with a candidacy for months, the former senator and actor known to millions as the tough prosecutor on NBC's "Law & Order" took the first formal step toward the race for the GOP nomination Friday in establishing a preliminary campaign committee. Thompson, however, said he still was not ready to commit to a 2008 campaign. "We've not made a final decision on it. But obviously we're thinking pretty seriously about it," he said. "Everybody who has an opportunity to make even a small difference in the course of the direction of the country has got to look at that very seriously." Thompson Generates Buzz in Richmond Thompson Forms Presidential Committee Wyoming Senator in Serious Condition 2008 Candidates Faking Authenticity? Related Topics & Web Content Top 35 Most Viewed &copy; 2007 The Associated Press Refinance Rates As Low As 2.9% - FREE QUOTES! $300,000 Mortgage for $965&frasl;mo! Refinance & Save $1,000's! Be Prepared. Fight Identity Theft! Equifax.com. $425,000 Loan for only $1,417&frasl;mo. NO SSN REQUIRED! $599,000 Loan for only $1,997&frasl;mo. NO SSN REQUIRED! Cool Gadgets, Great Deals, Visit CircuitCity.com Try Email Marketing with Constant Contact dell_ran = Math.floor(Math.random() * 1000000); document.write(' The Washington Post Store The Washington Post Company: Information and Other Post Co. Websites 1996- The Washington Post Company User Agreement and Privacy Policy
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-2&fd=R&url=http://www.hoinews.com/news/news_story.aspx%3Fid%3D37221&cid=1116817877&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg Galesburg graduate denied diploma : News : HOI 19 Online Your 24/7 source for everything in the Heart of Illinois. Galesburg graduate denied diploma Posted: Sunday, June 03, 2007 at 8:38 PM A rule designed to make a local high school graduation a sacred event has one graduate very upset after she and four others were denied their diplomas when members of the crowd cheered for them as they crossed the stage. Now, one week after what was supposed to be a very happy day, Galesburg High School graduate Caisha Gayles says her graduation turned out to be a nightmare. For most high schoolers graduation day is a culmination of 4 years of hard work and dedication. "It was exciting walking across the stage,"said Gayles. But for honors student Gales what began as a happy occasion became anything but. "There was a little cheering, they said my name, there was some cheering for like 5 seconds but that was it I hadn't even gone over to shake Mr. Chiles' hand or get my diploma at all before it was done," said Gayles. But school officials say those 5 seconds of cheering were enough to withhold her diploma. "It was disrespectful I think to our community," said Assistant Superintendent Joel Estes. After a very rowdy graduation two years ago, Estes explains, the school district adopted a zero tolerance approach to the graduation ceremony- making graduates and their parents sign a behavior contract. "That said they would refrain from these kinds of outbursts and celebrations, that we were going to be in order and it was going to be honorable and dignified so that everyone could hear their name," said Estes. But for Caisha and her mother, that explanation is not enough. "I don't understand why it's a big issue, you know, it wasn't even disrupting the ceremony," said Carolyn Gayles. "I'm not angry at my family at all. I'm glad they cheered for me because its my day, they're proud of me and I'm glad they showed they were proud of me," said Caisha. Now all that's left of what Caisha says should have been the happiest day of her high school career are some withering balloons hanging on her porch- a sad reminder of what she's missing. "All I want is that little piece of paper I want to frame it and put it on my wall," said Caisha. Caisha and the other students can still get their transcripts showing that they graduated- they just don't have the commemorative diploma. School officials are meeting with the students and their families this week to decide if there's a way they can earn back their diplomas. As for Caisha, she's off to college in the fall, she wants to become a teacher. Submit a comment about this story It is stupid for that school to have done that. If my school was to have done that none of us would have got our diplomas. &mdash; ashley helferich, Flanagan How can the Galesburg School District punish the student for something someone in the audience did??? It is sooooo unfair. &mdash; Sheri Owen, Galesburg 12 years of hardwork destroyed by 5 seconds of cheer by OTHERS!!! &mdash; B C, Houston At least on paper... .... this is high-level absurdity! Signing a "conduct contract?" A proud parent spontaneously cheering for honors student daughter? How incredibly ridiculous! This is an example of over zealous educators who are becoming so prevalent in our government-run school system. This could never have happened 25 years ago, and it should not happen now. If there was a problem with excessively disruptive behavior two years ago, this type of atrocity is is NOT the answer. Ridiculous! &mdash; M Stacy, Battle Creek What in the world are we doing to our kids? I think parents of current students should with hold local tax dollars until these young ladies get their diplomas. Maybe if we without a few pay checks from the school board officials they would know how these youngsters feel. &mdash; Adam Clark, Indianapolis Graduation is something to celebrate Graduation day is a day to celebrate. I am very thankful that no one in my family had the misfortune to attend Galesburg schools. That girl earned her diploma and should receive it - with an apology from the school administration. &mdash; Helen Bloom, Edelstein I find it ironic that this student wants to become a teacher. Perhaps she will be able to come back to Galesburg and take the job of some of the staff that made such a ridiculous decision. The outcome of this decision is poor public relations for the school district and ill will toward the district by those effected. &mdash; Steve Marshall, Dunlap What a shame that a school district would deny diplomas for 5 seconds of what didn't seem to be disruptive behavior! We as parents are entitled to cheer for our children when they graduated afterall we have spent 18 years with them helping them to reach this point. You, the educators, at the most, have only spent 12 years with them and in this case only 4 years. As long as it does not get too rowdy why not let the families have a little voice in the ceremony. I don't think it detracts from the dignity of the ceremony at all. School districts are getting to big for their britches in matters like this. Now these kids can't even throw their caps at graduation or have their families cheer for them. What has this world come to when traditions are simply thrown out the window for what some consider dignity? Let us and the students have some fun with what is a long process to get to!! Stop trying to control every person for every little thing they do. It can be done within reason without sacrificing what should be a wonderful tradition!! &mdash; Mary Zehr, Trinidad, CO Local police chief to be recognized Galesburg graduate denied diploma Junction City art fair Legislative session won't end on time Still no state budget One night down, 22 more to go Video causes concern for soldiers
