http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-0&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/01/america/NA-GEN-US-Death-Penalty-Lawsuit.php&cid=1116884007&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg US appeals court declines to review lawsuit over lethal injection - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings US appeals court declines to review lawsuit over lethal injection Published: June 1, 2007 A group of death row inmates on Friday lost another attempt to challenge Ohio&#039;s use of lethal injection when a U.S. appeals court declined to hear a case that has effectively placed their executions on hold. The full 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals let stand, without comment, an earlier ruling by a three-judge panel of the court that said an appeal by one of the inmates was filed too late. Ohio Attorney General Marc Dann said in a statement, "I am pleased with the 6th Circuit Court&#039;s decision today denying Cooey&#039;s request that the full court reconsider the panel&#039;s decision." The lawsuit was filed in 2004 by inmate Richard Cooey, who was sentenced to die for raping and killing two University of Akron students in 1986. The lawsuit, which was later joined by several other inmates, did not seek to reverse Cooey&#039;s conviction or sentence but argued the state&#039;s use of lethal injection is inhumane. The Ohio Public Defender&#039;s office, which represents Cooey, said it will now seek an appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court. Huge setback to Bush&#x27;s military tribunals at Guant&#xE1;namo Efficient adoption system attracts American couples to Ethiopia JFK plot was short on means and smarts "We believe these issues are strong enough to merit the U.S. Supreme Court&#039;s time and attention," said Greg Meyers, the chief counsel to the Ohio Public Defender. If the U.S. Supreme Court allowed a challenge to the statute of limitations in filing appeals, it would open the door to an evidentiary hearing on the merits of the inmates&#039; claim that Ohio&#039;s method of lethal injection is cruel and unusual punishment that amounts to torture. Ohio uses a three-drug cocktail: sodium pentothal, which is a barbiturate; pancuronium bromide, a paralyzing agent; and potassium chloride, which stops the heart. Opponents say the painkiller can wear off after the paralyzing agent is administered but before the heart-stopping agent is administered, leaving a person in pain but unable to let anybody know. Meyers said he was not sure how many inmates would be affected if the 6th Circuit&#039;s latest decision stands. Six judges on the 6th Circuit, many of whom oppose any implementation of the death penalty, took an unusual step Friday and criticized the majority&#039;s decision not to review the case, which they said will result in simultaneous and contradictory proceedings in state and federal court. Also Friday, a federal judge in Columbus, Ohio, delayed the upcoming execution of an inmate who was allowed to join the injection lawsuit earlier this year. Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile shield proceeds Inmates say Paris Hilton is in for a stay in &#39;hell&#39; Commanders say push in Baghdad is short of goal U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; Corruption in China: The anger boils over Chinese drug commissioner is sentenced to death Understanding and coping with tremors An escapee tells of life and death in North Korea&#39;s labor camps Malaysia rejects Muslim convert&#39;s bid to be recognized as Christian A rare glimpse of 19th-century Iran With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Genes take charge, and diets fall by the wayside U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Tracing a poison&#39;s global path back to China Jet lag: How to make the best of a bad situation Do not neglect culture In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy The assault on Assyrian Christians No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; IHT.com on the go Listen to IHT articles on your computer, and create custom podcasts for your portable music player. Today's Page One in Europe Today's Page One in Asia Advertise with the IHT Copyright &#169; 2007 the International Herald Tribune All rights reserved
