 enemy combatants" could be tried in the Guantanamo tribunals. Brownback said Khadr did not meet that strict definition because there had been no formal proceeding designating him as unlawful. Because none of the 380 foreign captives held at Guantanamo have been designated in that way, lawyers said they could not be tried unless they first faced proceedings reclassifying them as unlawful enemy combatants. Brownback dismissed the charges against Khadr, but left open the possibility that charges could be re-filed if Khadr went back before a review board and was formally reclassified. This was the latest setback for the Bush government's efforts to put the Guantanamo detainees through some form of judicial process. It was forced to rewrite the rules last year after the U.S. Supreme Court deemed the old tribunals illegal. &copy; Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. Editors Choice: Best pictures from the last 24 hours. Notes by Napoleon, Churchill found in laundry room Tiananmen Square, 18 years later" /> Tiananmen Square, 18 years later Feeling blue? Study says marriage might cheer you up START News Content Page Tags 'Text' | 'Picture' | 'Slideshow' | 'Video' ie. headline for article ie. headline for article END News Content Page Tags Thousands of revellers take part in one of Bolivia's most important festivals, the Feast of the Lord of Great Power. Iran president sees "countdown" to Israel's end I'm the world's only true democrat, says Putin U.S., NATO call Putin missile remarks unhelpful Taylor boycotts war crimes trial THE HAGUE (Reuters) - Former Liberian President Charles Taylor boycotted the start of his war crimes trial on Monday, saying he would not get a fair hearing at the U.N.- backed court where he is accused of atrocities in Sierra Leone. Loews in $4 billion deal for Dominion gas assets Paris Hilton begins jail term a day early Strikers have new gripe--no sex Apple says iPhone to go on sale June 29 Watch this week's video shows Covering the hottest new gadget