clear program is for peaceful purposes only. Comment on the story Copyright by People's Daily Online, all rights reserved
http://www.jta.org/cgi-bin/iowa/breaking/102215.html&cid Guantanamo compared to 'era of Hitler' " alt="mail" name="mail_icon_white" id="mail_icon_white" > Venezuela's foreign minister called the U.S. detention center in Guantanamo Bay a throwback to the "era of Hitler." In a testy exchange Monday between Nicolas Maduro and U.S. Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice at the Organization of American States meeting in Panama City, Rice lambasted Venezuela for closing an opposition-linked television station last month. Maduro responded by accusing the United States of attempting to destabilize the Venezuelan government and violating human rights through its immigration policies and refusal to close the prison at Guantanamo. After Rice rebuked the government of President Hugo Chavez for silencing critics, Maduro again took the floor to make the Hitler remark. "[Guantanamo] is a monstrous thing, comparable only to the era of Hitler, that in this historical epoch there are clandestine prisons with faceless prisoners and nameless prisoners," Maduro said. Rice walked out of the session as Maduro began his response. "There is a confrontation today between the government of the United States and the government of Venezuela that was evident with the discussion in the OAS," the Simon Wiesenthal Center's representative observer, Sergio Widder, said after the exchange. "But this comment and allusion to Hitler is unacceptable, as it trivializes what the Holocaust was." The OAS meeting had been scheduled to discuss energy policy in the region, but has been overshadowed by the conflict between the Bush administration and the Chavez regime, including disputes over press freedom, the release of wanted terrorist Luis Posada Carriles by U.S. authorities and the general clash of power in Latin America. Our free newsletter delivers breaking news & timely, topical information right to your inbox:
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-6&fd=R&url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/storm/content/local_news/epaper/2007/06/02/m1a_BARRY_06021.html&cid=1116778468&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg Storm season right on time with weak but rainy Barry Jose Lambiet's Page Two PDAs & Cell Phones Storm season right on time with weak but rainy Barry Palm Beach Post Staff Writer Saturday, June 02, 2007 As though it were itching for the calendar page to flip, the hurricane season introduced itself to Florida on Friday by way of a swirling, messy mass of rain and wind known as Tropical Storm Barry. One day, one storm and 182 anxious days of the season still to come. Audio and video clips News on PDAs, cellphones Join Bob King's blog Sound off on the forum Everything you need to know to keep yourself safe: Should you stay or go? WPB Storm Expo June 9-10 S. Fla. emergency resources Site map and A-Z guide photos and all of today's Sound off in the forum The formation of Barry just 17 hours into hurricane season was a coincidence - a product in part of warm gulf waters - and not an indicator that conditions will be any riper for hurricanes this year, meteorologists said. Barry is a mixed bag: It threatens to bring dangerous waves, coastal flooding up to 5 feet and rainfall of 3 to 6 inches in the Florida Keys north through southeast Georgia. But it also brings desperately needed rainfall to drought-stricken South Florida and could drop as much as 5 inches in isolated areas. &#34;It&#39;s a weaker tropical storm, on the lower end of the scale,&#34; said Robert Molleda, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service. &#34;However, it needs to be watched and taken seriously.&#34; By Friday night, Barry had dropped between a half-inch and an inch in most areas of Palm Beach County. About 2 to 4 inches are expected by the end of the weekend. Molleda warned South Floridians that heavy downpours could flood some roads and poor-drainage areas. Sustained winds could reach 20 to 25 mph across coastal regions, and scattered thunderstorms could produce higher gusts inland. Sustained winds of 20 mph were expected overnight Friday, with gusts up to 35 mph, meteorologists said. This morning&#39;s weather will look a lot like Friday&#39;s, with rain falling steadily before tapering off in the afternoon. Thunderstorms are still possible Sunday. At 11 p.m., Barry was about 270 miles southwest of Tampa and was moving north-northeast at about 9 mph, with maximum sustained winds near 50 mph. Forecasters expected Barry to turn to the northeast and increase its speed, though no significant change in strength was expected before possible landfall. Forecasters issued a tropical storm warning, meaning tropical storm conditions were expected within 24 hours, for the Gulf Coast from Bonita Beach to Keaton Beach west of Gainesville. A less-severe tropical storm watch, meaning such conditions were expected within 36 hours, was issued from north of Keaton Beach to St. Marks. As Barry evolved, it posed a difficult challenge for hurricane forecasters, who spent much of Friday debating whether to call it a tropical storm or a subtropical storm. A subtropical storm is a meteorological hybrid that produces winds of at least 39 mph but lacks an intense central core and the circular shape of a tropical storm or hurricane. &#34;The big issue is what is this thing?&#39;&#39; forecaster Jack Beven said. &#34;Some storms just don&#39;t fit neatly into the definitions.&#39;&#39; In the end, a burst of activity near Barry&#39;s center compelled Lixion Avila, the lead forecaster on duty, to designate it as a tropical storm. Forecasters have said they expect this hurricane season to be busier than normal, but they stressed that June storms such as Barry are not unusual. The National Weather Service said it expects 13 to 17 tropical storms, with seven to 10 becoming hurricanes and three to five in the strong category. Friday also marked the first of 12 days of tax breaks on hurricane-supply purchases. Molleda said that if people are apathetic at the start of hurricane season, Barry could be a blessing in disguise. &#34;As long as they don&#39;t really get impacted by it, an early storm can be a good thing,&#34; he said. &#34;Perhaps it will motivate them to get ready.&#34; Barry formed more than three weeks after the first named storm of the year, Subtropical Storm Andrea, developed off Florida&#39;s east coast. Andrea skirted the southern Atlantic coast. Rain from Barry won&#39;t bring South Florida close to normal rainfall amounts, but it certainly will help, officials said. &#34;This is a good reprieve,&#34; said Randy Smith, a South Florida Water Management District spokesman. &#34;This will give us a week or so, maybe more, in which people won&#39;t have to water as much.&#34; The rains also could raise Lake Okeechobee&#39;s water level above its current record low, Smith said. How much more rain do we need? &#34;To really alleviate the drought conditions, we&#39;re going to need anywhere from 30 to 40 inches,&#34; said Kim Brabander, a weather service meteorologist. Place An Ad 24/7 ad with color photos Copyright &copy; 2007, The Palm Beach Post. All rights reserved. By using PalmBeachPost.com, you accept the terms of our visitor agreement. Advertise with The Post
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-6&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601087%26sid%3Dav4xn4i8uP78%26refer%3Dhome&cid=1116887572&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg , Jun 04 17:17 , Jun 04 22:17 , Jun 05 06:17 Violent Crime in U.S. Rises for Second Straight Year (Update1) June 4 (Bloomberg) -- Violent crime in the U.S. rose slightly for the second straight year in 2006, while property crime fell, according to a Federal Bureau of Investigation report. Violent crime increased 1.3 percent last year over 2005, with robbery rising 6 percent and murder and non-negligent manslaughter 0.3 percent, the FBI said in its preliminary annual crime report released today. Property crime, which includes motor vehicle thefts and larceny, decreased 2.9 percent. The report may fuel critics of the Bush administration&#39;s crime policies, including many police chiefs and mayors who say the rise in crime is the result of federal funding cuts. Last week, Attorney General Alberto Gonzales proposed new legislation that would increase penalties for some violent crimes and restore mandatory minimum sentences. ``It doesn&#39;t appear that the current data reveal nationwide trends,&#39;&#39; Gonzales said at the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives headquarters in Washington last week. ``Rather, they show local increases in certain communities.&#39;&#39; According to the report, the rise in violent crime was greatest, with a 3.2 percent increase, in cities with populations between 250,000 and 499,999 and between 25,000 to 49,999. Cities with 1 million or more residents had the biggest rise in murders, 6.7 percent. Forcible rapes fell by 1.9 percent and aggravated assaults were down 0.7 percent. Brian Roehrkasse, a Justice Department spokesman, said today&#39;s report ``shows that overall crime remains historically low in America.&#39;&#39; The 1.3 percent rise, he added, ``is still of concern and the reason why the attorney general has acted to expand federal efforts to combat violent crime.&#39;&#39; In 2005, violent crime in the U.S. rose 2.3 percent -- the first increase since 2001. The FBI collected its data from 11,723 law enforcement agencies. The preliminary figures may change slightly when the bureau releases its final annual report in September. To contact the reporter on this story: Robert Schmidt in Washington at Last Updated: June 4, 2007 13:00 EDT U.S. Stocks Rise to Records, Led by Oil Producers; Wal-Mart, XTO Advance Loews, XTO Will Buy Dominion&#39;s Onshore Oil, Gas Business for $6.5 Billion Ritchie Hedge Fund, Facing Losses, Plans Bankruptcy for Insurance Holdings
