 countered Estes&#39; argument. Says Mixon: "I mean if they would have went crazy and really had air horns and people would have kept screamin&#39; and delayed the process then that&#39;s a just punishment but that didn&#39;t happen." Estes admits, "The kids are truly in the middle and we are looking at ways to try to help identify who were the people that caused the disruption." The five grads were also barred from a class-wide post-graduation party -- and didn&#39;t take any pictures that day -- they were all crying. "I guess we&#39;ll never get that memory back," Nadia mulled. Her mom insists there will be a fight. "I&#39;m going to talk to a lawyer if I have to, I&#39;m gonna fight to get my baby her diploma. I can&#39;t get her graduation party back but I&#39;m gonna get her diploma." How or if they&#39;ll get their diplomas was still under discussion. Copyright (c) 1998- 2007 Nexstar Broadcasting, Inc. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-2&fd=R&url=http://www.stltoday.com/stltoday/news/stories.nsf/missouristatenews/story/4C7581E0941F623C862572EE001D0B3E%3FOpenDocument&cid=1116884007&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg STLtoday - News - Missouri State News St. Louis Post-Dispatch | Suburban Journals | St. Louis Best Bridal MONDAY | JUNE 4, 2007 #1 ST. LOUIS WEB SITE ST. LOUIS CITY / COUNTY NEWS OF THE WEIRD ST. LOUIS' BEST BRIDAL MAPS & YELLOW PAGES Appeals court judge to retire, return to private practice &#8212; A state appeals court judge said Friday that he was leaving the bench to return to private legal practice. Judge Edwin H. Smith has been on the Missouri Court of Appeals' Western District since being appointed by Democratic Gov. Mel Carnahan in October 1995. He was its chief judge from July 2004 through June 2006. "He is experienced and is know- ledgeable in almost every aspect of the law, making him invaluable to our court," Judge Victor C. Howard, current chief judge of that court, said in a written statement on Smith's retirement. Smith will retire July 6. He is leaving to be a partner in the Shughart Thomson and Kilroy law firm, practicing corporate law in the firm's St. Joseph office. Howard said Smith was years away from required retirement, but he said his departure was an example of how hard it was to keep judges on the bench rather than pursuing more lucrative work in the private sector. "We in the judiciary are resigned to the fact that at the present levels of compensation, it will become increasingly more difficult to retain judges with Judge Smith's credentials," he said. Previously, Smith was presiding judge of the circuit court that covers Andrew and Buchanan counties. In November 1978, at age 26, Smith was elected probate and magistrate judge of Andrew County, becoming one of the youngest judges elected in Missouri. E-mail this story to a friend 3 O'Clock Stir e-mail alerts. Details here. Get RSS Feeds of STLtoday.com headlines. Subscribe 