ife didn't measure up anymore," by the patient's own standards and choice. Kevorkian contended that even with only Oregon having an assisted suicide law on the books, "Doctors now are sneaking around and doing it." "There's where the law creates immorality in medicine," Kevorkian said. "Any ... medical act should never be done in an atmosphere of fear and concern and secrecy." Kevorkian thwarted four attempts by prosecutors to convict him and flouted a Michigan ban on assisted suicide aimed at him. State regulators revoked his medical license in 1991. As to his own health, Kevorkian, 79, said he is "just fair ... That liver disease is a fright ... it concerns me." But, he insisted, he is "content" with his life now. "I'm doing what I think is important." &copy; Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. FBI hunts down "24" pirate Editors Choice: Best pictures from the last 24 hours. Notes by Napoleon, Churchill found in laundry room Tiananmen Square, 18 years later" /> Tiananmen Square, 18 years later Feeling blue? Study says marriage might cheer you up START News Content Page Tags 'Text' | 'Picture' | 'Slideshow' | 'Video' ie. headline for article ie. headline for article END News Content Page Tags Thousands of revellers take part in one of Bolivia's most important festivals, the Feast of the Lord of Great Power. Iran president sees "countdown" to Israel's end I'm the world's only true democrat, says Putin U.S., NATO call Putin missile remarks unhelpful Democratic congressman indicted in bribery probe WASHINGTON (Reuters) - U.S. Democratic Rep. William Jefferson was indicted on Monday on 16 criminal counts for conspiring to solicit bribes and pay off a Nigerian official, with $90,000 of an intended bribe found hidden in his home freezer wrapped in aluminum foil. Loews in $4 billion deal for Dominion gas assets Paris Hilton begins jail term a day early Strikers have new gripe--no sex Apple says iPhone to go on sale June 29 Watch this week's video shows Covering the hottest 