http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-2&fd=R&url=http://www.news-record.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070604/NEWSREC0101/70604015&cid=1116887572&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg News-Record.com - Greensboro, North Carolina: News: Violent crime up in 2006 Help & Reader Services New Triad Homes: Your Spring Guide to New Communities !-- style class in dom_shared_leftCol.css -- !-- needed to link to traffic.com with our branding -- !-- START OF TRAFFIC.COM TrafficMagnet -- !-- This code generates a Traffic.com TrafficMagnet. -- !-- Modifying this code may break the Magnet. -- !-- Use of the Traffic.com TrafficMagnet is subject to -- !-- the Terms of Use found at magnet.traffic.com. -- !-- Copyright 2005 Traffic.com, Inc. -- !-- END OF TRAFFIC.COM TrafficMagnet-- --> Monday, June 4, 2007 Violent crime up in 2006 Staff and wire report WASHINGTON &mdash; Violent crime spiked in the Triad in 2006, reflecting a national trend shown in preliminary FBI data released Monday. In Greensboro, like the nation as a whole, violent crime increased 6 percent. The increase was due almost exclusively to reported robberies. FBI data shows the number of local murders remained unchanged. Winston-Salem saw a jump in murders, rapes and robberies. Its number of aggravated assaults declined from 2005 to 2006. The nation's murder rate rose slightly last year but the number of robberies skyrocketed by 6 percent. The statistics were part of an overall 1.3 percent rise in violent crime across the country in 2006 &mdash; the second straight annual increase. However, car thefts, arsons and other property crimes dipped nationally for the second straight year, the data show. The modest increase in murders reflected a mixed bag for cities. The number of homicides in major metropolitan areas &mdash; those with at least 1 million residents &mdash; climbed by 6.7 percent. Smaller cities, meanwhile, saw their murders decrease by a collective 11.9 percent. The spike in robberies marked the highest increase in any category of crime surveyed in the FBI report, which was compiled with data from more than 11,700 law enforcement agencies nationwide. Only the nation's largest cities, including Greensboro and Winston-Salem, had individual statistics released Monday. Statistics for High Point were not published. Nor was the data from local sheriff's offices. A comprehensive report with detailed information from all cities and counties is scheduled for publication in September. Violent crime rose in every region of the country except for the Northeast, the FBI reported. Western states saw the largest jump in violent crime, by 2.8 percent, the data show. The new numbers come amid a Justice Department push to tamp down violent crime with millions of new dollars in funds to local police and a surge of federal agents to troubled cities. Attorney General Alberto Gonzales &mdash; who took office as violent crime started to rise &mdash; has called the crackdown one of his top priorities for the remaining 18 months of his tenure at the Justice Department. In a spot of good news, violent crime grew at a slower pace than initially expected. In December, the FBI projected a 3.7 percent increase for the first six months of 2006. The year before, in 2005, violent crime rose by 2.3 percent. Property crimes decreased overall by 2.9 percent from 2005, the FBI reported. Burglaries, however, rose slightly &mdash; particularly in mid-sized cities, where the rate grew by 3.3 percent. Comment on this article News & Record file Add N&R RSS Feeds News & Record Jobs &copy; 2007 News & Record 200 East Market Street, Greensboro, NC 27401 (336) 373-7000 or (800) 553-6880 .Build 3: 31 ms (Article) .Build 9: 31 ms (Content)
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-5&fd=R&url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/06/04/mccain-takes-on-immigration-critics/&cid=1116922529&ei=h4BkRpOiM5fYqgOt1dGiBg McCain Takes On Immigration Critics - The Caucus - Politics - New York Times Blog Back to front page &raquo; June 4, 2007, 9:35 am McCain Takes On Immigration Critics CORAL GABLES, Fla. â Senator John McCain is about to deliver his full-throated defense of the Senateâs proposal to overhaul the nationâs immigration laws â coupled with some sharp words for presidential rivals like Mitt Romney who oppose the measure â in a speech here to the Greater Miami Chamber of Commerce. The immigration proposal plays a little differently in Florida, a major early state with a large Cuba-American population. The former governor, Jeb Bush, is supporting it (as is his brother George, the president). So the chose the Miami area to mount their most complete defense to date against the many vocal Republicans now opposing the measure. Here are some more excerpts from the speech: âThe politics of Washington have encouraged us to leave solutions to the toughest problems for another unluckier generation of leaders. Problems are left unsolved year after year, because we fear the political consequences of seriously addressing them or value their utility as political attacks in our campaigns. â¦ âTo do nothing now would be an unconscionable abrogation of our responsibilities to defend the security, prosperity and values of our country.â âI welcome any attempt to meet our responsibility to fix our broken borders and immigration system. Our proposal has provoked criticism from some on both the left and right. Compromises usually do. People of good will, who take their responsibilities seriously, argue variously that our ideas are too tough or not tough enough. I do not question the sincerity of their convictions or their purpose in proposing other ways to address the problem. There is one premise most of us agree on: the status quo is unacceptable. âOur borders are unsecured, our laws are being violated, and our current immigration laws do not meet the needs of a growing economy. And while we are argue over the means to solve a problem, we should respect each otherâs intentions.â âThe most difficult problem is what to do about the twelve million or more undocumented workers who live and work here now. No critic of our bill has offered a serious proposal to round up all these millions, many of whom have children born in this country, and ship them back to their countries of origin. There is simply no practical way to do that, and most Americans understand that.â âThose undocumented workers who declare themselves, pass criminal background checks, prove their employment, pay fines, taxes, learn English and study American civics may be offered eventually, and I stress eventually, a path to citizenship. Critics of the bill attack this as amnesty and a special path to citizenship that is denied to lawful immigrants. Both charges are false. â¦ âIllegal immigrants broke our laws and they should pay a penalty for doing so. We impose fines, fees and other requirements as punishment. And if the path to citizenship we offer them is âspecial,â it is because it is harder, longer and more expensive than the path offered to those immigrants who come here legally.â âIt is a hard problem, and I understand that. But the choice is between doing something, imperfect but effective and achievable, and doing nothing. I would hope that any candidate for President would not suggest doing nothing. And I would hope they wouldnât play politics for their own interests if the cost of their ambition was to make this problem even harder to solve. To want the office so badly that you would intentionally make our countryâs problems worse might prove you can read a poll or take a cheap shot, but it hardly demonstrates presidential leadership. â¦ âWe have a chance now to secure our borders and place effective controls on immigration that benefit all of us, and enhance our ability to apprehend terrorists before they strike us. It is a common sense, conservative approach to the problem. Is any office worth sacrificing the progress we can make now to solve this crisis? â¦ âI make one pledge to you that I will keep no matter what. I will never conduct my campaign in such a way that it makes our countryâs most difficult challenges harder to solve. I hope you will hold all candidates to that same standard. Pandering for votes on this issue, while offering no solution to the problem, amounts to doing nothing. And doing nothing is silent amnesty.â âWe canât leave our borders so undefended that people who come here to hurt us can enter it as easily as someone following a dream of living in a great country. But these people are also Godâs children, who wanted simply to be Americans, and we cannot forget the humanity God commands of us as we seek a remedy to this problem. â¦ âWe have a chance this year to prevent such terrible tragedies from occurring in the numbers they have occurred in the past. Letâs do it. For the sake of security, justice, prosperity and humanity, let us do it. â 29 comments so far... Yeah sure, God commands that we and our livestock become the only species of animal life on the whole planet too, according to the seers of divine intentions. â Posted by Steve Bolger The problem that even reasonable people have with the current bill is that they know that the government has neither the will nor capacity to implement it or enforce it. The border cannot be sealed. &#8220;Guest workers&#8221; will not go home after two years and we will not find them. One third of the twelve million illegals will not sign up and will stay underground and we will not find them. We will not charge those businesses that defy this bill. Why should we expect this bill to be enforced any better than the last one? â Posted by c. perry There is a lot to mull over in Sen. McCain&#8217;s speech. There are both trenchant observations and election banalities. But it all boils down to one key sentence: &#8220;The choice is between doing something, imperfect but effective and achievable, and doing nothing.&#8221; There is not much doubt that the Immigration Bill is imperfect. One only has to look at the various criticisms ennunciated by the public as well as specialized groups to wonder how well the Bill addresses all the conflicting issues that immigration represents. And the Bill does look increasingly like it may well be achieveable if current news reports are accurate. It certainly has been able to bridge the congressional divide to gain impressive bi-partisan support. But the key word upon which the whole complicated three hundred page Bill really pivots is &#8220;effective&#8221;. Does the Bill actually provide the means and dollars and tools to secure the border, identify most illegals, and provide a way to manage all those illegals so as to provide American business with the labor pool it needs without bankrupting local governmenets and depressing the overall wage scale of American workers? And there is the rub. The Bill&#8217;s very complexity suggests a Rube Goldberg contraption, an example of governmental ineffectiveness born of politcal compromise. And that potential ineffectiveness comes with a potential price tag that is staggering both in dollars and missed opportunities. And I for one am still waiting to hear the arguments supporting that alleged effectiveness. â Posted by Barton Keyes Well now&#8230;&#8230;isn&#8217;t this right out of the McCain playbook? He &#8220;walks&#8221; through an Iraqi marketplace recently, protected by an arsenal of weaponry&#8230;..whereupon, he declared the Iraqi open market as safe as one in Indiana&#8230;..as helicopters loaded with armed military personnel hovered overhead ready to shoot dead anyone who dared aproach him. He really is a v